{"parentUuid":"e5710633-f812-47d7-84d3-a65b557fd323","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Netflix Open Connect CDN live streaming infrastructure 2024 2025 engineering blog"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01LekPgKt8vHkSnBW9MVpd5B","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01JHbgxGT2WnnGWmenzpoPuA","uuid":"3ed78b27-eee4-4d82-8011-3eb7fdaa0bf7","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:15:25.358Z"}
{"parentUuid":"0e81f9dd-e8d0-4221-8ca4-428be89194bc","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JHbgxGT2WnnGWmenzpoPuA","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Netflix Open Connect CDN live streaming infrastructure 2024 2025 engineering blog\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Netflix Live Origin. Xiaomei Liu, Joseph Lynch, Chris Newton | by Netflix Technology Blog | Dec, 2025 | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/netflix-live-origin-41f1b0ad5371\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Details Its Live Streaming Infrastructure and What They Learned While Building It\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamingmediablog.com/2025/07/netflix-live-infrastructure.html\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Tech Stack Explained: CDN (Open Connect), and Microservices\",\"url\":\"https://www.vdocipher.com/blog/netflix-tech-stack-and-architecture/\"},{\"title\":\"From On-Demand to Live : Netflix Streaming to 100 Million Devices in under 1 Minute - InfoQ\",\"url\":\"https://www.infoq.com/news/2025/12/netflix-live-streaming-pipeline/\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Architecture: A Deep Dive into Seamless Global Streaming\",\"url\":\"https://talent500.com/blog/netflix-streaming-architecture-explained/\"},{\"title\":\"Under the hood : Netflix Open Connect – Antho's blog\",\"url\":\"https://www.anthony-balitrand.fr/2024/09/26/under-the-hood-netflix-open-connect/\"},{\"title\":\"Behind the Streams: Building a Reliable Cloud Live Streaming Pipeline for Netflix. Part 2. | by Netflix Technology Blog | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/behind-the-streams-building-a-reliable-cloud-live-streaming-pipeline-for-netflix-part-2-8627c608c967\"},{\"title\":\"⭐Netflix's Livestreaming Disaster- The Engineering Challenge of Streaming at Scale | Ani's Blog\",\"url\":\"https://www.anirudhsathiya.com/blog/Netflix-livestreaming\"},{\"title\":\"Behind the Streams: Three Years Of Live at Netflix. Part 1. | by Netflix Technology Blog | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/behind-the-streams-live-at-netflix-part-1-d23f917c2f40\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Architecture Case Study: How Does the World’s Largest Streamer Build for Scale?\",\"url\":\"https://www.clustox.com/blog/netflix-case-study/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of Netflix's Open Connect CDN and live streaming infrastructure based on the latest engineering blog posts and analyses from 2024–2025:\n\n## Netflix Open Connect CDN & Live Streaming Infrastructure\n\n### Overview of Open Connect\n\nNetflix built Open Connect, its own content delivery network, to optimize video streaming. The CDN uses a two-tier architecture: Storage Appliances located at internet exchange points, holding nearly the entire Netflix catalog, and Edge Appliances placed within ISP networks, caching regionally popular content. Content is delivered via its own CDN (Open Connect), with more than 18,000 servers located near viewers at over 6,000 locations and connected to AWS locations via a dedicated Open Connect backbone network.\n\nNetflix makes it simple for ISPs and IXs to get OCAs, which are offered for free to hosting partners. By placing these appliances within their partners' infrastructures, Netflix minimizes bandwidth consumption across backbone networks while improving streaming quality for end-users — a win-win for both Netflix and the ISPs/IXs.\n\n### The Live Streaming Challenge\n\nNetflix's existing Open Connect CDN infrastructure was tailor-made for processing static content. As noted, Netflix gets its performance from co-locating caches within ISP datacenters, but a live broadcast doesn't work with that model — it fundamentally undermines their entire infrastructure advantage.\n\nWhen Netflix started exploring live streaming, the goal was ambitious: deliver a live experience that could reach as many Netflix-supported devices as possible, and meet or exceed industry standards for quality and latency. However, the path to achieving this was anything but straightforward.\n\n### Live Streaming Architecture\n\nNetflix's live streaming pipeline involves several key components:\n\n1. **Cloud-Based Ingest & Transcoding:** Netflix leverages AWS MediaConnect and AWS MediaLive to acquire feeds in the cloud and transcode them into various video quality levels with bitrates tailored per show. Their cloud-based approach enables dynamic scaling, flexibility in configuration, and seamless integration with their DRM, content management, and content delivery services.\n\n2. **Custom Packager & Live Origin:** Netflix built a custom packager to better integrate with its delivery and playback systems and also built a custom live origin to ensure strict read and write SLAs for live segments. The Live Origin sits at the demarcation point between the cloud live streaming pipelines on its upstream side and the distribution system, Open Connect, on its downstream side, and acts as a broker managing what content makes it out to Open Connect and ultimately to the client devices.\n\n3. **Origin Architecture:** Netflix Live Origin is a multi-tenant microservice operating on EC2 instances within the AWS cloud. The storage abstraction layer features distinct clusters for key-value (KV) read and KV write operations, with the storage layer separating read (EVCache) and write (Cassandra) paths. This comprehensive path isolation facilitates independent cloud scaling of publishing and retrieval, and prevents CDN-facing traffic surges from impacting the performance and reliability of origin publishing.\n\n4. **CDN Delivery for Live:** The live origin architecture directly connects with top-tier Open Connect nodes, which are geographically distributed across several sites. To minimize the load on the origin, only designated nodes per stream rendition at each site are permitted to directly fill from the origin. When the Live project started, Open Connect had become highly optimized for VOD content delivery. Unlike traditional CDNs, Open Connect is more of a distributed origin server — VOD assets are pre-positioned onto carefully selected server machines rather than being filled on demand. Live didn't fit neatly into this \"small object delivery\" model, so they extended the proxy-caching functionality of nginx to address Live-specific needs.\n\n5. **Streaming Format Choices:** Netflix utilizes HTTPS-based live streaming due to its widespread support among devices and compatibility with delivery and encoding systems, bypassing UDP even though it would provide ultra-low latency. They utilize AVC and HEVC video codecs, transcode with multiple quality levels ranging from SD to 4K, and employ a 2-second segment duration to balance compression efficiency, infrastructure load, and latency.\n\n### Tyson vs. Paul Event — A Landmark Moment\n\nDuring the Tyson vs. Paul fight event in 2024, a historic peak of 65 million concurrent streams was observed. This exposed limitations in live content delivery, such as real-time encoding, manifest management, and CDN caching. However, the platform's microservices design ensured that issues with live streaming did not affect on-demand services.\n\n### Rate Limiting & Resilience\n\nThe Netflix Live Origin implemented priority-based rate limiting when the underlying system is under stress. This approach ensures that requests with greater user impact are prioritized to succeed, while requests with lower user impact are allowed to fail during times of stress to protect the streaming infrastructure and are permitted to retry later.\n\n### Real-Time Discovery & Recommendations\n\nTraditional recommendation systems rely on precomputation and caching, which fail for fast-moving live content. Netflix redesigned its infrastructure so live events appear quickly across the UI, even during demand spikes. To keep millions of devices in sync, it uses a two-phase system: prefetching recommendations ahead of time to spread load and broadcasting low-cardinality updates in real time to trigger instant cache updates.\n\n### Testing & Operational Readiness\n\nNetflix builds synthetic load testing capabilities to stress test cloud and CDN systems. They use two approaches, allowing them to generate up to 100K starts-per-second: capturing, modifying, and replaying past Live production traffic, and virtualizing Netflix devices to generate traffic against CDN or Cloud endpoints. They also run automated failure injection, forcing missing or corrupted segments from the encoding pipeline, loss of a cloud region, network drops, or server timeouts.\n\n### Future Plans\n\nTo support the growing number of Live titles and new formats, like FIFA WWC in 2027, Netflix continues building its broadcast and delivery infrastructure and is actively working to further improve the Live experience.\n\n### Key Sources\n\n- **Netflix Tech Blog** (Dec 2025): *Netflix Live Origin* — detailed architecture of the custom origin server\n- **Netflix Tech Blog** (Sep 2025): *Behind the Streams* Parts 1 & 2 — comprehensive series on live streaming pipeline\n- **InfoQ** (Dec 2025): Analysis of Netflix's live streaming to 100 million devices\n- **Streaming Media Blog** (Jul 2025): Summary of Netflix's live infrastructure disclosures\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"758fb09b-ba3e-4e2f-976a-07438a8c69b4","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:16:13.330Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0e81f9dd-e8d0-4221-8ca4-428be89194bc"}
