{"parentUuid":"9b70e969-30f1-41b4-bca4-b46cff1a1ae7","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QRvF3iLHE4CKEeqd4PGJTs","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Netflix Cosmos encoding pipeline AV1 per-title encoding 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"AV1 — Now Powering 30% of Netflix Streaming | by Netflix Technology Blog | Dec, 2025 | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/av1-now-powering-30-of-netflix-streaming-02f592242d80\"},{\"title\":\"Decoding Netflix's AV1 Streams: Here are 10 things I found | KAY SINGH\",\"url\":\"https://singhkays.com/blog/netflix-av1-decode/\"},{\"title\":\"Rebuilding Netflix Video Processing Pipeline with Microservices | Noise\",\"url\":\"https://noise.getoto.net/2024/01/11/rebuilding-netflix-video-processing-pipeline-with-microservices/\"},{\"title\":\"The Making of VES: the Cosmos Microservice for Netflix Video Encoding | Noise\",\"url\":\"https://noise.getoto.net/2024/04/10/the-making-of-ves-the-cosmos-microservice-for-netflix-video-encoding/\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 Open Video Codec Now Powers 30% of Netflix Streaming | TV Tech\",\"url\":\"https://www.tvtechnology.com/news/av1-open-video-codec-now-powers-30-percent-of-netflix-streaming\"},{\"title\":\"Rebuilding Netflix Video Processing Pipeline with Microservices | by Netflix Technology Blog | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/rebuilding-netflix-video-processing-pipeline-with-microservices-4e5e6310e359\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Adopts AV1 Codec, Powering 30% of Streams for Enhanced Efficiency\",\"url\":\"https://www.webpronews.com/netflix-adopts-av1-codec-powering-30-of-streams-for-enhanced-efficiency/\"},{\"title\":\"video-encoding | Noise\",\"url\":\"https://noise.getoto.net/tag/video-encoding/\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 now powers 30% of Netflix streaming: \\\"On track to become number one\\\" - FlatpanelsHD\",\"url\":\"https://www.flatpanelshd.com/news.php?subaction=showfull&id=1764912460\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 Open Video Codec Now Powers 30% of Netflix Streaming - Slashdot\",\"url\":\"https://news.slashdot.org/story/25/12/05/0146253/av1-open-video-codec-now-powers-30-of-netflix-streaming\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of Netflix's Cosmos encoding pipeline, AV1 adoption, and per-title encoding developments in 2024–2025:\n\n---\n\n## Netflix Cosmos Encoding Pipeline & AV1 Per-Title Encoding (2024–2025)\n\n### Cosmos Platform Overview\n\nNetflix's Video and Image Encoding team in Encoding Technologies (ET) spent several years rebuilding its video processing pipeline on the next-generation microservice-based computing platform called **Cosmos**.\n\nDevelopment of Cosmos began in 2018, aiming to significantly increase system flexibility and feature development velocity beyond its predecessor, Reloaded. Cosmos was developed as a computing platform for workflow-driven, media-centric microservices.\n\nCosmos combines microservice architecture with asynchronous workflows and serverless functions, aiming to modernize Netflix's media processing pipelines with improved flexibility, efficiency, and developer productivity.\n\n### Key Microservices in the Pipeline\n\nThe Cosmos-based pipeline is composed of several specialized microservices:\n\n1. **Video Inspection Service (VIS):** This service takes a mezzanine as input and performs various inspections. It extracts metadata from different layers for downstream services and flags issues if invalid or unexpected metadata is observed.\n\n2. **Complexity Analysis Service (CAS):** The optimal encoding recipe is highly content-dependent, and CAS handles the complexity data needed for optimization.\n\n3. **Ladder Generation Service (LGS):** This service creates an entire bitrate ladder for a given encoding family (H.264, AV1, etc.). It fetches the complexity data from CAS and runs the optimization algorithm to create encoding recipes. The CAS and LGS cover innovations like per-title encoding, mobile encodes, per-shot optimization, and optimized 4K encoding.\n\n4. **Video Encoding Service (VES):** This service takes a mezzanine and an encoding recipe and creates an encoded video. The recipe includes the desired encoding format and properties of the output, such as resolution, bitrate, etc. VES supports encoding into a variety of codec formats, including AVC, AV1, and VP9, using different encoder binaries for different codec formats.\n\n### Per-Title Encoding with AV1\n\nNetflix's adoption of AV1 involves a sophisticated pipeline of encoding, testing, and deployment. The company employs \"per-title encoding,\" where each piece of content is analyzed and compressed individually to maximize efficiency. AV1 fits seamlessly into this, offering tools like film grain synthesis that recreate the textured look of movies without bloating file sizes.\n\n### AV1 Adoption Milestones (2024–2025)\n\n- As of late 2025, AV1 accounts for approximately 30% of all Netflix streaming, making it the second most-used codec — and it's on track to become number one very soon.\n\n- On TVs, Netflix's AV1 video streams outperform both MPEG4 AVC and HEVC in quality evaluations while using one-third less bandwidth on average.\n\n- **AV1 HDR:** In March 2025, Netflix launched AV1 HDR streaming using HDR10+ as the HDR format. The combination of AV1 and HDR10+ delivers images with greater detail, more vibrant colors, and an overall heightened sense of immersion. At that time, 85% of their HDR catalog had AV1-HDR10+ coverage, expected to reach 100% within months.\n\n- **Film Grain Synthesis (FGS):** The AV1 specification incorporates Film Grain Synthesis — instead of encoding grain as part of every frame, the grain is stripped out before encoding and then resynthesized at the decoder using parameters sent in the bitstream. In July 2025, Netflix successfully productized AV1 FGS. AV1 FGS can reduce bitrate by 66% while delivering clearly better quality compared to regular AV1 streams.\n\n### Device Ecosystem\n\nOver the past five years (2021–2025), 88% of large-screen devices submitted for Netflix certification — including TVs, set-top boxes, and streaming sticks — have supported AV1, with the vast majority offering full 4K@60fps capability.\n\n### Future: AV1 Beyond VOD and AV2\n\n- Netflix is actively evaluating the use of AV1 in live streaming, believing it could help further scale Netflix's live programming, including delivery to tens of millions of viewers simultaneously.\n\n- For live sports like football, tennis, and boxing, AV1's layered coding supports encoding the main content in a base layer and graphics overlays in an enhancement layer, which could greatly simplify the live streaming workflow and reduce delivery costs.\n\n- Netflix is also excited about the forthcoming release of AV2, announced by the Alliance for Open Media. AV2 is poised to set a new benchmark for compression efficiency and streaming capabilities.\n\n---\n\nIn summary, Netflix's Cosmos microservice platform has been the foundation for major encoding innovations in 2024–2025, enabling seamless per-title and per-shot encoding optimization across codecs including AV1. AV1 has rapidly grown to power nearly a third of all Netflix streaming, with Film Grain Synthesis and HDR support being standout features of the recent rollout.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"04859136-087e-4927-83ec-7bacc98854b1","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:16:55.749Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9b70e969-30f1-41b4-bca4-b46cff1a1ae7"}
