{"parentUuid":"456ef722-f569-4fdc-b41e-aa61d770340f","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012Q96mkcMEWeBJwrNUx5DDC","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Amazon Prime Video Twitch streaming infrastructure Go language encoding 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"The Game Awards 2025 to Stream on Prime Video in New Deal With Amazon\",\"url\":\"https://variety.com/2025/gaming/news/game-awards-streaming-amazon-prime-video-twitch-1236574939/\"},{\"title\":\"Streaming video teardown: Twitch vs. Amazon Prime for Thursday Night Football | Mux\",\"url\":\"https://www.mux.com/blog/thursday-night-football-streaming-technology-showdown-amazon-prime-vs-twitch\"},{\"title\":\"Amazon Emerges as Exclusive Streaming Partner for All Things Go 2025 — With Amazon Music, Prime Video, and Twitch Included In the Action - NewsBreak\",\"url\":\"https://www.newsbreak.com/digital-music-news-296091106/4238604287798-amazon-emerges-as-exclusive-streaming-partner-for-all-things-go-2025-with-amazon-music-prime-video-and-twitch-included-in-the-action\"},{\"title\":\"PrimeVideo - Twitch\",\"url\":\"https://www.twitch.tv/primevideo\"},{\"title\":\"Link Amazon Prime to Twitch: Step-by-Step Guide 2025\",\"url\":\"https://smartbuy.alibaba.com/tips/prime-twitch-linking\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting - Streamrun docs\",\"url\":\"https://streamrun.com/docs/twitch-enhanced-broadcasting\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch introduces multi-encode livestreaming and AV1 support - CSI Magazine\",\"url\":\"https://www.csimagazine.com/csi/Twitch-introduces-Enhanced-Broadcasting-and-AV1-support.php\"},{\"title\":\"Linking Your Amazon and Twitch Accounts - Amazon Customer Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html?nodeId=GTCADSYDQFMD5DRS\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch Prime settings\",\"url\":\"https://www.twitch.tv/settings/prime\"},{\"title\":\"Amazon, Twitch & The Bold Future Of Live Streaming | ROS\",\"url\":\"https://repertoireproductions.com/2019/09/27/amazon-twitch-livestreaming/\"}]\n\nThe initial search returned results primarily about Amazon/Twitch streaming partnerships and video encoding infrastructure, but didn't specifically address the use of the **Go programming language** in their encoding systems. Let me refine the search to target that more specifically.\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Inside Amazon Prime: Top Programming Languages Powering Web & Mobile Magic\",\"url\":\"https://www.technologywithvivek.com/2025/06/Top%20programming%20languages%20used%20in%20Amazon%20Prime%20App.html\"},{\"title\":\"Which Programming Languages Are Being Used by Popular Streaming Services (Netflix, Apple TV, Amazon Prime, YouTube…)? - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/emma_richardson/which-programming-languages-are-being-used-by-popular-streaming-services-netflix-apple-tv-amazon-41n1\"},{\"title\":\"Top Programming Languages Used Behind Amazon Prime Streaming Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.technologywithvivek.com/2024/07/Top%20Programming%20Languages%20Used%20in%20Amazon%20Prime%20Streaming%20Service.html\"},{\"title\":\"What are the most notable computer programming languages for streaming movies on websites such as Amazon Prime? - Quora\",\"url\":\"https://www.quora.com/What-are-the-most-notable-computer-programming-languages-for-streaming-movies-on-websites-such-as-Amazon-Prime\"},{\"title\":\"Watch C Programming Language | Prime Video\",\"url\":\"https://www.amazon.com/C-Programming-Language/dp/B07WDT9JSF\"},{\"title\":\"Realtime Video Capture with the Go Programming Language | Learning the Go Programming Language\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/learning-the-go-programming-language/realtime-video-capture-with-go-65a8ac3a57da\"},{\"title\":\"Video Central\",\"url\":\"https://videocentral.amazon.com/support/delivery-experience/mec-title-meta-data/languages-and-genres\"},{\"title\":\"Adopting Kotlin at Prime Video for higher developer satisfaction and less code | AWS Open Source Blog\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/opensource/adopting-kotlin-at-prime-video-for-higher-developer-satisfaction-and-less-code/\"},{\"title\":\"Playing videos with Golang. I created a new Go library called… | by Maxim Gradan | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@maximgradan/playing-videos-with-golang-83e67447b111\"},{\"title\":\"Support – Video Central\",\"url\":\"https://videocentral.amazon.com/home/help?topicId=GGUTLEAY9WXZQD8C&ref_=avd_sup_GGUTLEAY9WXZQD8C\"}]\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Twitch Engineering: An Introduction and Overview\",\"url\":\"https://blog.twitch.tv/en/2015/12/18/twitch-engineering-an-introduction-and-overview-a23917b71a25/\"},{\"title\":\"Breaking the Monolith at Twitch: Part 2\",\"url\":\"https://blog.twitch.tv/en/2022/04/12/breaking-the-monolith-at-twitch-part-2/\"},{\"title\":\"Breaking the Monolith at Twitch: Part One\",\"url\":\"https://blog.twitch.tv/en/2022/03/30/breaking-the-monolith-at-twitch/\"},{\"title\":\"Which programming languages were used to build Twitch.tv website and app? - Quora\",\"url\":\"https://www.quora.com/Which-programming-languages-were-used-to-build-Twitch-tv-website-and-app\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch Engineering\",\"url\":\"https://blog.twitch.tv/en/tags/engineering/\"},{\"title\":\"Software Engineer - Developer Infrastructure at Twitch\",\"url\":\"https://startup.jobs/software-engineer-developer-infrastructure-at-twitch-3\"},{\"title\":\"Community Resources | Twitch Developers\",\"url\":\"https://dev.twitch.tv/code/\"},{\"title\":\"I worked at Twitch from 2014 to 2018. I was never on the video team, but here ar... | Hacker News\",\"url\":\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=20349004\"},{\"title\":\"What technology does Twitch use? - Quora\",\"url\":\"https://www.quora.com/What-technology-does-Twitch-use\"},{\"title\":\"Live Video Streaming Infrastructure at Twitch - Scaleyourapp\",\"url\":\"https://scaleyourapp.com/live-video-streaming-infrastructure-at-twitch/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive summary of what I found about **Amazon Prime Video and Twitch's streaming infrastructure**, particularly regarding the **Go programming language** and **encoding/transcoding systems**:\n\n---\n\n## Twitch's Use of Go (Golang)\n\n### Backend Migration to Go\nBack in 2015, a new company-wide campaign to move all of Twitch's backend code into Go microservices started, codenamed \"Wexit.\" At the time of writing, most teams at Twitch own multiple services, and the language of choice for server code is Go (Twitch also uses TypeScript, Python, C++, Java/Kotlin and ObjectiveC/Swift on other platforms).\n\n### Go in Chat Infrastructure\nChat is a highly scalable real-time distributed system written in Go. It delivers hundreds of billions of messages per day to users who are watching video via their own protocols, as well as supporting IRC as a communication protocol. Core chat components include Edge (which receives and distributes messages between clients and backend services, speaking IRC over both raw TCP and WebSockets), and Pubsub (which distributes messages internally across Edge nodes, combining with Edge to form a hierarchical message distribution system for massive fanout).\n\n### Go's Role in Performance\n\"We use Go at Twitch for many of our busiest systems. Its simplicity, safety, performance, and readability make it a good tool.\"\n\n### Early Go Adoption\nIn 2012, the Go language was gaining a lot of popularity, especially with the launch of Go 1.0. A number of Twitch engineers attended a GoSF meetup to determine if Go was ready for production. The first Go code to run in production was a tiny Pubsub server—a small but important piece of the chat system. With only about 100 lines of code, it handled every message at Twitch through a single thread. The performance-per-thread was doubled with respect to the previous Python implementation, and it could be modified to run in multiple threads using goroutines.\n\n### Twirp RPC Framework\nTwitch released Twirp, an RPC framework they use for communication between backend servers written in Go.\n\n---\n\n## Video Encoding & Transcoding Infrastructure\n\n### Twitch Transcoding System (C/C++ and Go)\nTranscoding (a system written in C/C++ and Go) converts the stream into multiple formats to be played on the viewer's device under different network conditions. The transcoded formats are then distributed across data centers and PoPs (Point of Presence) worldwide. Initially, Twitch transcoded only two to three percent of channels, but with a hardware-based transcoder built in-house, they significantly reduced costs, allowing them to scale and transcode every video upload to their servers.\n\n### Amazon Prime Video Encoding\nAmazon (Prime Video) uses the common combination of H.264 for video and AAC for audio. Amazon uses 9 video renditions for their desktop player ranging from 288p up to 720p30p @ 8 Mbit. Amazon is leveraging a good amount of their own AWS Elemental-based software solutions for packaging and ad-insertion technology.\n\n### Twitch vs. Prime Video Infrastructure\nIt's well known from talks by Twitch engineers that Twitch built most of their video infrastructure in-house, which makes it harder to compare responses to known platforms in the industry. Twitch is a big fan of the Apple HLS format for delivering their content. It seems unlikely that Twitch is just pulling the Amazon Prime Video stream and rebranding it—they maintain separate encoding pipelines.\n\n### Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting (2024–2025)\nTwitch Enhanced Broadcasting is available for anyone who wants to stream with multiple resolutions up to Full HD with H.264 codec. Higher resolutions and modern codecs (AV1 and HEVC) are being tested with the TEB Beta Community as of June 2025. Twitch and NVIDIA released Enhanced Broadcasting/Multi-Encode Livestreaming, a new feature that allows streamers to transmit up to three concurrent streams at different resolutions and quality so each viewer gets the optimal experience.\n\n---\n\n## Amazon Prime Video's Programming Languages\n\nGo (Golang) is used for Microservices & Backend Services. Amazon's massive backend relies on microservices, and Go has become popular for writing performance-optimized, lightweight services. C++ is often used in performance-critical components of Amazon Prime Video, such as the video encoding and decoding processes. Amazon Prime Video's tech stack includes Java, Python, Go, Node.js, and C++.\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. **Go is the primary backend language at Twitch**, powering chat, microservices, and RPC communication (via Twirp).\n2. **Twitch's transcoding system** uses both **C/C++ and Go** — C/C++ for the computationally intensive video encoding, with Go managing orchestration and service layers.\n3. **Amazon Prime Video** uses Go for microservices and backend services, while relying on **C++** for performance-critical encoding/decoding tasks and **AWS Elemental** for its streaming pipeline.\n4. **Twitch and Prime Video maintain separate video infrastructure**, despite both being owned by Amazon.\n5. As of 2025, Twitch is advancing its encoding with **Enhanced Broadcasting**, testing modern codecs like **AV1 and HEVC** alongside the standard H.264.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"46f2dbb0-ddf2-4bf8-bf3d-45dad0bee69e","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:17:42.646Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"456ef722-f569-4fdc-b41e-aa61d770340f"}
