{"parentUuid":"60bea888-0eff-441e-9f70-d714fef5957f","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FHYJZYaa7av2m3eTXwbooC","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AWS Elemental MediaLive MediaConnect IVS live streaming architecture 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Choosing the right AWS live streaming solution for your use case | Amazon Web Services\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/awse-choosing-aws-live-streaming-solution-for-use-case/\"},{\"title\":\"AWS Direct-to-Consumer & Streaming showcase at IBC 2024 | Amazon Web Services\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/aws-direct-to-consumer-streaming-showcase-at-ibc-2024/\"},{\"title\":\"Delivering a reliable live video stream using AWS Elemental Link and Amazon IVS | Amazon Web Services\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/delivering-a-reliable-live-video-stream-using-aws-elemental-link-and-amazon-ivs/\"},{\"title\":\"Architecture overview - Live Streaming on AWS\",\"url\":\"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/solutions/latest/live-streaming-on-aws/architecture-overview.html\"},{\"title\":\"Live Video Processing - AWS Elemental MediaLive - AWS\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/medialive/\"},{\"title\":\"Amazon IVS vs. AWS Elemental MediaLive – Which Live Streaming Solution Should You Choose?\",\"url\":\"https://trackit.io/amazon-ivs-or-aws-elemental-medialive-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"AWS Media Services: Build a Scalable Media Platform in Cloud\",\"url\":\"https://www.cloudthat.com/resources/blog/aws-media-services-build-a-scalable-media-platform-in-cloud\"},{\"title\":\"AWS Elemental MediaLive – AWS for M&E Blog\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/category/media-services/aws-elemental-medialive/feed/\"},{\"title\":\"AWS Elemental MediaLive | AWS for M&E Blog\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/category/media-services/aws-elemental-medialive/\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - aws-solutions-library-samples/live-streaming-on-aws: The live stream solution is a reference deployment that demonstrates how to deliver ...\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/aws-solutions/live-streaming-on-aws\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of the AWS live streaming architecture involving **AWS Elemental MediaLive**, **AWS Elemental MediaConnect**, and **Amazon IVS** based on the latest information:\n\n---\n\n## AWS Live Streaming Architecture (2024–2025)\n\n### Key Services Overview\n\n1. **AWS Elemental MediaLive**\n   - AWS Elemental MediaLive is a live video encoding service that makes delivering 24/7 linear channels and live events at scale easier and more reliable.\n   - AWS Elemental MediaLive is a broadcast-quality live video processing and streaming service. It enables users to easily set up live streams with advanced broadcasting capabilities, high-availability, and a wide range of customization possibilities.\n\n2. **AWS Elemental MediaConnect**\n   - MediaConnect can be used to ingest live video from a remote event location and share it with cable distributors or the AWS cloud to process the stream.\n   - Managing encrypted AWS Elemental MediaConnect entitlements across AWS accounts can be challenging, particularly when dealing with secret strings and upstream changes.\n\n3. **Amazon Interactive Video Service (IVS)**\n   - Amazon IVS is a fully-managed and easy-to-set-up AWS live streaming solution that is ideal for creating low latency interactive video experiences. Amazon IVS is built on the same live streaming technology that powers Twitch. It is simple-to-use and can easily be integrated into websites and apps.\n\n---\n\n### Reference Architecture: Live Streaming on AWS\n\nThe official **Live Streaming on AWS** solution provides a reference deployment:\n\n- You can configure this solution to ingest Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP), Real-Time Messaging Protocol (RTMP), HTTP Live Streaming (HLS), or AWS Elemental MediaConnect flows. This solution also includes three encoding profiles.\n- AWS Elemental MediaLive ingests two input feeds and transcodes your content into two adaptive bitrate (ABR) HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) streams as output. Two feeds are ingested for MediaLive redundancy. Each MediaLive transcodes a single ingest feed into ABR outputs. AWS Elemental MediaPackage ingests the MediaLive ABR output and packages the live stream into HTTP Live Streaming (HLS), Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP (DASH) and Common Media Application Format (CMAF) formats that are delivered to three MediaPackage custom endpoints.\n- MediaPackage is an origin server that prepares the content for delivery to phones, tablets, smart TVs, and other devices. An Amazon CloudFront distribution is configured to use the MediaPackage custom endpoints as its origin and includes a CDN Identifier custom HTTP header to authenticate requests.\n- This solution uses AWS Elemental MediaLive, MediaPackage, and MediaConnect, which are currently available in specific AWS Regions only. If you use MediaConnect as input, you must deploy this solution in the same Region as your MediaConnect flows.\n\n---\n\n### MediaLive + IVS Integration Architecture\n\nA specific architecture pattern combines Elemental Link, MediaLive, and IVS:\n\n- AWS Elemental Link is a small, portable, and easy-to-setup device that delivers high-quality HD video from your HDMI or SDI source to AWS Elemental MediaLive. AWS Elemental Link uses an advanced video compression technology that continuously adjusts to available bandwidth. AWS Elemental MediaLive encodes an RTMP output that can be ingested by Amazon Interactive Video Service.\n- AWS Elemental MediaLive encodes your live stream and pushes the RTMP output to Amazon Interactive Video Service channel. Amazon IVS then transcodes, packages, and delivers a reliable live stream for your audience to consume via the Amazon IVS player SDK, which you can embed in your website and/or mobile application.\n\n---\n\n### Choosing Between IVS and MediaLive\n\n| Feature | Amazon IVS | AWS Elemental MediaLive |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Latency** | Around 2 seconds | Around 30 seconds (typical market performance) |\n| **Resolution** | Max 1080p, up to 60 FPS | Up to 8K and over 120 FPS |\n| **Codec Support** | Only H.264 and AAC | Supports most current codecs |\n| **Setup** | Very easy to set up — users simply create a channel, configure their streaming software (e.g., OBS), and start streaming. | Requires additional setup — users need to design and assemble components including ingest endpoints, encoders, MediaPackage outputs, and CDN. |\n| **Interactivity** | A cornerstone feature of Amazon IVS. Interactivity is enabled via a flexible metadata API to insert interactive elements into the video stream, making it easy to drive updates like polls, product carousels, and viewer counts. | Interactivity is technically possible but requires more custom work. |\n\n---\n\n### 2024–2025 Developments\n\n- Amazon IVS powers live sports streaming and other events with support for multi-user chat, polls, event statistics, and other custom content delivered in synchronization with video playback.\n- In the dynamic world of sports broadcasting, a subtle revolution was unfolding behind the scenes during the Paris 2024 Olympic Games, with technological mastery at play behind the curtain.\n- For NAB 2025, AWS will be demonstrating an end-to-end Live Capture and Fast-Turnaround workflow, with TAMS as the 'single source of truth' for stored content.\n- AWS Elemental MediaLive provides built-in reliability and resiliency. The service manages resources across multiple Availability Zones and automatically addresses potential issues without disrupting the live streams.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nThe typical AWS live streaming architecture in 2024–2025 follows this flow:\n\n**Source → MediaConnect (transport) → MediaLive (encoding) → MediaPackage (packaging) → CloudFront (CDN) → Viewers**\n\nOr for interactive/low-latency use cases:\n\n**Source → MediaLive (encoding) → Amazon IVS (transcoding + packaging + delivery) → IVS Player SDK → Viewers**\n\nThe choice between the two paths depends on your requirements for latency, interactivity, video quality, customization, and operational complexity.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"795e77c4-c725-412f-babf-06d76780ac87","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:18:27.156Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"60bea888-0eff-441e-9f70-d714fef5957f"}
