{"parentUuid":"bfb3f8c0-a7bf-43db-9354-f95b2073068c","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PreToolUse","hookName":"PreToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/pretooluse.py"},"toolUseID":"toolu_013xgfH6M9x5rcSQ94zeJ2nT","parentToolUseID":"toolu_013xgfH6M9x5rcSQ94zeJ2nT","uuid":"c7295111-9c26-4dc9-b65a-e2651ebcf7db","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:20:08.647Z"}
{"parentUuid":"c7295111-9c26-4dc9-b65a-e2651ebcf7db","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"Disney+ streaming technology stack CDN encoding transcoding CMAF HLS backend architecture"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_013xgfH6M9x5rcSQ94zeJ2nT","uuid":"3fe3cb40-f810-445e-a38c-89861a51e6ed","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:20:12.560Z"}
{"parentUuid":"3fe3cb40-f810-445e-a38c-89861a51e6ed","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Disney+ streaming technology stack CDN encoding transcoding CMAF HLS backend architecture"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01JJmg8LTyH1CkT8iM8oAufA","parentToolUseID":"toolu_013xgfH6M9x5rcSQ94zeJ2nT","uuid":"97858393-0016-4b9c-945e-436363bbbc8d","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:20:16.074Z"}
{"parentUuid":"bfb3f8c0-a7bf-43db-9354-f95b2073068c","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013xgfH6M9x5rcSQ94zeJ2nT","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Disney+ streaming technology stack CDN encoding transcoding CMAF HLS backend architecture\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Inside Disney+ Streaming Technology: Transcoding, ABR, And Akamai CDN Explained\",\"url\":\"https://www.frugaltesting.com/blog/inside-disney-streaming-technology-transcoding-abr-and-akamai-cdn-explained\"},{\"title\":\"CMAF Streaming Specification: One File for HLS and DASH\",\"url\":\"https://www.videoexpertsgroup.com/glossary/cmaf\"},{\"title\":\"Encryption Archives – The Broadcast Knowledge\",\"url\":\"https://thebroadcastknowledge.com/tag/encryption/\"},{\"title\":\"Hulu Archives – The Broadcast Knowledge\",\"url\":\"https://thebroadcastknowledge.com/tag/hulu/\"},{\"title\":\"How Disney Streaming Delivers Consistent Media Experiences\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamingmedia.com/Articles/ReadArticle.aspx?ArticleID=147353\"},{\"title\":\"Achieving 3-Second Latency in Streaming: A Deep Dive into LL-HLS and LL-DASH Optimization with CDN\",\"url\":\"https://gcore.com/blog/optimizing-hls-dash-3sec\"},{\"title\":\"What Is HLS Streaming and When Should You Use It [2026 Update]\",\"url\":\"https://www.dacast.com/blog/hls-streaming-protocol/\"},{\"title\":\"A Developer's Guide to Encoding for Streaming - LiveAPI Blog\",\"url\":\"https://liveapi.com/blog/encoding-for-developers/\"},{\"title\":\"Live Streaming & Transcoding API | Qencode\",\"url\":\"https://cloud.qencode.com/live-streaming\"},{\"title\":\"HLS, MPEG-DASH, RTMP, and WebRTC - Which Protocol is Right for Your App?\",\"url\":\"https://getstream.io/blog/protocol-comparison/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of the Disney+ streaming technology stack, including its CDN, encoding/transcoding, CMAF, HLS, and backend architecture:\n\n---\n\n## Disney+ Streaming Technology Stack & Architecture\n\n### Cloud-Native Infrastructure\n\nDisney+ follows a cloud-native architecture built on scalable cloud computing infrastructure, hybrid cloud infrastructure deployments, and distributed CI/CD pipelines. The distributed architecture allows Disney+ to process large volumes of content in parallel using AWS Elemental, Amazon Web Services instances, and cloud infrastructure as a service platforms.\n\n### Streaming Protocols: 100% HLS + CMAF\n\nA defining characteristic of Disney+'s architecture is its commitment to CMAF with HLS. Disney+, as explained by Bill Zurat, is 100% HLS CMAF. Benefiting from the long experience of the Disney Streaming Services teams (formerly BAMTECH), but also from setting up a new service, Disney were able to bring in CMAF from the start.\n\nThere are issues ensuring end-device support, but as part of the launch, a number of devices were sunsetted which didn't have the requirements necessary to support either the protocol or the DRM needed.\n\n### What CMAF Brings to the Stack\n\nThe Common Media Application Format (CMAF) was introduced to solve format fragmentation. CMAF makes it possible to package video once and deliver it to both HLS and DASH players. As a result, streaming platforms can simplify their workflows while improving efficiency and latency performance.\n\nCMAF sits beneath HLS and DASH in the delivery stack. HLS and DASH define how the player requests video segments and adapts to network conditions. CMAF defines how those segments are structured and packaged. This layered approach allows streaming platforms to combine the strengths of both protocols.\n\n### Adaptive Bitrate (ABR) Streaming\n\nWith billions of playback requests, diverse device compatibility (from smart TVs to Apple TV 4K), and a rapidly growing content library, Disney+ depends on advanced adaptive bitrate streaming, intelligent video transcoding software, a multi-layer CDN architecture, and a secure cloud infrastructure built for resilience.\n\nHLS and DASH streaming technologies use automatic selection of the superior version dependent on the internet speed. This avoids buffering and allows smooth playback. When using a slow internet connection, Disney+ will automatically downgrade to a lower-quality version so that the video does not have to stop playing.\n\n### Encoding & Transcoding\n\nx264 encoding is used as a method of compressing videos which can then utilize less space and be easily streamed. Older devices — phones, tablets, or TVs that do not have the ability to run 4K or HDR — still receive a compatible version of the video.\n\nAs HDR vs Dolby Vision workflows advance, AV1 adoption increases, and cloud infrastructure services expand toward serverless and edge-native architectures, Disney+ is positioned to push the limits of video quality, low latency, and user experience.\n\n### CDN Architecture (Akamai)\n\nA panel from Streaming Media West Connect discusses CMAF use within Akamai, Netflix, Disney+, and Hulu. Peter Chave from Akamai explained that CMAF is important to CDNs because if companies are able to use just one CMAF file as the source for different delivery formats, this reduces storage costs and makes each individual file more popular, thus increasing the chance of having a file available in the CDN (particularly at the edge) and reducing cache misses.\n\nThey've had to do some work to ensure that CMAF is carried throughout the CDN efficiently and ensuring the manifests are correctly checked.\n\n### DASH-HLS Interoperability & CTA WAVE\n\nDisney Streaming Services has also been involved in industry standardization. According to Zachary Cava, media experience comes through via the manifest play formats. That's where DASH and HLS interoperability becomes a very significant topic. The manifest playlists are the things that define the media experience, and you need to be able to represent those CMAF assets equally in any form you're using.\n\nThey have worked a long time within the Hulu product to define interoperability between DASH and HLS, and a group started up under CTA WAVE to help define this.\n\n### DRM & Content Protection\n\nDisney handles premium studio masters, high-value series, original programming, and exclusive theatrical releases — making strong digital rights management an essential part of its streaming platform architecture. Disney ensures content protection through a multi-layer security foundation built on secure cloud infrastructure, encryption standards, and real-time authentication checks.\n\nDisney+ supports multiple DRM systems to cover all devices, including Widevine (DRM technology used mostly on Android devices and Chrome browsers) and PlayReady (DRM used mainly for Windows devices and some smart TVs).\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Component | Technology |\n|---|---|\n| **Streaming Protocol** | HLS (100% HLS CMAF) |\n| **Media Packaging** | CMAF (fMP4 segments) |\n| **Encoding** | x264 / H.264; exploring AV1, HEVC |\n| **ABR** | Adaptive bitrate with multi-rung ladder |\n| **CDN** | Akamai (multi-layer CDN architecture) |\n| **Cloud Infrastructure** | AWS (AWS Elemental, hybrid cloud) |\n| **DRM** | Widevine, PlayReady, FairPlay |\n| **Heritage** | BAMTECH (Disney Streaming Services) |\n\nThis architecture enables Disney+ to deliver 4K HDR content globally across a vast range of devices while maintaining low latency, high quality, and robust content protection.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"02d24d05-5906-4682-9618-2973478420bd","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:20:53.877Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bfb3f8c0-a7bf-43db-9354-f95b2073068c"}
