{"parentUuid":"bf943b2d-8672-4b99-a495-3195c889998f","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"YouTube Live streaming infrastructure VP9 AV1 DASH architecture engineering 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01C2u9EL2wcBMGDRJzVFNFED","uuid":"24ddbfb9-570e-48be-8774-dfeb0012dbfe","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:20:58.715Z"}
{"parentUuid":"24ddbfb9-570e-48be-8774-dfeb0012dbfe","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"YouTube Live streaming infrastructure VP9 AV1 DASH architecture engineering 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_017AADwWhtVrxJ426EkQdp5N","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01C2u9EL2wcBMGDRJzVFNFED","uuid":"c395a75a-bb13-40f4-b090-2d82ef786a14","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:21:00.774Z"}
{"parentUuid":"82a641de-0c66-4878-ac1d-d39b21a834ad","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01C2u9EL2wcBMGDRJzVFNFED","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"YouTube Live streaming infrastructure VP9 AV1 DASH architecture engineering 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Unveiling the Backbone of YouTube Live Streaming: A Deep Dive into YouTube’s Architecture and Real-Time Video Processing - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/wittedtech-by-harshit/unveiling-the-backbone-of-youtube-live-streaming-a-deep-dive-into-youtubes-architecture-and-real-time-video-processing-f6j\"},{\"title\":\"Video Streaming with the AV1 Video Codec in Mobile Devices\",\"url\":\"https://engineering.fb.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Meta-AV1-White-Paper-FINAL.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 - What is it and how does it work?\",\"url\":\"https://getstream.io/glossary/av1/\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 vs VP9 vs VP8: Codec Comparison Guide 2026\",\"url\":\"https://www.red5.net/blog/av1-vs-vp9-vs-vp8-comparison-for-live-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 Live Streaming Is Finally Coming To YouTube | Tom's Hardware\",\"url\":\"https://www.tomshardware.com/news/av1-live-streaming-is-finally-coming-to-youtube\"},{\"title\":\"Best Video Codec For Streaming in 2026 - AV1 vs H.265 vs VP9 ?\",\"url\":\"https://www.muvi.com/blogs/best-video-codec-for-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AV1\"},{\"title\":\"YouTube Tech Stack: How 2.5B Users Stream Video at Scale\",\"url\":\"https://www.vdocipher.com/blog/youtube-tech-stack-architecture/\"},{\"title\":\"VP9 Codec: Google's Open-Source Video Codec for Streaming\",\"url\":\"https://antmedia.io/vp9-codec/\"},{\"title\":\"Video Streaming With the AV1 Video Codec in Mobile Devices - Engineering at Meta\",\"url\":\"https://engineering.fb.com/2025/09/24/video-engineering/video-streaming-with-av1-video-codec-mobile-devices-meta-white-paper/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive summary of the latest information on YouTube's live streaming infrastructure, VP9, AV1, DASH architecture, and engineering developments in 2024–2025:\n\n---\n\n## YouTube Live Streaming Infrastructure & Codec Architecture (2024–2025)\n\n### Streaming Protocols: DASH & HLS\n\nYouTube uses MPEG-DASH as the primary protocol for web browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge) and HLS for Apple devices (iOS, Safari). DASH uses 1–5 second segments with H.264/VP9/AV1 codec support, while HLS uses 6–10 second segments with H.264/HEVC support. DASH's shorter segments allow faster quality adaptation, reducing rebuffering by up to 30% on mobile networks.\n\nVideos are segmented into short chunks (usually 2–6 seconds) compatible with HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) and Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP (DASH). This segmentation enables smooth playback by allowing quick switching between quality levels based on real-time network conditions.\n\n### Codec Strategy: H.264, VP9, and AV1\n\nYouTube transcodes uploads into multiple codecs: H.264 (baseline), VP9, and AV1 (for supported clients), at multiple bitrates per resolution. VP9 saves 30–40% bandwidth vs H.264, while AV1 saves 50–60% but costs 50–100x more to encode.\n\nAV1, Google's open-source codec, offers high-quality video at lower bitrates, reducing bandwidth usage, especially important in mobile and low-speed networks.\n\n### AV1 in Live Streaming on YouTube\n\nYouTube rolled out beta support for a new video live-streaming standard known as Enhanced RTMP, which allows streamers to utilize several of the latest video codecs, including AV1, VP9, and HEVC (H.265) to live stream videos to YouTube.\n\nThe only side-effect of YouTube's implementation is that videos still get transcoded to VP9. This means AV1 live streams are re-coded to YouTube's VP9 codec. VP9 is known to be of slightly lesser quality but supports far more GPU hardware. Thankfully, transcoding doesn't take away much from AV1's encoding capabilities, and video quality remains exceptionally good.\n\nIn 2025, YouTube launched AV1 support for popular live streams.\n\n### AV1 Adoption Milestones\n\nIn 2018, YouTube began deploying AV1, starting with its AV1 Beta Launch Playlist. By December 2025, they reported that 30% of their streams use AV1.\n\nThe broader codec landscape shows: 2024–2025 saw widespread hardware decoding support across new devices; 2025–2027 is expected to bring hardware encoding support to make AV1 viable in live streaming and broadcasting applications; and by 2027, AV1 should replace VP9 and HEVC in most streaming applications.\n\n### VP9's Continued Role\n\nVP9 remains optimal for latency-critical live streaming. YouTube encodes SDR video in VP9 Profile 0 by default. For low-volume or real-time encoding scenarios, VP9 offers a practical middle ground between H.264 compatibility and compression efficiency.\n\n### CDN and Playback Architecture\n\nThe YouTube CDN delivers video segments from edge servers located close to viewers to minimize latency and buffering. When a user presses play, requests are routed to the nearest healthy edge cache. If a segment is not cached, it is fetched from a regional cache or origin storage and then cached for future requests. High cache hit ratios allow YouTube to serve billions of views daily with low latency.\n\nYouTube most likely uses internal tracing systems similar to Google's Dapper to correlate latency across services. Each playback request propagates a trace ID across the stack: API gateway → metadata service → CDN edge → player, allowing engineers to pinpoint failures.\n\n### Custom Hardware\n\nYouTube uses proprietary encoding chips designed for real-time compression optimized for codecs like AV1, high-density storage disks to minimize footprint and maximize storage per physical rack, and custom-built switches and fiber connections to ensure high-speed data transfers across its global infrastructure.\n\n### AV2 on the Horizon\n\nThe Alliance for Open Media has announced that AV2, the successor to AV1, is planned for release by the end of 2025. Broader adoption is expected in 2026–2027 as hardware support becomes available and platforms begin integrating it into production workflows. AV2 is expected to deliver even greater compression efficiency and new features for next-generation streaming.\n\n### Industry-Wide AV1 Momentum\n\nCurrently, over 70% of global video watch on the Meta Family of Apps is AV1. Along with other large technology companies like Google, Meta has found that AV1 codecs can enhance video compression by 30% compared to prior standards like H.264 and VP9.\n\n---\n\nIn summary, YouTube's streaming infrastructure in 2024–2025 is a sophisticated, multi-codec system that balances cutting-edge AV1 compression with the widely supported VP9 codec, delivered primarily over DASH with adaptive bitrate switching, backed by a massive custom CDN and proprietary encoding hardware.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b5212511-6314-47bb-88c2-887a3a95a759","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:21:37.067Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"82a641de-0c66-4878-ac1d-d39b21a834ad"}
{"parentUuid":"b5212511-6314-47bb-88c2-887a3a95a759","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/posttooluse.py"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01C2u9EL2wcBMGDRJzVFNFED","toolUseID":"toolu_01C2u9EL2wcBMGDRJzVFNFED","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:21:37.068Z","uuid":"d4f5173b-1ca6-48c8-b5e2-cbd3bb1d3ed8"}
