{"parentUuid":"750d5fc3-a38e-4fb8-a679-0dad4e3986de","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PreToolUse","hookName":"PreToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/pretooluse.py"},"toolUseID":"toolu_01BqJnHePjiVsw2WaCKziTbp","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01BqJnHePjiVsw2WaCKziTbp","uuid":"8ccc97f6-401c-4c6a-ac9d-72b31e9d7b6d","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:22:14.945Z"}
{"parentUuid":"8ccc97f6-401c-4c6a-ac9d-72b31e9d7b6d","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"YouTube Google backend infrastructure programming languages Borg Spanner video processing 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01BqJnHePjiVsw2WaCKziTbp","uuid":"6da6dd18-047d-422f-b3db-74bf3e2f5dc4","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:22:17.453Z"}
{"parentUuid":"6da6dd18-047d-422f-b3db-74bf3e2f5dc4","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"YouTube Google backend infrastructure programming languages Borg Spanner video processing 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01LfQ38P3PKk46Mh5L2mJAD9","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01BqJnHePjiVsw2WaCKziTbp","uuid":"0cac2c5f-9edb-41b7-b950-7f0cf8f13ce6","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:22:19.536Z"}
{"parentUuid":"750d5fc3-a38e-4fb8-a679-0dad4e3986de","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BqJnHePjiVsw2WaCKziTbp","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"YouTube Google backend infrastructure programming languages Borg Spanner video processing 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Unveiling the Backbone of YouTube Live Streaming: A Deep Dive into YouTube’s Architecture and Real-Time Video Processing - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/wittedtech-by-harshit/unveiling-the-backbone-of-youtube-live-streaming-a-deep-dive-into-youtubes-architecture-and-real-time-video-processing-f6j\"},{\"title\":\"What Framework Does YouTube Use? A Detailed Breakdown\",\"url\":\"https://www.nogentech.org/what-framework-does-youtube-use/\"},{\"title\":\"YouTube Development: Architecture & API Guide\",\"url\":\"https://createbytes.com/insights/case-study-how-was-youtube-developed\"},{\"title\":\"System Design of YouTube: A Detailed Deep Dive into the Video Giant - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/wittedtech-by-harshit/system-design-of-youtube-a-detailed-deep-dive-into-the-video-giant-5019\"},{\"title\":\"YouTube – Programming Languages That Built It - GreenWare Tech\",\"url\":\"https://greenware-tech.com/youtube-programming-languages-that-built-it/\"},{\"title\":\"Top Backend Programming Languages in 2025: Trends and Insights - CloudThat Resources\",\"url\":\"https://www.cloudthat.com/resources/blog/top-backend-programming-languages-in-2025-trends-and-insights\"},{\"title\":\"Spanner innovations in 2024 | Google Cloud Blog\",\"url\":\"https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/databases/spanner-innovations-in-2024\"},{\"title\":\"Google's Top Programming Languages in 2024\",\"url\":\"https://www.analyticsinsight.net/programming/googles-top-programming-languages-in-2024\"},{\"title\":\"Spanner in 2025 | Google Cloud Blog\",\"url\":\"https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/databases/spanner-in-2025\"},{\"title\":\"Best Back-End Programming Languages 2025 & Beyond : Aalpha\",\"url\":\"https://www.aalpha.net/blog/best-back-end-programming-languages/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of YouTube's backend infrastructure, including the programming languages, key systems like Borg and Spanner, and video processing technologies based on recent 2024–2025 sources:\n\n---\n\n## YouTube's Backend Infrastructure\n\n### Programming Languages\n\nYouTube uses a **polyglot (multi-language) approach** to its backend. The main languages are Python for data pipelines and infrastructure, Java for core backend services, C++ for high-performance tasks like video processing, and Go for networking services.\n\n- **Python**: YouTube originally started as a platform heavily reliant on Python due to its simplicity and versatility. Python is great for rapid development and handling backend tasks, and it remains a significant part of YouTube's infrastructure today.\n\n- **C++**: C++ is used in performance-critical areas, especially in video processing — tasks requiring high performance and efficiency, such as encoding and decoding videos, optimizing playback, and managing resource-heavy operations.\n\n- **Java**: Java is used for backend services and scalability. Known for its reliability and scalability, Java is used in many of YouTube's core systems, such as serving APIs and managing large-scale server-side applications.\n\n- **Go (Golang)**: Go is used for high-performance services and networking. YouTube uses Go for building highly concurrent and efficient systems, especially for handling large-scale network requests and microservices.\n\nAt a broader Google level, Google heavily relies on Go and Java for its backend infrastructure.\n\n---\n\n### Borg (Cluster Management)\n\nBorg is Google's internal cluster manager, used for deploying and managing large-scale services, ensuring that containerized microservices are orchestrated and balanced efficiently. Borg, an internal Google cluster management system, predated Kubernetes but remains influential. It schedules workloads and manages resources effectively, and it enabled the development of Kubernetes, serving as a blueprint for modern orchestration tools.\n\n---\n\n### Spanner (Globally Distributed Database)\n\nSpanner is Google's always-on, virtually unlimited database that powers planet-scale applications like Gmail, YouTube, and Google Photos. Outside of Google, Spanner powers demanding workloads for household brands like Yahoo!, The Home Depot, Wayfair, and Pokémon Go. Today, Spanner handles over 4 billion queries per second at peak and more than 15 exabytes of data, with five 9s of availability, plus global consistency.\n\nAs of 2025, those numbers have grown significantly: Spanner now handles over 6 billion queries per second at peak and more than 17 exabytes of data, with five 9s of availability, plus global consistency.\n\nWithin YouTube specifically, Spanner is Google's globally distributed, strongly consistent database. It manages transactional data, such as user watch history and session tracking, providing consistency across YouTube's global user base. For data that requires strong global consistency, YouTube leverages Spanner — the world's first globally distributed relational database. This is crucial for systems like Content ID and rights management, where data must be consistent and accurate across the entire globe in real-time.\n\n#### Spanner Innovations (2024–2025)\n\nWith the launch of Spanner Graph, full-text search and vector search, Spanner went from being a highly available, globally consistent and scalable database to a multi-model database with intelligent, interoperable capabilities for building AI-enabled applications. Spanner's multi-model support lets you consolidate databases, saving on costs and reducing operational overhead.\n\nIn 2025, Google expanded these multi-model capabilities, adding new functionality across graph, vector, text search, as well as Vertex AI integrations. They introduced multiple capabilities to make Spanner an AI-first database, including built-in AI integrations such as ML.PREDICT for natural language queries, MCP Toolbox for Databases, and Agent Development Kit for Spanner.\n\n---\n\n### Video Processing & Delivery\n\nVideos uploaded by users need to be stored, processed, and transcoded into various formats (240p, 480p, 720p, 1080p, 4K) to accommodate different user bandwidths. Users upload video data in chunks (multi-part upload) using the Google Cloud Storage API.\n\nYouTube follows a microservices architecture with services dedicated to specific functionalities (like encoding, recommendations, live chat, and content moderation). This isolation allows each component to be developed, deployed, and scaled independently.\n\nFor content delivery, YouTube uses Google's custom-built CDN to distribute content across edge nodes worldwide. These CDNs ensure low latency and high-speed content delivery by caching popular content closer to users.\n\nFor live streaming, Real-Time Messaging Protocol (RTMP) is the primary method for ingesting live video streams. When a stream starts, YouTube's ingestion servers handle the incoming video via RTMP, which is ideal for low-latency video transport.\n\n---\n\n### Additional Infrastructure Components\n\n- **Bigtable**: A petabyte-scale, fully managed NoSQL database service. YouTube uses Bigtable for a wide range of analytical and large-scale data workloads, such as storing user watch history, analytics data for creators, and feeding data into machine learning models.\n\n- **Colossus/GFS**: The actual video files are stored on Google's internal distributed file system (Colossus, successor to GFS). This system is designed for storing massive files and ensuring redundancy and high-throughput access across Google's data centers.\n\n- **Vitess**: Born at YouTube, Vitess is a database clustering system for horizontally scaling MySQL.\n\n- **Communication Protocols**: gRPC and REST APIs are used for microservices communication, while QUIC and HTTP/2 are often used for faster, more reliable video transmission.\n\n- **TensorFlow**: TensorFlow is an open-source machine learning framework from Google. It powers YouTube's recommendation engine, which analyzes user behavior to provide personalized video suggestions using neural networks, collaborative filtering, and content-based filtering.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"27d579cf-3bbf-49fa-a2df-6167e00033f3","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:22:53.442Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"750d5fc3-a38e-4fb8-a679-0dad4e3986de"}
