{"parentUuid":"c71685d5-6dde-4f1d-bce6-74371250c220","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PreToolUse","hookName":"PreToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/pretooluse.py"},"toolUseID":"toolu_01DCm227oW15oukzwsJv42Q9","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01DCm227oW15oukzwsJv42Q9","uuid":"bb6e53e8-e2f2-4f54-b26d-8a265bf6201d","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:22:55.943Z"}
{"parentUuid":"bb6e53e8-e2f2-4f54-b26d-8a265bf6201d","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"streaming video industry CMAF adoption multi-CDN strategy object storage S3 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01DCm227oW15oukzwsJv42Q9","uuid":"477446c3-9bf8-48bd-95a8-7b7942a3ee1a","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:22:57.661Z"}
{"parentUuid":"477446c3-9bf8-48bd-95a8-7b7942a3ee1a","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"streaming video industry CMAF adoption multi-CDN strategy object storage S3 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_013hZfv1dGzvRwrRgRk8DLSu","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01DCm227oW15oukzwsJv42Q9","uuid":"8fcbd94d-6038-4003-8ba7-f8867d1677c0","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:22:59.757Z"}
{"parentUuid":"c71685d5-6dde-4f1d-bce6-74371250c220","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DCm227oW15oukzwsJv42Q9","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"streaming video industry CMAF adoption multi-CDN strategy object storage S3 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"CMAF\",\"url\":\"https://www.cta.tech/cmaf/\"},{\"title\":\"Comparing The 10 Best Video CDN Providers for Live Streaming in 2026\",\"url\":\"https://www.dacast.com/blog/content-delivery-network-cdn-providers-live-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"Migrating Microsoft Smooth Streaming to Amazon CloudFront for streaming video | Amazon Web Services\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/migrating-microsoft-smooth-streaming-to-amazon-cloudfront-for-streaming-video/\"},{\"title\":\"Load testing streaming video at scale, part 2: Optimizing remote object storage-based VOD\",\"url\":\"https://www.unified-streaming.com/blog/load-testing-streaming-video-at-scale-part-2-optimizing-remote-object-storage-based-vod\"},{\"title\":\"Video Delivery on Multi-CDN | CDN Handbook\",\"url\":\"https://www.cdnhandbook.com/multicdn/video-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Live Origin. Xiaomei Liu, Joseph Lynch, Chris Newton | by Netflix Technology Blog | Dec, 2025 | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/netflix-live-origin-41f1b0ad5371\"},{\"title\":\"CMAF-IF\",\"url\":\"https://www.cta.tech/Resources/Standards/CMAF-IF\"},{\"title\":\"The State of CMAF in 2026: How \\\"Common\\\" Is It 10 Years Later?\",\"url\":\"https://www.wowza.com/blog/the-state-of-cmaf-in-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Top 5 CDNs for Video Streaming (2025) — See Which One Dominates\",\"url\":\"https://blog.blazingcdn.com/en-us/which-cdn-is-ideal-for-video-streaming\"},{\"title\":\"Choosing the ideal origin for live media & entertainment workflows | Amazon Web Services\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/choosing-the-ideal-origin-for-live-media-entertainment-workflows/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of the latest developments in the streaming video industry related to **CMAF adoption**, **multi-CDN strategies**, and **object storage/S3** across 2024–2026:\n\n---\n\n## CMAF Adoption\n\nThe Common Media Application Format (CMAF) is a container format that enables interoperability between HLS and DASH. The CMAF Industry Forum promotes the adoption of CMAF based on common codec media profiles, encryption modes and delivery mechanisms, supported by both the DASH and HLS adaptive streaming standards.\n\n### Current State (2025–2026)\nBack in 2022, CMAF was a necessary but slow-moving effort to bridge the gap between .ts and .mp4 containers. At that time, it was primarily a promise of efficiency — one set of files could cover both HLS and DASH, reducing storage costs and simplifying the delivery chain. While the potential was clear, the implementation was often plagued by inconsistent player support and the growing pains of early-stage low-latency standards.\n\nWhile the early promise of CMAF focused on basic storage savings and the first iterations of low latency, today's standard is defined by its reliability across complex, global workflows. It is no longer just a packaging trick. It is the architectural foundation for a new generation of video workflows.\n\nCMAF has carved out a dominant sweet spot in the latency spectrum. By delivering scalable low latency, typically in the 2-to-5-second range, CMAF provides the perfect balance for live sports, news, and large-scale events where synchronicity and high quality are paramount, but sub-second interactivity is not a requirement.\n\nIn 2026, the industry has converged on a common, best-in-class implementation logic that ensures feature parity is the default, not the exception. Whether delivering via DASH or HLS, the underlying CMAF chunks now support identical encryption schemes, captioning formats, and playback behaviors.\n\nCMAF provides a common container and supports small chunks for low latency playback.\n\n---\n\n## Multi-CDN Strategies\n\nMany businesses are adopting a multi-CDN approach, combining multiple providers to enhance reliability, mitigate outages, and improve load balancing.\n\nGeographic gaps demand a multi-CDN blend. The \"best\" CDN depends on your priorities: global scale, low latency, security, China delivery, analytics, or cost control.\n\n### Key CDN Providers and Trends\n- If you need maximum global scale and proven live streaming reliability, start with Akamai.\n- If you want developer-friendly edge control and real-time performance, look at Fastly or Cloudflare.\n- If you're all-in on a cloud ecosystem, pair the cloud CDN with its media tooling: AWS CloudFront, Google Cloud CDN/Media CDN, or Azure CDN/Front Door.\n\nAs 5G adoption grows, CDNs are optimizing scalable video streaming to support higher resolutions, such as 4K and 8K, while ABR ensures seamless playback based on a viewer's network conditions.\n\nBy 2027, analysts predict 45% of global CDNs will fold compute and storage into unified programmable edges, slashing round-trips for personalization and dynamic ad insertion.\n\n### Netflix's Approach\nNetflix chose to build a highly scalable origin instead of relying on the traditional origin shields approach for better end-to-end cache consistency control and simpler system architecture. The live origin in this architecture directly connects with top-tier Open Connect nodes, which are geographically distributed across several sites.\n\n---\n\n## Object Storage / S3 for Streaming\n\n### S3 as a VOD Origin\nThe simplest way to create a VOD origin for Smooth Streaming is to store prepackaged content in Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), an object storage service offering industry-leading scalability, data availability, security, and performance.\n\nFor nearly two decades, customers have been serving media stored in Amazon S3 through Amazon CloudFront to their global end users. On-demand assets can be encrypted at rest in S3 and served securely to end-users at scale, as S3 retains multiple copies of the objects for resiliency and redundancy purposes.\n\n### S3 Scaling Considerations\nWhile Amazon S3 is infinitely scalable, customers need to understand how performance is impacted by the operations and API requests that occur for peak events. Amazon S3 scales its high request rates by parallelizing access across a number of buckets or prefixes. A single partition can provide 3,500 PUT/POST/DELETE and 5,500 GET requests per second.\n\n### Netflix's S3 Challenges for Live Streaming\nNetflix's original storage architecture for the Live Origin was simple: just use AWS S3 like they do for SVOD. This served them well initially for low-traffic events, but as they scaled up they discovered that live streaming has unique latency and workload requirements that differ significantly from on-demand. While S3 met its stated uptime guarantees, their strict 2-second retry budget inherent to live events led them to explore optimizations specifically tailored for real-time delivery at scale. As they put it, \"AWS S3 is an amazing object store, but our Live streaming requirements were closer to those of a global low-latency highly-available database.\"\n\nDuring the Tyson vs. Paul fight event in 2024, Netflix observed a historic peak of 65 million concurrent streams.\n\n### CMAF + S3 VOD Optimization\nFor VOD use cases with remote object storage, Unified Streaming packaged media from progressive MP4 to CMAF using two-second segments for audio and video, created 'index' dref MP4 files from each CMAF media file, and uploaded the dref MP4s, server manifest, and CMAF files to an AWS S3 bucket. Such setups that rely on remote object-based cloud storage services like S3 have become the norm for streaming services that work with very large content libraries.\n\n### AWS Elemental MediaPackage\nAWS Elemental MediaPackage ensures that HLS/DASH/CMAF/Microsoft Smooth outputs are functional and always up-to-date with the newest specifications, such as LL-HLS. MediaPackage provides just-in-time packaging for both live and VOD content, allowing customers to save costs on both encoding and storage by ingesting only a single type of source feed, such as HLS. This source can be repackaged on-the-fly to any of the other output types, with minimal effect to latency, and zero effect to quality.\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. **CMAF has matured** from an efficiency promise to the architectural backbone of modern streaming, with full feature parity across HLS and DASH now largely achieved.\n2. **Multi-CDN is becoming standard practice** for large-scale streaming services seeking reliability, geographic coverage, and cost optimization.\n3. **S3 remains the default storage layer** for VOD workflows, but live streaming at massive scale (as Netflix discovered) may require custom storage architectures beyond basic object storage.\n4. **Just-in-time packaging** (e.g., AWS MediaPackage) with CMAF reduces storage duplication and simplifies multi-format delivery across CDNs.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"90766bfb-7d0d-4cf0-a040-0a4a91cc074f","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:23:48.240Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c71685d5-6dde-4f1d-bce6-74371250c220"}
