{"parentUuid":"33d0c71a-409f-462f-a0f0-53eaf5b442a2","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"live streaming ingest protocol SRT RTMP WebRTC WHIP comparison adoption 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01A7gxS8VQDe99GDFJ4P1KWo","uuid":"adfbac3a-0e88-4943-b153-ddfb5baddbe7","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:23:52.096Z"}
{"parentUuid":"adfbac3a-0e88-4943-b153-ddfb5baddbe7","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"live streaming ingest protocol SRT RTMP WebRTC WHIP comparison adoption 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_016SJuzQ7JCtNtt7sjXGSdUj","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01A7gxS8VQDe99GDFJ4P1KWo","uuid":"9425b04d-9d01-4ba1-96fc-bb22ed2b8963","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:23:54.057Z"}
{"parentUuid":"023506ae-9ce4-46e4-95f9-8e01fb20e273","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01A7gxS8VQDe99GDFJ4P1KWo","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"live streaming ingest protocol SRT RTMP WebRTC WHIP comparison adoption 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Streaming Protocols for Live Broadcasting: Everything You Need to Know\",\"url\":\"https://www.dacast.com/blog/streaming-protocols/\"},{\"title\":\"RTMP, HLS, SRT, RTSP, and WebRTC: a comprehensive guide to video streaming protocols in 2024\",\"url\":\"https://flussonic.com/blog/news/best-video-streaming-protocols\"},{\"title\":\"The Latency Wars: Why WHIP and MoQ are Dethroning RTMP & SRT for Real-Time Streaming | by D F | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@contact_45426/the-latency-wars-why-whip-and-moq-are-dethroning-rtmp-srt-for-real-time-streaming-7e5bea4032ee\"},{\"title\":\"Which live stream ingest protocol is right for you? | Mux\",\"url\":\"https://www.mux.com/blog/which-live-stream-ingest-protocol-is-right-for-you\"},{\"title\":\"WHIP Protocol - What is it and how does it work?\",\"url\":\"https://getstream.io/glossary/whip-protocol/\"},{\"title\":\"All About Video Streaming Protocols: The Complete Guide\",\"url\":\"https://vidizmo.ai/blog/everything-you-need-to-know-about-video-streaming-protocols\"},{\"title\":\"How to Choose the Right Ingest Protocol for Your Livestreaming Project | Native Frame\",\"url\":\"https://www.nativeframe.com/blog/choosing-the-right-livestream-ingest-protocol-a-developers-guide\"},{\"title\":\"Low-Latency & Real-Time Streaming: SRT vs WHIP\",\"url\":\"https://srtminiserver.com/tpost/g0p2vmk331-low-latency-amp-real-time-streaming-srt\"},{\"title\":\"WebRTC Latency: Comparing Low-Latency Streaming Protocols (2026 Update)\",\"url\":\"https://www.nanocosmos.net/blog/webrtc-latency/\"},{\"title\":\"Best Low-Latency Streaming Protocols for IRL Streaming\",\"url\":\"https://www.tvunetworks.com/guides/best-video-streaming-protocols-for-low-latency-streaming/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of the current landscape of live streaming ingest protocols — **SRT, RTMP, WebRTC, and WHIP** — based on recent industry sources:\n\n---\n\n## Live Streaming Ingest Protocol Comparison & Adoption (2024–2025)\n\n### **RTMP (Real-Time Messaging Protocol)**\n- **Status: Still dominant for ingest.** While RTMP's use as a delivery protocol has mostly faded away in favor of newer technologies, it still reigns as the dominant technology for getting media from source to encoder.\n- RTMP remains the default ingest protocol for Twitch, YouTube, Facebook, and Kick. It is simple, reliable, and widely supported.\n- A number of factors have contributed to its dominance in the space, but the largest one is the chicken and egg problem between encoders and live streaming providers. Encoders don't want to build in support for a protocol that no providers support and providers don't want to support a protocol that no encoders support.\n- Most major platforms still rely on RTMP for ingest, which strongly influences real-world workflows. Even if a stream starts with SRT or another protocol, it often ends as RTMP before reaching Twitch or YouTube.\n\n### **SRT (Secure Reliable Transport)**\n- **Status: Growing adoption, especially for contribution/transport.** SRT is an open-source protocol designed by Haivision to deliver high-quality, low-latency video across unpredictable networks. SRT addresses many of the challenges associated with streaming over the public internet, such as packet loss, jitter, and fluctuating bandwidth.\n- SRT can transmit high-quality video, including full HD and 4K resolutions, making it ideal for professional broadcasts. It provides low-latency transmission, essential for live broadcasting and real-time video applications. SRT includes robust error correction mechanisms that maintain stream quality even over unstable networks.\n- SRT is used to transmit a high-quality signal between locations and the Studio for further processing and preparation of the final signal.\n- SRT is excellent for IRL streaming to the cloud, but usually requires conversion to RTMP before reaching platforms.\n- However, this protocol is still not widely supported yet due to being an emerging technology.\n\n### **WebRTC / WHIP (WebRTC-HTTP Ingestion Protocol)**\n- **Status: Rapidly gaining traction for ultra-low-latency ingest.** Standardized by the IETF as RFC 9725 in March 2025, WHIP provides a simple, HTTP-based signaling mechanism to initiate a WebRTC session for media ingestion.\n- WHIP itself isn't the media protocol; WebRTC is. WebRTC is designed from the ground up for real-time, sub-second latency communication. It runs over UDP and incorporates sophisticated techniques for congestion control and fast adaptation. WHIP just makes it far easier to connect your WebRTC source to a media server or CDN that supports WHIP.\n- Adoption is growing steadily, with many encoders (hardware and software) and media server platforms (like Dolby.io, Cloudflare, Red5 Pro, Wowza) offering WHIP support for ingest. It's becoming the go-to for bringing WebRTC's low latency into professional streaming workflows.\n- RTMP and SRT both depend on network protocols that are inaccessible in a browser environment, which probably means WebRTC/WHIP is your best option for browser-based streaming.\n- In the latest release of OBS Studio there is already a possibility to stream using WHIP protocol.\n- WHIP is in early adoption, and many major platforms do not support it as an ingestion option. This means broadcasters often still rely on RTMP as WHIP gains traction.\n\n### **Latency Comparison**\n| Protocol | Typical Latency | Best For |\n|----------|----------------|----------|\n| RTMP | 1–5 seconds | Ingestion with low latency for sports streaming, financial trading, and interactive webinars |\n| SRT | 400–800 ms | Low-latency streaming where you can achieve glass-to-glass delay within 400–800 milliseconds |\n| WebRTC/WHIP | 200–500 ms | Auctions, two-way classrooms, betting-style interactivity, live shopping, instant reactions |\n\n### **Emerging: Media over QUIC (MoQ)**\n- If WHIP is the specialized sprinter for ingest, MoQ aims to be the versatile, next-generation decathlete for both ingest and widespread media delivery. MoQ is an emerging transport protocol, currently under active development by the IETF MoQ Working Group (as of May 2025). It's designed to send media directly over QUIC.\n- In 2025, nanocosmos was the first global live streaming provider who added MOQ to the nanoStream platform as a next-generation transport protocol for real-time media delivery. Built on QUIC and WebTransport, MOQ enables even lower latency and improved network stability compared to other workflows.\n\n### **Key Takeaway: The Recommended Stack**\nThe common recommendation is: RTMP or SRT for ingest/contribution (easy encoder support vs. more resilient transport), HLS or DASH for large-scale delivery (CDN-friendly ABR), WebRTC for ultra-low latency interactivity (sub-second), and Low-latency HLS/CMAF sitting in the middle (near-real-time without WebRTC complexity).\n\nMany providers have found that supporting multiple ingest protocols gives users the most flexibility, primarily using RTMP for its wide compatibility while building support for WHIP and keeping a close eye on SRT and Media over QUIC (MoQ).\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"f99a9a2c-a88e-4371-893f-a98285f00d6c","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:24:31.356Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"023506ae-9ce4-46e4-95f9-8e01fb20e273"}
