{"parentUuid":"047bd532-fef9-4a55-a918-c46b8d1944fe","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PreToolUse","hookName":"PreToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/pretooluse.py"},"toolUseID":"toolu_01XnsoC9qYgydUfxjSP5AdfR","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01XnsoC9qYgydUfxjSP5AdfR","uuid":"52824361-1fcd-4924-831f-671f20e1695d","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:24:34.073Z"}
{"parentUuid":"52824361-1fcd-4924-831f-671f20e1695d","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"Kafka video streaming pipeline event-driven architecture media processing 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01XnsoC9qYgydUfxjSP5AdfR","uuid":"45cd606a-1436-4863-be67-ec1cfca6485c","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:24:35.396Z"}
{"parentUuid":"45cd606a-1436-4863-be67-ec1cfca6485c","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Kafka video streaming pipeline event-driven architecture media processing 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_0164J7USA75DrXvGE7JMHWRm","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01XnsoC9qYgydUfxjSP5AdfR","uuid":"219eb020-033c-4e75-bf58-2404a7ac1d05","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:24:37.331Z"}
{"parentUuid":"047bd532-fef9-4a55-a918-c46b8d1944fe","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XnsoC9qYgydUfxjSP5AdfR","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Kafka video streaming pipeline event-driven architecture media processing 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"How and Why Netflix Built a Real-Time Distributed Graph: Part 1 — Ingesting and Processing Data Streams at Internet Scale | by Netflix Technology Blog | Oct, 2025 | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/how-and-why-netflix-built-a-real-time-distributed-graph-part-1-ingesting-and-processing-data-80113e124acc\"},{\"title\":\"What Is A Kafka Data Pipeline? Architecture & Examples 2025\",\"url\":\"https://estuary.dev/blog/kafka-data-pipeline/\"},{\"title\":\"Top Trends for Data Streaming with Apache Kafka and Flink in 2026 - Kai Waehner\",\"url\":\"https://www.kai-waehner.de/blog/2025/12/10/top-trends-for-data-streaming-with-apache-kafka-and-flink-in-2026/\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Real-Time Video Streaming on the Pub/Sub Architecture: Case of Apache Kafka\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/384006571_Real-Time_Video_Streaming_on_the_PubSub_Architecture_Case_of_Apache_Kafka\"},{\"title\":\"Kafka Event Driven Architecture for Seamless Streaming | Hevo\",\"url\":\"https://hevodata.com/learn/kafka-event-driven-architecture/\"},{\"title\":\"Event-driven architectures with Kafka and Kafka Streams\",\"url\":\"https://developer.ibm.com/articles/awb-event-driven-architectures-with-kafka-and-kafka-streams/\"},{\"title\":\"How Apache Kafka and Flink Power Event-Driven Agentic AI in Real Time - Kai Waehner\",\"url\":\"https://www.kai-waehner.de/blog/2025/04/14/how-apache-kafka-and-flink-power-event-driven-agentic-ai-in-real-time/\"},{\"title\":\"Event Streaming is Topping Out - by Stanislav Kozlovski\",\"url\":\"https://bigdata.2minutestreaming.com/p/event-streaming-is-topping-out\"},{\"title\":\"How to Build Scalable Streaming Data Pipelines with Apache Kafka - RisingWave: Real-Time Event Streaming Platform\",\"url\":\"https://risingwave.com/blog/how-to-build-scalable-streaming-data-pipelines-with-apache-kafka/\"},{\"title\":\"Event Driven Architecture with Kafka: Real Use Cases\",\"url\":\"https://www.decipherzone.com/blog-detail/event-driven-architecture-with-kafka\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of the latest developments and insights on **Kafka video streaming pipelines, event-driven architecture, and media processing** from 2024–2025:\n\n---\n\n## Kafka in Event-Driven Architecture & Streaming Pipelines\n\nApache Kafka remains one of the most powerful and scalable architectures for real-time data pipelines. Its event-driven design enables organizations to ingest, process, and deliver high-throughput data with fault tolerance and reliability, making it a critical piece of modern data infrastructure.\n\nAs of 2025, over 150,000 organizations rely on Apache Kafka to power data streaming and real-time systems, making it the de facto standard in the event streaming world. In a recent study, analysts observed that 85% of global businesses have already turned to event-driven architecture (EDA) to meet their business requirements. The EDA software market was valued at $8.63 billion in 2024 and is projected to grow to $21.4 billion by 2035.\n\n### Kafka 4.0 and Evolving Architecture\n\nWith the release of Kafka 4.0, the platform has become even more streamlined thanks to its new KRaft-based architecture, which removes the ZooKeeper dependency and reduces operational complexity. But even with these improvements, managing Kafka at scale still requires significant engineering investment.\n\nIn 2024, unified data architectures emerged, including open table formats like Apache Iceberg. In 2025, the Kafka protocol was democratized, with multiple vendors offering compatible services and deployment options.\n\n---\n\n## Netflix: A Real-World Example of Kafka-Powered Media Processing\n\nNetflix provides a prime example of Kafka at the heart of a large-scale media and video streaming pipeline:\n\n- Netflix opted for a stream processing architecture, enabling them to update data as events happen, minimizing delay and ensuring the system reflects the latest member actions. Member actions in the Netflix app are published to their API Gateway, which writes them as records to Apache Kafka topics. Kafka is the mechanism through which internal data applications consume these events.\n\n- Netflix's applications consume several different Kafka topics, each generating up to roughly 1 million messages per second. Topic records are encoded in the Apache Avro format, with schemas persisted in a centralized schema registry.\n\n- Event records in the Kafka streams are ingested by Flink jobs. Netflix chose Flink because of its strong capabilities around near-real-time event processing, with robust internal platform support allowing jobs to integrate with Kafka and various storage backends seamlessly.\n\n- Initially, Netflix tried having just one Flink job that consumed all the Kafka source topics, but this became a big operational headache. They pivoted to a 1:1 mapping from the Kafka source topic to the consuming Flink job, which made each job much simpler to maintain, analyze, and tune.\n\n---\n\n## Real-Time Video Streaming on Kafka's Pub/Sub Architecture\n\nA 2024 research paper specifically explored Kafka for video streaming:\n\nThe study investigates the specific operational demands inherent in implementing real-time video streaming within the Pub/Sub architecture, focusing on the Apache Kafka framework.\n\nKey findings include that the diverse spectrum of Pub/Sub platforms, adaptable to various configuration parameters, necessitates thorough consideration for real-time video streaming. Parameters like video compression rates, codecs, frame rate, and bit rate significantly impact video quality and performance. Additionally, Pub/Sub configurations—such as broker vs. partition choices, replication factors, and publisher nuances—affect network performance and jitter.\n\n---\n\n## 2025–2026 Trends: Kafka + Flink + AI\n\nAs agentic AI adoption grows, data streaming and its event-driven architecture are becoming the foundation that delivers the context, state, and coordination these agents need to work safely and effectively.\n\nProven technologies such as Kafka and Flink are evolving into complete platforms that integrate storage, governance, analytics, and automation.\n\nKafka ensures agents receive reliable, ordered event streams, while Flink provides stateful, low-latency stream processing for real-time reactions and long-lived context management.\n\n### Market Dynamics\n\nWarpStream started their company in 2023 and got acquired in 2024 for $220M, as Confluent's acquisition paired with WarpStream's positioning resulted in an exit the whole streaming world envies. However, some analysts note that Kafka is becoming a commodity — as one commentator put it, \"Everybody and their abuela has a Kafka service now.\"\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. **Kafka remains central** to modern event-driven architectures, especially for media and video streaming pipelines at scale.\n2. **Real-time video streaming** over Kafka requires careful tuning of both video parameters (codecs, frame rates) and Kafka configurations (partitions, replication).\n3. **Kafka + Flink** is the dominant combination for high-throughput, low-latency media event processing, as demonstrated by Netflix.\n4. **Kafka 4.0's KRaft architecture** simplifies operations, while the ecosystem continues to evolve toward unified streaming and analytics platforms.\n5. **AI integration** (especially agentic AI) is the next frontier for Kafka-based event-driven systems in 2025–2026.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b761a0cf-8007-450f-a911-eb403de77782","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:25:10.991Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"047bd532-fef9-4a55-a918-c46b8d1944fe"}
