{"parentUuid":"ea8dfeda-87c1-45c5-b9df-f9e9a27ce2db","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"Netflix live streaming Go Golang backend microservices 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01MBUey8H84AVsvaHm9G8juC","uuid":"909258b5-cb23-4b3c-a78b-6b713d82b7ba","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:25:16.957Z"}
{"parentUuid":"909258b5-cb23-4b3c-a78b-6b713d82b7ba","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Netflix live streaming Go Golang backend microservices 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01HTBi34c5rQCRBVQETTBWde","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01MBUey8H84AVsvaHm9G8juC","uuid":"e7d3fc84-2594-4080-b071-d90a7e31023b","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:25:19.126Z"}
{"parentUuid":"ffc78449-dd8b-4a87-9555-90685dafe0b9","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MBUey8H84AVsvaHm9G8juC","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Netflix live streaming Go Golang backend microservices 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Golang for Backend Developers — Part 6: The Netflix-Style Microservice Architecture — Built from Scratch | by Harshavardhan Mamidipaka | Oct, 2025 | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@mamidipaka2003/go-backend-mastery-part-6-the-netflix-style-microservice-architecture-built-from-scratch-6a0ebcccd241\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - mithildani/go-netflix: A simple CRUD REST API service written in Go using Gin framework for a Netflix like movie streaming application.\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/mithildani/go-netflix\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix, Inc. · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/Netflix?language=go\"},{\"title\":\"Microservices Architecture Guide: From Monolith to Netflix-Scale · BackendBytes\",\"url\":\"https://www.backendbytes.com/system-design/microservices-architecture-monolith-netflix-scale/\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Architecture: A Deep Dive into Seamless Global Streaming\",\"url\":\"https://talent500.com/blog/netflix-streaming-architecture-explained/\"},{\"title\":\"ByteByteGo | Netflix's Tech Stack\",\"url\":\"https://bytebytego.com/guides/netflixs-tech-stack/\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Live Origin. Xiaomei Liu, Joseph Lynch, Chris Newton | by Netflix Technology Blog | Dec, 2025 | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/netflix-live-origin-41f1b0ad5371\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Tech Stack Explained: CDN (Open Connect), and Microservices\",\"url\":\"https://www.vdocipher.com/blog/netflix-tech-stack-and-architecture/\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Architecture Case Study: How Does the World’s Largest Streamer Build for Scale?\",\"url\":\"https://www.clustox.com/blog/netflix-case-study/\"},{\"title\":\"From On-Demand to Live : Netflix Streaming to 100 Million Devices in under 1 Minute - InfoQ\",\"url\":\"https://www.infoq.com/news/2025/12/netflix-live-streaming-pipeline/\"}]\n\nHere are the results of the search on **Netflix live streaming, Go/Golang, backend microservices (2024–2025)**:\n\n---\n\n## Netflix's Live Streaming Architecture & Go/Golang Usage\n\n### Netflix's Live Origin Service\nNetflix Live Origin is a multi-tenant microservice operating on EC2 instances within the AWS cloud. According to Netflix's own tech blog (Dec 2025), during the Tyson vs. Paul fight event in 2024, a historic peak of 65 million concurrent streams was observed. Consequently, a scalable architecture for live origin is essential for the success of large-scale live streaming. They chose to build a highly scalable origin instead of relying on the traditional origin shields approach for better end-to-end cache consistency control and simpler system architecture.\n\nKey design decisions include:\n- Resilience is achieved through redundant regional live streaming pipelines, with failover orchestrated at the server-side to reduce client complexity. The implementation of epoch locking at the cloud encoder enables the origin to select a segment from either encoding pipeline.\n- Netflix adopted a manifest design with segment templates and constant segment duration to avoid frequent manifest refresh.\n- Leveraging Netflix's microservice platform priority rate limiting feature, the origin prioritizes live edge traffic over DVR traffic during periods of high load on the storage platform. The live edge vs. DVR traffic detection is based on the predictable segment template. The template is further cached in memory on the origin node to enable priority rate limiting without access to the datastore.\n\n### Netflix's Go/Golang Open-Source Projects\nNetflix maintains several Go-based projects on GitHub:\n- **go-env**: a golang library to manage environment variables.\n- **spectator-go-runtime-metrics**: updated in July 2024, and **go-env** updated in October 2024.\n- **virtual-kubelet** (forked): Virtual Kubelet is an open source Kubernetes kubelet implementation.\n- **go-expect**: an expect-like golang library to automate control of terminal or console based programs.\n\n### Netflix's Microservices Architecture at Scale\nNetflix is a global tech giant powering entertainment for over 300 million subscribers (Q1 2025) across 190+ countries. Netflix is composed of over 1,000 loosely coupled microservices, each responsible for a specific function. These services communicate asynchronously using APIs, event queues (Kafka), and service discovery mechanisms. This modular design helps Netflix iterate faster, isolate failures, and deploy updates without system-wide impact.\n\nWhile Netflix's architecture excels at on-demand streaming, live events present new challenges. The 2024 Tyson-Paul boxing match, with 65 million concurrent viewers, exposed limitations in live content delivery, such as real-time encoding, manifest management, and CDN caching. However, the platform's microservices design ensured that issues with live streaming did not affect on-demand services.\n\n### Live Streaming Pipeline (InfoQ, Dec 2025)\nNetflix's global live streaming platform powers millions of viewers with cloud-based ingest, custom live origin, Open Connect delivery, and real-time recommendations. The architecture includes low-latency pipelines, adaptive bitrate streaming, and operational monitoring that ensure reliable, scalable, and synchronized live event experiences worldwide.\n\n### Educational / Community Resources\n- A Medium article covers building a \"Netflix-Style Microservice Architecture\" from scratch using Golang for backend developers.\n- There's also a GitHub project (**go-netflix**) — a simple CRUD REST API service written in Go using the Gin framework for a Netflix-like movie streaming application.\n- BackendBytes published a complete guide to microservices architecture, from monolith decomposition to production deployment, with patterns used by Netflix and Amazon featuring Java and Go examples.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\nNetflix uses **Go (Golang)** for specific infrastructure and tooling libraries (environment management, metrics, Kubernetes integrations), while its broader backend runs primarily on **Java/Spring Boot** with a massive microservices architecture on AWS. Their **live streaming platform**, battle-tested during the 2024 Tyson vs. Paul event with 65M concurrent viewers, is a cloud-native microservice system that leverages priority rate limiting, custom CDN (Open Connect), and redundant encoding pipelines for resilience and scalability.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9bb0cf23-9ff2-4d39-80e8-3dc044afc4bc","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:25:40.448Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ffc78449-dd8b-4a87-9555-90685dafe0b9"}
