{"parentUuid":"a0b5585a-00e2-4202-97a9-9a83d2255e65","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"streaming video GPU vs CPU encoding transcoding cloud comparison cost 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01FSPxdfvbdeRtv1b8z8WLve","uuid":"5c05ae23-581c-4aee-b2c2-0d77393d2727","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:26:17.833Z"}
{"parentUuid":"5c05ae23-581c-4aee-b2c2-0d77393d2727","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"streaming video GPU vs CPU encoding transcoding cloud comparison cost 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01V6gTcHCXjTC6YAB32T1L7t","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01FSPxdfvbdeRtv1b8z8WLve","uuid":"8acaa8ae-8396-4f01-8115-37646447a3fc","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:26:21.615Z"}
{"parentUuid":"ddfcb573-ab27-4c68-8ff9-23ef27df58ea","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FSPxdfvbdeRtv1b8z8WLve","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"streaming video GPU vs CPU encoding transcoding cloud comparison cost 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"GPU vs CPU Transcoding: Which One Delivers Better Streaming Performance\",\"url\":\"https://antmedia.io/gpu-vs-cpu-transcoding-for-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"CPU vs. GPU for Video Transcoding: Challenging the Cost-Speed Video Encoding Myth\",\"url\":\"https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/cpu-vs-gpu-video-transcoding-challenging-cost-speed-myth-mirza-bilal-vvznf\"},{\"title\":\"GPU vs CPU. How to Cut Live Streaming & AI Processing Costs?\",\"url\":\"https://www.red5.net/blog/gpu-vs-cpu-how-to-cut-live-streaming-ai-processing-costs/\"},{\"title\":\"CPU vs GPU for Video Transcoding: Challenging the Cost-Speed Myth\",\"url\":\"https://mirzabilal.com/cpu-vs-gpu-for-video-transcoding-challenging-the-cost-speed-myth\"},{\"title\":\"Why Encoder Compute Efficiency is Being Measured by Everyone - NETINT Technologies\",\"url\":\"https://netint.com/why-encoder-compute-efficiency-is-being-measured-by-everyone/\"},{\"title\":\"Optimizing video encoding with FFmpeg using NVIDIA GPU-based Amazon EC2 instances | Amazon Web Services\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/compute/optimizing-video-encoding-with-ffmpeg-using-nvidia-gpu-based-amazon-ec2-instances/\"},{\"title\":\"Cloud Video Encoding vs Transcoding [2024 Update] | Coconut©\",\"url\":\"https://www.coconut.co/articles/cloud-video-encoding-vs-transcoding-2024-update\"},{\"title\":\"Boosting Video Streaming: Efficient Transcoding for Better Performance & Cost\",\"url\":\"https://netint.com/efficient-transcoding-for-better-performance-cost/\"},{\"title\":\"CPU against GPU: Fighting Video Encoding | Coconut©\",\"url\":\"https://www.coconut.co/articles/cpu-vs-gpu-video-encoding-battle\"},{\"title\":\"CPU or CPU+GPU Processing for Video & Image Transcoding - Cinnafilm\",\"url\":\"https://cinnafilm.com/cpu-or-cpugpu-processing-how-can-i-achieve-quality-transcoding-and-image-processing-in-the-cloud/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of the **GPU vs. CPU encoding/transcoding for streaming video in the cloud**, based on the latest comparisons and benchmarks:\n\n---\n\n## GPU vs. CPU Encoding & Transcoding: Cloud Cost & Performance Comparison (2024–2025)\n\n### Speed & Scalability\n\nThe primary advantage of GPU transcoding is speed and scalability. Hardware-accelerated encoders enable real-time or near–real-time processing while consuming less power per stream, making GPUs ideal for live streaming, cloud-based video platforms, and high-throughput workloads.\n\nGPUs process multiple video frames simultaneously, drastically reducing encoding times. Many GPUs come with dedicated video encoding/decoding hardware, such as NVIDIA NVENC or AMD VCE.\n\nIn contrast, CPUs are not optimized for parallel processing, making encoding slower compared to GPUs.\n\n### Quality & Flexibility\n\nOne of the main strengths of CPU transcoding is its high output quality and flexibility. CPU encoders offer fine control over compression settings, motion estimation, and bitrate optimization, often resulting in better visual quality at lower bitrates.\n\nCPU encoders do a particularly good job with containing output file sizes for most tested cases, producing smaller output file sizes even when perceived quality is similar. This is an important aspect since it can have a big impact in cost — depending on the amount of media files distributed, data transfer and storage cost will noticeably increase if GPUs are used.\n\n### Cloud Cost Benchmarks (AWS)\n\nThe performance of batch encoding in the best GPU instance (g4dn.xlarge) shows around 73% better price/performance in x264 compared to the c6i.4xlarge and around 82% improvement in x265.\n\nFor streaming use cases, a GPU-based instance family like g4dn can sustain up to 4 parallel encodings from 4K to multiple output resolutions simultaneously. However, the GPU-based p5 family performance does not compensate for the cost increase. Meanwhile, CPU-based instances can sustain 1 parallel stream at most.\n\nAn independent benchmark underscores that in video transcoding, modern GPU instances aren't just faster; they also offer a more economical choice. When choosing between a CPU or GPU for cloud-based operations, it's essential to consider both performance and cost. As demonstrated, sometimes the supposedly \"faster and pricier\" option can also be the most cost-effective.\n\n### GPU Cloud Pricing Disparities (2025)\n\nThe costs of GPU instances and clusters vary greatly among hyperscalers. For example, in 2025, the per-instance hourly cost for an eight-GPU cluster of NVIDIA H100 (80GB) was $88.49 on Google Cloud Platform, $55.04 on AWS, and $98.32 on Microsoft Azure. Oracle Cloud Infrastructure offers an 8× H100 bare-metal node priced at US $80.00/hour (US $10.00 per GPU-hour).\n\nGPU or related commodity hardware accelerator costs are in a highly volatile state as options multiply with AMD, Intel, and ever more entrants looking to dent NVIDIA's dominance.\n\n### The Rise of ASICs as a Third Option\n\nBeyond GPUs and CPUs, ASIC-based solutions are emerging as a compelling alternative. In the past, CPUs were the most common solution for high-volume transcoding. However, CPUs were found to be inefficient for video transcoding, especially with new video codecs like HEVC, leading companies to consider GPUs, FPGAs, and ASICs.\n\nNETINT's ASIC-based transcoders slashed api.video's encoding costs, enabling it to provide free transcoding to all its customers.\n\n### Codec Considerations\n\nAs codecs evolve, they tend to become more computationally intensive. For instance, AV1 offers superior compression efficiency compared to H.264 and HEVC but requires significantly more processing power. Selecting a transcoder that can handle current and future codec demands ensures long-term cost efficiency and scalability.\n\n### When to Use CPU vs. GPU\n\nIf it's just simple transcoding, CPU-based technologies that scale to use free or highly reduced compute platforms will probably do just fine. But for tasks like up-resing, deinterlacing, frame rate conversion, standards conversion, or HDR conversion, the value of leveraging both CPU and GPU compute power becomes self-evident.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Factor | CPU | GPU |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Speed** | Slower (sequential) | Much faster (parallel) |\n| **Quality** | Higher at low bitrates | Comparable (improving) |\n| **File Size** | Smaller output | Larger output |\n| **Cost/Stream (Cloud)** | Higher at scale | Lower at scale (73–82% savings) |\n| **Power Efficiency** | Lower | Higher |\n| **Best For** | Quality-critical, low-volume | Live streaming, high-throughput |\n| **Scalability** | Expensive to scale | Excellent |\n\nThe consensus from recent benchmarks is clear: **for most cloud-based streaming and live transcoding workloads, GPU instances now offer both faster performance and better cost-efficiency than CPU-only instances**, though CPU encoding still holds an edge for maximum quality control and smaller output file sizes. Additionally, ASIC-based solutions are emerging as the most power-efficient and cost-effective option for very high-volume transcoding.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"93fdb51c-48dc-4bf6-ac0d-40c310236465","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:26:56.630Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ddfcb573-ab27-4c68-8ff9-23ef27df58ea"}
