{"parentUuid":"eebe39e4-41f7-4490-b78b-9f8d2d06796a","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"LL-HLS low latency HLS implementation production streaming 2024 2025 partial segments"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01ACAKy97KzDH3SQuPCvvVzR","uuid":"cd31bb65-8113-4c18-89ea-f339c7db4cd3","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:27:00.241Z"}
{"parentUuid":"cd31bb65-8113-4c18-89ea-f339c7db4cd3","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"LL-HLS low latency HLS implementation production streaming 2024 2025 partial segments"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01WQAcJ3pSzd7wU3i78werFW","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01ACAKy97KzDH3SQuPCvvVzR","uuid":"fb3098c3-318c-4ead-b08e-e8e71f8c7f4c","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:27:01.735Z"}
{"parentUuid":"d085f004-410b-4ed7-bf94-9877547c9b77","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ACAKy97KzDH3SQuPCvvVzR","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"LL-HLS low latency HLS implementation production streaming 2024 2025 partial segments\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"HLS Low Latency: The Ultimate 2025 Guide for Real-Time Streaming - VideoSDK\",\"url\":\"https://www.videosdk.live/developer-hub/hls/hls-low-latency\"},{\"title\":\"LL-HLS Tutorial: Low-Latency HLS Streaming Guide (2-5s)\",\"url\":\"https://antmedia.io/low-latency-hls-or-ll-hls/\"},{\"title\":\"Low-Latency HLS: The Era of Flexible Low-Latency Streaming | by OvenMediaEngine | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@OvenMediaEngine/low-latency-hls-the-era-of-flexible-low-latency-streaming-ec675aa61378\"},{\"title\":\"An update on Low Latency HLS live streaming | Mux\",\"url\":\"https://www.mux.com/blog/low-latency-hls-part-2\"},{\"title\":\"Introduction to Low Latency Streaming with HLS\",\"url\":\"https://www.100ms.live/blog/hls-low-latency-streaming\"},{\"title\":\"Low Latency HLS with CDN: The Ultimate Production Guide\",\"url\":\"https://blog.cdnsun.com/low-latency-hls-with-cdn-the-ultimate-production-guide/\"},{\"title\":\"Introducing Low-Latency HLS Support for Cloudflare Stream\",\"url\":\"https://blog.cloudflare.com/low-latency-hls-support-for-cloudflare-stream/\"},{\"title\":\"How to Optimize LL-HLS for Low Latency Streaming | Dolby OptiView\",\"url\":\"https://optiview.dolby.com/resources/blog/streaming/how-to-optimize-ll-hls-for-low-latency-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"How to configure a low-latency HLS workflow using AWS Media Services | Amazon Web Services\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/how-to-configure-a-low-latency-hls-workflow-using-aws-media-services/\"},{\"title\":\"LL-HLS vs HLS vs LL-DASH: Low-Latency Streaming Compared in 2024 | Teyuto Documentations\",\"url\":\"https://docs.teyuto.com/blog/what-is-low-latency-http-live-streaming-ll-hls-vs-hls-vs-ll-dash\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of **LL-HLS (Low-Latency HLS) implementation for production streaming**, based on the latest information from 2024–2025:\n\n---\n\n## What is LL-HLS?\n\nLow-Latency HLS (LL-HLS) emerged to address latency issues in traditional HLS, debuting as a draft in 2019 and maturing through 2025. Classic HLS was reliable but suffered from high latency due to large segment sizes and playlist update intervals, meaning viewers could experience delays upwards of 30 seconds—unacceptable for interactive or real-time events.\n\n## Key Technical Innovations\n\n### Partial Segments (Parts)\nLL-HLS introduces partial segments (parts)—sub-segment chunks, typically 200–500 ms—allowing the player to start downloading data almost as soon as it is encoded. Segments are typically 1–2 seconds, and partial segments (parts) may be 200–400ms for ultra-low latency.\n\n### Blocking Playlist Reload\nClients use playlist requests that \"wait\" until new media is available, reducing polling frequency and enabling quicker segment delivery.\n\n### Preload Hints\nThe playlist announces the URL of upcoming parts before they exist, enabling the player to send an HTTP request that the server (and CDN edge) holds open until the data is ready. The latest revision of the specification replaces the HTTP/2 PUSH with a new prefetch behaviour signalled by a new tag in the HLS playlist — `EXT-X-PRELOAD-HINT`.\n\n### Playlist Delta Updates\nThe playlist is updated in LL-HLS with less transfer cost as compared to HLS. This is done by requesting the server to provide delta updates, which update the relevant portions of the playlist already available with the client.\n\n### Rendition Reports\nLL-HLS minimizes the number of roundtrips during bit-rate adaptation by adding `EXT-X-RENDITION-REPORT` tags for all media playlists in a multivariant playlist. These tags provide information such as the last Media Sequence Number and Part currently in the Media Playlist, so the client can request required parts from the server without having to fetch an entirely new Media Playlist.\n\n## Latency Achievements\n\nThe result is dramatically reduced live streaming latency, often as low as 2–5 seconds, while retaining the scalability and reliability of traditional HLS. Using OvenMediaEngine, they achieved a latency of approximately 1 to 4 seconds.\n\n## CMAF Interoperability\n\nApple's LL-HLS specification is tightly integrated with CMAF (Common Media Application Format), which enables chunked transfer encoding and standardized segmenting. A side effect of the specification changes is that Apple's specification has now become much more closely interoperable with MPEG DASH-LL.\n\n## Production CDN Considerations\n\nA general checklist for any CDN is to use HTTP/2 or HTTP/3 on the edge, since LL-HLS generates many small HTTP requests (playlist fetches and parts), and HTTP/2/3 multiplexing prevents head-of-line blocking and reduces connection overhead.\n\nKey CDN tuning:\n- Playlists (.m3u8) should have very short TTLs or be marked with `Cache-Control: no-store` or `max-age=0, must-revalidate` so players always see the latest segments. Media parts and segments (.m4s) should be cached aggressively with a longer TTL because they are immutable and requested many times.\n- Enabling origin shield/mid-tier caching reduces load on the origin when many edge locations request the same parts simultaneously.\n\n## Production Platforms & Players\n\nModern HLS players (hls.js, Video.js, Safari native) and servers (AWS Elemental, Oryx, Wowza) support LL-HLS extensions, but compatibility varies across devices and browsers.\n\nNotable production implementations:\n- **Cloudflare Stream**: Cloudflare introduced support for LL-HLS in a closed beta, offering reduced latency from highs of around 30 seconds to less than 10 in many cases.\n- **AWS Media Services**: AWS offers LL-HLS as an extension of the protocol that appeared in 2020 in the 2nd edition of the specification, enabling low-latency video streaming while maintaining scalability.\n- **OvenMediaEngine**: OvenMediaEngine (OME) is an open-source, low-latency streaming server that uses WebRTC and LL-HLS.\n- **Ant Media Server**: Claims to reduce HLS latency from 30s to 2–5s with a complete guide covering installation, configuration, and player integration.\n\n## Backward Compatibility\n\nOne of the main advantages of using LL-HLS is its backward compatibility with legacy HLS players. Players that don't support this variant may fall back to standard HLS and still work with higher latency. Players that don't support LL-HLS yet tend to ignore tags like `EXT-X-PART` and `EXT-X-PRELOAD-HINT`, enabling them to treat the playlist with the traditional HLS and load segments at a higher latency.\n\n## Open Range Request Optimization\n\nWhen working in an interoperable mode with DASH-LL, an LL-HLS client can issue an open-ended byte range request against the start of a part of a segment. The origin blocks until the first part is available, releasing it via CDN to the client, and the client can continue to use that open-ended range request, waiting for the next part while transferring the just-downloaded part into the MSE buffer.\n\n---\n\nIn summary, LL-HLS has matured significantly by 2025 into a production-ready, scalable low-latency streaming solution with broad ecosystem support, achieving 2–5 second glass-to-glass latency through partial segments, preload hints, blocking playlist reloads, and tight CDN integration.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"300bf7d5-f140-4a91-91b4-e009846e6cf1","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:27:39.701Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d085f004-410b-4ed7-bf94-9877547c9b77"}
