{"parentUuid":"ca9adbd5-bf9e-41c5-bbd0-009b98f2cc0b","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SUH8hA5B65MGCkcqaHft4p","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Netflix engineering blog 2025 2026 video streaming technology conference talks\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Netflix Live Origin. Xiaomei Liu, Joseph Lynch, Chris Newton | by Netflix Technology Blog | Dec, 2025 | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/netflix-live-origin-41f1b0ad5371\"},{\"title\":\"From On-Demand to Live : Netflix Streaming to 100 Million Devices in under 1 Minute - InfoQ\",\"url\":\"https://www.infoq.com/news/2025/12/netflix-live-streaming-pipeline/\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix’s Engineering Culture - by Gergely Orosz\",\"url\":\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/netflix\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Details Its Live Streaming Infrastructure and What They Learned While Building It\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamingmediablog.com/2025/07/netflix-live-infrastructure.html\"},{\"title\":\"2025 Data Engineering Open Forum at Netflix\",\"url\":\"https://2025dataengineeringopenforumat.splashthat.com/\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Technology Blog – Medium\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.medium.com/\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Architecture: A Deep Dive into Seamless Global Streaming\",\"url\":\"https://talent500.com/blog/netflix-streaming-architecture-explained/\"},{\"title\":\"How Netflix is Reimagining Data Engineering for Video, Audio, and Text - InfoQ\",\"url\":\"https://www.infoq.com/news/2025/08/netflix-ml-data-eng/\"},{\"title\":\"Behind the Streams: Building a Reliable Cloud Live Streaming Pipeline for Netflix. Part 2. | by Netflix Technology Blog | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/behind-the-streams-building-a-reliable-cloud-live-streaming-pipeline-for-netflix-part-2-8627c608c967\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix TechBlog posts on daily.dev\",\"url\":\"https://app.daily.dev/sources/netflix\"}]\n\nHere are the results from the search on **Netflix engineering blog 2025–2026 video streaming technology conference talks**:\n\n---\n\n## Netflix Tech Blog – Live Streaming Architecture\n\n### 1. **Netflix Live Origin** (December 2025)\nThe \"Behind the Streams\" series introduced the architecture of Netflix's streaming pipeline, and a December 2025 blog post focuses on the custom Origin Server built for Live — the Netflix Live Origin. It sits at the demarcation point between the cloud live streaming pipelines and Open Connect, Netflix's in-house CDN, acting as a broker for what content reaches client devices.\n\nKey technical details include:\n- The KeyValue Payload Chunking and Compression Algorithm breaks work down so each part can be idempotently retried and hedged to maintain strict latency SLOs. Combined with Apache Cassandra's local-quorum consistency model and LSM storage engine, Netflix achieved write availability with a P99 tail latency similar to the previous P50 average latency.\n- To handle read storms, Netflix introduced write-through caching using EVCache (based on Memcached), allowing almost all reads to be served from a highly scalable cache, easily hitting 200Gbps and beyond without affecting the write path.\n\n### 2. **Behind the Streams: Building a Reliable Cloud Live Streaming Pipeline – Part 2** (September 2025)\nWhen Netflix started exploring live streaming, the goal was to deliver a live experience reaching as many Netflix-supported devices as possible and meet or exceed industry standards for quality and latency, despite the absence of existing broadcast infrastructure.\n\n- Netflix adopted a hub-and-spoke model that aggregates production feeds at a well-connected broadcast facility before cloud ingestion. Cloud ingest operates in two separate regions, each receiving feeds through two distinct, managed direct network paths.\n- As content expanded to sports, reality, and awards shows, Netflix utilized its orchestration service to create customized encoding pipelines for each event — from Chris Rock: Selective Outrage in UHD at 30 fps, to back-to-back NFL Christmas Gameday streams in HD at 59.94 fps with four audio languages and ad support.\n\n---\n\n## Coverage & Analysis from InfoQ\n\n### 3. **From On-Demand to Live: Netflix Streaming to 100 Million Devices** (InfoQ, December 2025)\nNetflix's global live streaming platform powers millions of viewers with cloud-based ingest, custom live origin, Open Connect delivery, and real-time recommendations. The article explores the architecture, low-latency pipelines, adaptive bitrate streaming, and operational monitoring behind reliable live event experiences.\n\n### 4. **How Netflix is Reimagining Data Engineering for Video, Audio, and Text** (InfoQ, August 2025)\nNetflix introduced a new engineering specialization — Media ML Data Engineering — alongside a Media Data Lake designed to handle video, audio, text, and image assets at scale. Early results include richer ML models trained on standardized media, faster evaluation cycles, and deeper insights into creative workflows.\n\n---\n\n## Netflix-Hosted Conference\n\n### 5. **2025 Data Engineering Open Forum at Netflix** (April 23, 2025, Los Gatos, CA)\nNetflix hosted the Data Engineering Open Forum in person on April 23rd in Los Gatos, CA — a conference designed to unite data engineers for knowledge-sharing, learning, and networking, welcoming industry professionals, academic scholars, and emerging talent. This year featured more speakers and new formats including interactive panels and lightning talks.\n\nWhile Netflix did not live stream the event, they intended to upload the talks to their Netflix Data YouTube channel, with no RSVP required for accessing the recordings.\n\n---\n\n## Other Notable Items\n\n### 6. **Netflix's Engineering Culture** (Pragmatic Engineer, December 2025)\nNetflix CTO Elizabeth Stone shared how the company has no formal performance reviews, learns from failures, and builds at a global scale.\n\n### 7. **Netflix Live Streaming Infrastructure** (Streaming Media Blog, July 2025)\nNetflix builds support for a single product and has control over the full live lifecycle, from production to screen. They leverage AWS MediaConnect and AWS MediaLive to acquire feeds in the cloud and transcode them, with their cloud-based approach enabling dynamic scaling, flexibility, and seamless integration with DRM, content management, and CDN services.\n\n---\n\n### Upcoming Conference Mention\nQCon London (March 16–19, 2026) is highlighted as a venue for actionable insights and strategic perspectives on enterprise challenges, and is likely to feature Netflix-related engineering content based on past years.\n\nThese results paint a picture of Netflix's significant engineering investment in live streaming infrastructure throughout 2025, with multiple detailed blog posts and conference events documenting their technology.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"62af9b1f-bc36-4ffa-99ea-602dd866c971","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:28:10.640Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ca9adbd5-bf9e-41c5-bbd0-009b98f2cc0b"}
