{"parentUuid":"2a5f1d08-8767-4994-bfc0-2405dbdf6360","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PreToolUse","hookName":"PreToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/pretooluse.py"},"toolUseID":"toolu_01QH4TjmJXkYGnZ7ygN5F4io","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01QH4TjmJXkYGnZ7ygN5F4io","uuid":"df9bc881-e103-4da9-b9b1-312837e93f2a","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:28:12.619Z"}
{"parentUuid":"df9bc881-e103-4da9-b9b1-312837e93f2a","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"streaming fault tolerance failover live video redundancy pipeline architecture 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01QH4TjmJXkYGnZ7ygN5F4io","uuid":"38ebefe4-f87a-4493-9ece-f195c279e538","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:28:14.948Z"}
{"parentUuid":"38ebefe4-f87a-4493-9ece-f195c279e538","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"streaming fault tolerance failover live video redundancy pipeline architecture 2024 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_0163VcpgnYiGLemHHYGwm89o","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01QH4TjmJXkYGnZ7ygN5F4io","uuid":"183adefd-e417-45a4-8cba-39d751e73437","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:28:17.416Z"}
{"parentUuid":"2a5f1d08-8767-4994-bfc0-2405dbdf6360","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QH4TjmJXkYGnZ7ygN5F4io","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"streaming fault tolerance failover live video redundancy pipeline architecture 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Supporting server-level fault tolerance in concurrent-push-based parallel video servers | IEEE Journals & Magazine | IEEE Xplore\",\"url\":\"https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/iel5/76/19344/00894280.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"The evolution of real-time data streaming: Architectures ...\",\"url\":\"https://journalwjarr.com/sites/default/files/fulltext_pdf/WJARR-2025-1746.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Fault Tolerance of Real-time Video Streaming Protocols over SDN Networks | IEEE Conference Publication | IEEE Xplore\",\"url\":\"https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/8450440/\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Fault Tolerance of Real-time Video Streaming Protocols over SDN Networks\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/327328113_Fault_Tolerance_of_Real-time_Video_Streaming_Protocols_over_SDN_Networks\"},{\"title\":\"A Decentralized Multi-Venue Real-Time Video Broadcasting System Integrating Chain Topology and Intelligent Self-Healing Mechanisms\",\"url\":\"https://www.mdpi.com/2076-3417/15/14/8043\"},{\"title\":\"Streaming Data Architecture in 2024: Components and Examples - RisingWave: Real-Time Event Streaming Platform\",\"url\":\"https://risingwave.com/blog/streaming-data-architecture-in-2024-components-and-examples/\"},{\"title\":\"Fault Tolerance Strategies for Low-Latency Live Video Streaming - ProQuest\",\"url\":\"https://www.proquest.com/openview/712cc96101011c1745436a5c4ceb2b21/1?cbl=18750&diss=y&pq-origsite=gscholar\"},{\"title\":\"Improved Fault-tolerance and Zero Data Loss in Apache Spark Streaming\",\"url\":\"https://www.databricks.com/blog/2015/01/15/improved-driver-fault-tolerance-and-zero-data-loss-in-spark-streaming.html\"},{\"title\":\"Fault-Tolerant Storage for Streaming Data: Basics\",\"url\":\"https://www.serverion.com/uncategorized/fault-tolerant-storage-for-streaming-data-basics/\"},{\"title\":\"Spark Structured Streaming — Fault Tolerance | by Teepika R M | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://teepika-r-m.medium.com/fault-tolerance-in-spark-structured-streaming-6463c95e32cd\"}]\n\nHere's a summary of the most relevant findings on **streaming fault tolerance, failover, and live video redundancy pipeline architecture** from recent (2024–2025) research and industry resources:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Real-Time Data Streaming Architectures (2025)\n\nA 2025 paper in the *World Journal of Advanced Research and Reviews* covers the evolution of real-time data streaming architectures with a focus on fault tolerance:\n\n- Spark Streaming's fault tolerance model implements a deterministic replay mechanism that ensures processing reliability in distributed environments prone to partial failures. The framework maintains lineage information for all derived streaming datasets, enabling automatic reconstruction of lost data through deterministic recomputation when worker nodes fail.\n- Research demonstrates that implementing optimized checkpoint intervals based on workload recovery time objectives can reduce the recovery time following node failures by approximately 65% compared to default configurations.\n- Optimized Kafka deployments in cloud-native environments can achieve up to 99.995% availability when implementing multi-region replication strategies with appropriate network redundancy. This reliability is achieved through Kafka's sophisticated partition leadership management and replication protocol, where each partition maintains a designated leader responsible for handling read and write operations while replica nodes continuously synchronize. The architecture employs a quorum-based consensus mechanism that ensures data consistency even when individual nodes fail.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Decentralized Multi-Venue Real-Time Video Broadcasting with Self-Healing (2025)\n\nA recent paper published in *MDPI Applied Sciences* (July 2025) proposes a novel decentralized live video broadcasting system:\n\n- The system employs a peer-to-peer (P2P) chain topology based on IPv6 networking and the Secure Reliable Transport (SRT) protocol. By exploiting the global addressing capability of IPv6, the solution simplifies direct node interconnections, eliminating complexities associated with NAT. It introduces a chain-relay transmission method combined with distributed node management strategies, substantially reducing reliance on central servers.\n- A WebSocket-based real-time fault detection algorithm coupled with a rapid fallback self-healing mechanism enables millisecond-level fault detection and swift restoration of disrupted links. Performance evaluations confirm substantial improvements in latency, video quality stability, and fault tolerance over existing P2P methods, along with over tenfold enhancements in frame rates compared with conventional RTMP-based solutions.\n- The protocol benefits from an enhanced ARQ retransmission strategy that combines selective retransmission with Forward Error Correction (FEC). For critical video frames, such as I-frames and important P-frames, the system automatically adds redundant encoding. For regular data packets, a rapid retransmission mechanism is employed.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Live Video Streaming Fault Tolerance over SDN Networks\n\nAn IEEE publication addresses fault tolerance specifically for real-time video streaming:\n\n- Video streaming protocols such as MPEG-DASH, HDS, and RTMP provide adaptive streaming capability and application-level fault tolerance to handle failures while providing uninterrupted live video streaming service.\n- Both transport layer and video streaming protocols have built-in fault tolerance mechanisms. Integrating streaming protocol's fault handling mechanism with the automatic network fault recovery would provide optimized video streaming performance.\n- SPIDER, based on stateful data plane abstractions such as OpenState or P4, offers guaranteed short (few milliseconds or less) failure detection and recovery delays, with a configurable trade-off between overhead and failover responsiveness.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Streaming Data Architecture Components (2024)\n\nA 2024 overview from RisingWave highlights key architectural principles:\n\n- Fault tolerance ensures the reliability of Streaming Data Architecture. The system continues functioning despite hardware or software failures. Redundant components and failover mechanisms enhance resilience.\n- Apache Kafka provides a powerful platform for managing high-performance data pipelines and real-time data processing. Amazon Kinesis offers a fully managed cloud-based service that handles large-scale real-time processing from diverse sources.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Fault-Tolerant Storage for Streaming Data\n\nA December 2025 guide from Serverion outlines practical fault-tolerance strategies:\n\n- Key methods include hardware redundancy (duplicate power supplies, network interfaces, storage controllers), mirroring (real-time synchronization between primary and backup systems), and network path redundancy (multiple network routes connecting storage nodes). Systems often maintain at least three copies of data across different physical locations, with automated recovery processes that kick in when a failure occurs.\n- Distributed storage systems spread data across multiple nodes to avoid a single point of failure. These systems use data replication and partitioning, including full replication (every node stores a complete copy), partial replication (only critical data is duplicated), and geographic replication (copies stored in different physical locations).\n- Redundancy, automated backups, failover mechanisms, and recovery processes ensure minimal downtime. Techniques like tiered storage, write-back caching, and horizontal scaling help systems grow while maintaining speed and reliability.\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n| Aspect | Modern Approach |\n|---|---|\n| **Protocol** | SRT, MPEG-DASH, RTMP with built-in adaptive failover |\n| **Fault Detection** | WebSocket-based, heartbeat signals, millisecond-level detection |\n| **Redundancy** | Multi-region replication, FEC for critical frames, erasure codes |\n| **Failover** | Automated path switching, self-healing chain-relay topologies |\n| **Data Integrity** | Exactly-once semantics (Kafka + Spark), write-ahead logs, checkpointing |\n| **Availability Target** | Up to 99.995% with optimized multi-region Kafka deployments |\n\nThese results reflect the state-of-the-art in building resilient, fault-tolerant live video streaming and data pipeline architectures as of 2024–2025.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"8de7287d-f746-410b-8240-bf21e8244fc6","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:28:45.260Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2a5f1d08-8767-4994-bfc0-2405dbdf6360"}
