{"parentUuid":"4e79487e-b58e-48b3-a155-71faf3c38972","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PreToolUse","hookName":"PreToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/pretooluse.py"},"toolUseID":"toolu_01Kd4XW4j2PbZfPCorafTd8W","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01Kd4XW4j2PbZfPCorafTd8W","uuid":"7dd4a1e2-a385-45c2-b441-868775c29649","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:29:17.936Z"}
{"parentUuid":"7dd4a1e2-a385-45c2-b441-868775c29649","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting AV1 HEVC multi-encode 2025 architecture"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01Kd4XW4j2PbZfPCorafTd8W","uuid":"68a514c7-2182-4ce4-8f9b-a077cf9e3773","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:29:20.834Z"}
{"parentUuid":"68a514c7-2182-4ce4-8f9b-a077cf9e3773","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting AV1 HEVC multi-encode 2025 architecture"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01KgCJqKudL7jG6qPYZv6GKG","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01Kd4XW4j2PbZfPCorafTd8W","uuid":"8f9e5598-5443-4e50-b5be-576e95c2fa15","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:29:22.888Z"}
{"parentUuid":"4e79487e-b58e-48b3-a155-71faf3c38972","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Kd4XW4j2PbZfPCorafTd8W","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting AV1 HEVC multi-encode 2025 architecture\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Introducing the Enhanced Broadcasting Beta\",\"url\":\"https://blog.twitch.tv/en/2024/01/08/introducing-the-enhanced-broadcasting-beta/\"},{\"title\":\"Enhanced Broadcasting with Multiple Encodes\",\"url\":\"https://help.twitch.tv/s/article/multiple-encodes?language=en_US\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting - Streamrun docs\",\"url\":\"https://streamrun.com/docs/twitch-enhanced-broadcasting\"},{\"title\":\"twitch-multiencode-av1-livestreaming\",\"url\":\"https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/geforce/news/gfecnt/20241/twitch-multiencode-av1-livestreaming/\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch, OBS & NVIDIA to Release Multi-Encode Livestreaming | NVIDIA Blog\",\"url\":\"https://blogs.nvidia.com/blog/twitch-multiencode-av1-livestreaming/\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch introduces multi-encode livestreaming and AV1 support - CSI Magazine\",\"url\":\"https://www.csimagazine.com/csi/Twitch-introduces-Enhanced-Broadcasting-and-AV1-support.php\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 or HEVC to Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting - Streamrun\",\"url\":\"https://streamrun.com/templates/av1-or-hevc-to-twitch-enhanced-broadcasting\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch’s Dual-Layout Streaming: Technical Innovation or Industry Revolution?\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamingmedia.com/Articles/News/Online-Video-News/Twitchs-Dual-Layout-Streaming-Technical-Innovation-or-Industry-Revolution-170053.aspx\"},{\"title\":\"AV1 Encoding for OBS Studio main releasE. For everyone - API - Twitch Developer Forums\",\"url\":\"https://discuss.dev.twitch.com/t/av1-encoding-for-obs-studio-main-release-for-everyone/59814\"},{\"title\":\"Twitch Enhanced Broadcast Adds NVIDIA HEVC Encoder Support | NVIDIA Blog\",\"url\":\"https://blogs.nvidia.com/blog/studio-twitch-enhanced-broadcasting-hevc-driver/\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of **Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting** and its architecture involving AV1, HEVC, and multi-encode capabilities:\n\n## Overview\n\nTwitch, OBS, and NVIDIA are leveling up livestreaming technology with the new Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting beta, powered by GeForce RTX GPUs. Streamers are able to stream multiple encodes concurrently, providing optimal viewing experiences for all viewers.\n\n## The Problem It Solves\n\nToday, many streamers must choose between higher resolution and reliable streaming. High-quality video provides more enjoyable viewing experiences but causes streams to buffer for viewers with low bandwidth or older viewing devices. Streaming lower-bitrate video allows more people to watch the content seamlessly, but introduces artifacts.\n\n## Architecture & How It Works\n\nThis is built on Twitch's Enhanced Broadcasting architecture, which shifts encoding to the creator and avoids duplicative server-side processing. That makes dual-format delivery viable at scale, something no other major platform has accomplished for live content.\n\n- **Multi-encode approach:** This is done by streaming with multiple resolutions, bitrates, and codecs from the streamer to viewers, who have varying network conditions and device capabilities.\n- **Automatic configuration:** Enhanced Broadcasting will automatically configure all OBS encoder settings, including resolution, bit rate and encoding parameters. A server-side algorithm will return the best possible configuration for OBS Studio based on the streamer's setup, taking the headaches out of tuning settings for the best viewer experiences.\n- **NVENC hardware encoding:** Using the dedicated NVENC hardware encoder, streamers can achieve the highest quality video across streaming bitrates, with minimal impact to app and game performance.\n\n## Codec Support: AV1 & HEVC\n\nAV1 is the next generation of video encoding technology — 40% more efficient than the current AVC standard — and it will improve visual quality, and reduce bandwidth.\n\nEnhanced Broadcasting beta testers will be able to experiment with higher-input bit rates, up to 4K resolutions, up to 5 concurrent streams, as well as new codecs. The new codecs include the latest-generation AV1 for GeForce RTX 40 Series GPUs, which provides 40% more encoding efficiency than H.264, and HEVC for previous-generation GeForce GPUs.\n\n## Current Status (2025)\n\nHigher resolutions and modern codecs (AV1 and HEVC) are being tested with the TEB Beta Community, as of June 2025.\n\nSome features, like AV1 codec and HEVC codec and high resolutions (1440p and 4K) are currently being tested by selected streamers in the TEB Beta community. Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting is available for anyone who wants to stream with multiple resolutions up to Full HD with the H.264 codec.\n\nRegarding AV1 playback specifically, Twitch stated: \"Long term, we're excited about the improved codec efficiency offered by both HEVC and AV1. However, we're hyper-conscious of practical device compatibility. We want viewers to have great experiences, which means waiting to enable AV1 codec support until there is a significant enough portion of devices that have robust and efficient AV1 decode support.\"\n\nTwitch also confirmed that VP9 will not be used for any streams with Enhanced Broadcasting or dual-layout delivery.\n\n## Enhanced RTMP Protocol\n\nThe underlying protocol supports modern video codecs (VP8, VP9, HEVC, AV1), modern audio codecs (AC-3, E-AC-3, Opus, FLAC), and multitrack video, allowing different resolutions and qualities to be streamed simultaneously over separate ERTMP tracks.\n\nAs steering committee members of the Veovera Software Organization, Twitch is driving industry collaboration to make the Enhanced RTMP Multitrack Feature specification available to the entire live streaming ecosystem.\n\n## Software & Hardware Requirements\n\n- TEB can be used with OBS, XSplit, and Streamrun.\n- System requirements for Enhanced Broadcasting include a supported GPU (typically NVIDIA RTX-class hardware), and a stable upload speed of at least 12 Mbps.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"436b4435-2521-40ca-adc2-18e33b062aa2","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:29:52.111Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4e79487e-b58e-48b3-a155-71faf3c38972"}
