{"parentUuid":"57661938-c1ee-4064-afd4-de8610778bb7","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"Google YouTube custom video encoding hardware Argos VCU chip transcoding infrastructure"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01YbSFP9Pf4uikr7h34xsgf7","uuid":"7924233d-89fa-45db-bfb9-915dd5e3d572","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:30:24.529Z"}
{"parentUuid":"7924233d-89fa-45db-bfb9-915dd5e3d572","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Google YouTube custom video encoding hardware Argos VCU chip transcoding infrastructure"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_015imRK5JHfocAqLwvmHEBGr","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01YbSFP9Pf4uikr7h34xsgf7","uuid":"9264028b-e2ce-45b0-98dc-6b2140e2879d","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:30:26.578Z"}
{"parentUuid":"adae3c80-fc90-4456-a9b9-59e51e0869a5","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YbSFP9Pf4uikr7h34xsgf7","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Google YouTube custom video encoding hardware Argos VCU chip transcoding infrastructure\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Google develops custom 'Argos' video-transcoding chips for YouTube processing - DCD\",\"url\":\"https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/google-develops-custom-argos-video-transcoding-chips-for-youtube-processing/\"},{\"title\":\"Google is building custom silicon for YouTube video transcoding | TechSpot\",\"url\":\"https://www.techspot.com/news/89468-google-building-custom-silicon-youtube-video-transcoding.html\"},{\"title\":\"Google-developed 'Argos' VCU chip helps YouTube process videos much more efficiently\",\"url\":\"https://9to5google.com/2021/04/22/youtube-google-custom-chip/\"},{\"title\":\"Google’s New Custom Data Center Chip (VCU) Improves YouTube Videos\",\"url\":\"https://www.datacenterknowledge.com/data-center-chips/google-s-new-custom-data-center-chip-improves-youtube-videos\"},{\"title\":\"Google Reveals 'Argos' As YouTube's Own Video-Transcoding Chips | Eyerys\",\"url\":\"https://www.eyerys.com/articles/timeline/google-reveals-argos-youtubes-own-video-transcoding-chips\"},{\"title\":\"Youtube to Make Its Own Video Server Chip. | Semiconductor Materials and Equipment\",\"url\":\"https://abachy.com/news/youtube-make-its-own-video-server-chip\"},{\"title\":\"YouTube Updates Server Infrastructure With Custom ASICs for Video Transcoding | TechPowerUp\",\"url\":\"https://www.techpowerup.com/281518/youtube-updates-server-infrastructure-with-custom-asics-for-video-transcoding\"},{\"title\":\"Google Powers YouTube With Its Own Video-Transcoding Chips - MarkTechPost\",\"url\":\"https://www.marktechpost.com/2021/06/12/google-powers-youtube-with-its-own-video-transcoding-chips/\"},{\"title\":\"Google Argos - NETINT technologies\",\"url\":\"https://netint.com/tag/google-argos/\"},{\"title\":\"Argos for the Rest of Us — With AV1 | by NETINT Technologies | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@mt_32873/argos-for-the-rest-of-us-with-av1-a07928ecf0d6\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of Google's custom **Argos VCU** chip for YouTube video transcoding:\n\n## Background & Motivation\n\nGoogle engineers began building a custom chip for transcoding video in 2015, when YouTube noted rising demand for higher-quality video, such as 1080p and 4K. To meet demand, it needed to shift to more data-efficient video codecs. A team of about 100 Google engineers designed the first-generation chips, led under the oversight of Scott Silver, the Google VP of engineering who oversees YouTube's infrastructure.\n\nTranscoding is no small task for the company, as casual users and creators upload more than 500 hours of video content per minute, and people are spending more time watching videos and livestreams with every passing year. Data-efficient video codecs like VP9 use five times more compute resources to encode than the widely used H.264 format.\n\n## What Is the Argos VCU?\n\nYouTube developed custom chips, ASICs, called VCUs or Video (trans)Coding Units. The video-streaming giant detailed its approach for \"reimagining video infrastructure,\" saying it built a video coding unit (VCU) called 'Argos' to deliver the best video quality and keep users from consuming too much data.\n\nThe VCU lets YouTube transcode a single video into over a dozen versions, which helps YouTube to have a smooth, bandwidth-efficient, and profitable video platform.\n\n## Hardware Specifications\n\n- The VCU is a full-length PCIe card that hosts two Argos chips cooled by a rather large aluminum heatsink, and seems to only need one 8-pin power connector for additional power, similar to what we typically see on mid-range graphics cards.\n- Each Argos chip has 10 cores which Google says are \"off-the-shelf IP cores\" that connect to six external LPDDR4-3200 RAM chips over four channels, for a total capacity of 8 GB dedicated for each Argos ASIC.\n- Each core is capable of encoding a 2160p source in realtime at up to 60 frames per second using three reference frames.\n- The cards resemble GPUs because they fit in Google's existing accelerator trays.\n\n## Performance Gains\n\nThe introduction of Argos VCUs brought a performance boost of anywhere between 20 to 33 times when compared to Google's previous solution that relied on well-tuned software transcoding on traditional servers.\n\nThe VCU is 20 to 33 times more compute-efficient than Google's previous optimized system, which ran on traditional servers. The improvement takes into account performance and total cost of ownership over a three-year period, including the cost to design and build the custom chip, as well as the cost to run it in Google data centers.\n\nFor H.264 transcoding, a single VCU matches the speed of the baseline system while using about one-tenth of the system-level power. For VP9, a single 20-VCU machine replaces multiple racks of CPU-only systems.\n\n## Deployment\n\nThousands of Argos chips are currently running in Google data centers. Google runs dedicated VCU machines in its facilities with the new cards, rather than putting them in all YouTube servers.\n\nGoogle is deploying them in a relatively small cluster of dedicated machines inside YouTube's existing server system, which is based around Intel Skylake CPUs and Nvidia T4 Tensor Core GPUs.\n\nThe company said YouTube met a huge spike in usage during the pandemic thanks to this innovation.\n\n## Impact & Broader Significance\n\nThe first version of the Argos chip aimed to take the existing video workload that YouTube was transcoding and complete it more cheaply. Those savings allowed YouTube to begin transcoding many more videos into superior video encoding formats that use considerably less data but offer the same image quality. Smaller files carry enormous benefits: They cost less to store and serve, they allow carriers to use less bandwidth and they deliver faster load times to consumers.\n\nTo stay ahead of this workload, Google designed their own ASIC, which enabled them to eliminate millions of Intel CPUs.\n\n## Next Generation\n\nGoogle has already developed a second-generation VCU chip that supports the AV1 codec, a next-generation standard that delivers even higher-quality video, with less buffering for users.\n\nThe VCU (named \"Argos\" internally) isn't the first custom data center chip Google has designed. The two others it's talked about publicly are the Tensor Processing Unit (TPU), an ASIC for AI workloads, and the Titan chip for security.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"a2b35029-0a23-483d-8649-98d51a34893f","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:31:02.593Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"adae3c80-fc90-4456-a9b9-59e51e0869a5"}
