{"parentUuid":"38c68715-8d59-4e57-b187-9b3488458e02","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Netflix Java Spring Boot microservices technology stack backend language 2025"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01RwQsTsQ7jLNDfBH1ug9RM9","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01VhYgvLGMxuU6SC8eKBYNHg","uuid":"76b0a83c-c0dc-41df-9501-886dc94a43a0","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:31:08.121Z"}
{"parentUuid":"ff59cce8-e99d-40dd-aadc-a06db2635cd1","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VhYgvLGMxuU6SC8eKBYNHg","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Netflix Java Spring Boot microservices technology stack backend language 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Netflix adopts Spring Boot as its core Java framework\",\"url\":\"https://www.packtpub.com/en-us/learning/how-to-tutorials/netflix-adopts-spring-boot-as-its-core-java-framework\"},{\"title\":\"How Netflix Powers Its Backend with Modern Java\",\"url\":\"https://talent500.com/blog/netflix-java-backend-architecture/\"},{\"title\":\"How Netflix Really Uses Java - InfoQ\",\"url\":\"https://www.infoq.com/presentations/netflix-java/\"},{\"title\":\"How Java Powers Netflix’s Backend Architecture (2025 Edition) | by Aditya Banerjee | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@adityabanerjee1406/how-java-powers-netflixs-backend-architecture-2025-edition-172e961af3ec\"},{\"title\":\"How Netflix Runs on Java?\",\"url\":\"https://blog.bytebytego.com/p/how-netflix-runs-on-java\"},{\"title\":\"Deep Dive: How Netflix Uses Spring Boot for High-Scale Microservices | by Balian's Deep Tech | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@ShantKhayalian/deep-dive-how-netflix-uses-spring-boot-for-high-scale-microservices-30315235818c\"},{\"title\":\"Inside Netflix’s Architecture: How It Handles Billions of Views Seamlessly\",\"url\":\"https://rockybhatia.substack.com/p/inside-netflixs-architecture-how\"},{\"title\":\"Netflix Tech Stack Explained: CDN (Open Connect), and Microservices\",\"url\":\"https://www.vdocipher.com/blog/netflix-tech-stack-and-architecture/\"},{\"title\":\"Does Netflix use Node or Java?\",\"url\":\"https://www.designgurus.io/answers/detail/does-netflix-use-node-or-java\"},{\"title\":\"How Java is used by Netflix and its microservices\",\"url\":\"https://www.linkedin.com/posts/alexxubyte_systemdesign-coding-interviewtips-activity-7183487056805789697-18w4\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of how Netflix uses Java, Spring Boot, and microservices in its backend technology stack as of 2025:\n\n## Netflix's Java & Spring Boot Backend Architecture (2025)\n\n### Primary Language: Java\n\nJava is the primary language for Netflix's backend services. While other languages like Go and Python are used in specific domains (e.g., low-level platform code and machine learning), Java remains dominant due to its ecosystem, performance, and maturity.\n\nThe majority of Netflix's backend services run on Java. This might surprise engineers who've watched the rise of Kotlin, Go, Rust, and reactive frameworks. But Netflix isn't sticking with Java out of inertia — Java has matured, and so has the ecosystem around it.\n\n### Spring Boot as the Core Framework\n\nNetflix standardizes backend services on a customized Spring Boot stack, integrating company-specific modules for security, observability, service mesh, gRPC, dynamic configuration, and retry logic.\n\nEvery Domain Graph Service (DGS) at Netflix is a Spring Boot application. The DGS framework itself is built as an extension of Spring Boot. Dependency injection, configuration, and lifecycle management are handled by Spring Boot. GraphQL resolvers are just annotated Spring components. Observability, security, retry logic, and service mesh integration are implemented using Spring's mechanisms.\n\n### Federated GraphQL Architecture\n\nAt the heart of Netflix's backend lies a federated GraphQL architecture. This is the primary abstraction through which all client applications interact with backend data. The model provides both flexibility and insulation. Every GraphQL query from a Netflix client — whether from a smart TV, phone, or browser — lands at a centralized API Gateway, which parses the query, decomposes it into subqueries, and routes those to the appropriate backend services. Each backend team owns a Domain Graph Service (DGS), which implements a slice of the overall GraphQL schema.\n\n### JDK Evolution & Migration\n\nNetflix pushed past the limits of Java 8 by aggressively upgrading its stack, not by rewriting it. It embraced Spring Boot as a foundation but extended it to meet the unique demands of a global streaming platform.\n\nThe move to Spring Boot 3 required migrating from `javax.*` to `jakarta.*` namespaces. It was a breaking change that affected many libraries. Rather than wait for external updates, Netflix built a Gradle plugin that performs bytecode transforms at artifact resolution time, allowing Spring Boot 2-era libraries to work on Spring Boot 3 without source changes.\n\nNetflix's Java architecture in 2025 exemplifies deliberate, ongoing optimization rather than reliance on legacy technology. By aggressively upgrading its stack, extending Spring Boot, adopting GraphQL, leveraging virtual threads, and tuning JVM infrastructure, Netflix continues to deliver scalable, resilient streaming services worldwide.\n\n### JVM Performance & Virtual Threads\n\nModern JVMs offer powerful garbage collectors. Spring Boot has become both extensible and reliable. And with the arrival of virtual threads and structured concurrency, Java is reclaiming its place in high-throughput, low-latency system design, without the overhead of reactive complexity.\n\n### Broader Technology Stack\n\n**Languages:** Java & Spring Boot for most microservices; Python & Go for machine learning and observability tools; gRPC & REST APIs for high-performance inter-service communication.\n\n**Data & Storage:** DynamoDB & Cassandra for NoSQL needs (user preferences, watch history, metadata); MySQL for transactional data like billing and payments; S3 & EBS for logs and assets; Apache Kafka & AWS Kinesis for event streaming and real-time analytics.\n\n**Infrastructure & DevOps:** Eureka for service discovery, Hystrix as a circuit breaker, Zipkin for distributed tracing, and Spinnaker for multi-cloud deployments.\n\n### Kotlin at Netflix\n\nSome teams at Netflix have been excited about Kotlin. The DGS framework itself is written in Kotlin, although it targets mostly Java apps. There are microservices written in Kotlin as well. However, the tooling investment required to support multiple languages makes it harder for platform teams. It's just a lot easier for platform teams if everyone is using Java — though that doesn't make Kotlin bad.\n\n### Microservices Architecture\n\nNetflix is one of the world's largest cloud-native microservices architectures, serving over 230 million users globally. Netflix follows a microservices-based architecture where independent services handle different functionalities such as user authentication, content discovery, streaming services, and billing/payments. Each microservice runs independently and communicates via APIs, ensuring high availability and scalability. This architecture allows Netflix to roll out updates seamlessly, preventing single points of failure.\n\nIn summary, Netflix's 2025 technology stack is anchored by **Java** and **Spring Boot** as the core backend framework, with a **federated GraphQL** architecture (via the DGS framework), modern JVM features like **virtual threads (JDK 21+)**, and a rich ecosystem of tools for observability, resilience, and deployment.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"e2450f13-bc59-43dd-add9-a02651d6454b","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:31:41.498Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ff59cce8-e99d-40dd-aadc-a06db2635cd1"}
