{"parentUuid":"4524073b-f9ea-4c19-96dd-40fe6e7a8f74","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Fh93Mi4QkAgyqLz1kz8Hx6","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"streaming video edge packaging just-in-time packaging origin architecture 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Netflix Live Origin. Xiaomei Liu, Joseph Lynch, Chris Newton | by Netflix Technology Blog | Dec, 2025 | Netflix TechBlog\",\"url\":\"https://netflixtechblog.com/netflix-live-origin-41f1b0ad5371\"},{\"title\":\"2025 Streaming CDN Trends: What CTOs Must Know\",\"url\":\"https://blog.blazingcdn.com/en-us/2025-streaming-cdn-trends-what-ctos-must-know\"},{\"title\":\"Streaming Media Delivery for VoD | Fastly\",\"url\":\"https://www.fastly.com/products/streaming-media/video-on-demand\"},{\"title\":\"Unified Packager - Unified Streaming\",\"url\":\"https://www.unified-streaming.com/products/unified-packager\"},{\"title\":\"The Role of Edge Computing in Video Streaming - Muvi One\",\"url\":\"https://www.muvi.com/blogs/role-of-edge-computing-in-video-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"What is Just in time encoding?\",\"url\":\"https://www.fastpix.io/blog/just-in-time-encoding\"},{\"title\":\"The Streaming Tsunami: Part 4 - Scaling From Origin To Edge - The Broadcast Bridge - Connecting IT to Broadcast\",\"url\":\"https://www.thebroadcastbridge.com/content/entry/19776/the-streaming-tsunami-part-4-scaling-from-origin-to-edge\"},{\"title\":\"Just-in-Time Video Packaging – AWS Elemental MediaPackage – Amazon Web Services\",\"url\":\"https://aws.amazon.com/mediapackage/\"},{\"title\":\"How Edge Computing and Open Caching are Shaping the Future of Video Delivery - NETINT Tech\",\"url\":\"https://netint.com/edge-computing-and-open-caching/\"},{\"title\":\"Revolutionizing content delivery: The edge streaming service for a greener future\",\"url\":\"https://blog.lumen.com/revolutionizing-content-delivery-the-edge-streaming-service-for-a-greener-future/\"}]\n\nHere's a summary of the latest information on **streaming video edge packaging, just-in-time packaging, and origin architecture** from 2024–2025:\n\n---\n\n## Netflix Live Origin Architecture\n\nNetflix has built a custom origin server for live streaming. The Netflix Live Origin sits at the demarcation point between cloud live streaming pipelines on its upstream side and Open Connect (Netflix's in-house CDN) on its downstream side, acting as a broker managing what content makes it out to Open Connect and ultimately to client devices.\n\n- **Scale:** During the Tyson vs. Paul fight event in 2024, a historic peak of 65 million concurrent streams was observed.\n- **Design choice:** Netflix chose to build a highly scalable origin instead of relying on the traditional origin shields approach. The live origin directly connects with top-tier Open Connect nodes, which are geographically distributed across several sites.\n- **Redundancy:** The redundant cloud streaming pipelines operate independently, encompassing distinct cloud regions, contribution feeds, encoder, and packager deployments, substantially mitigating the probability of simultaneous defective segments.\n- **Request holding:** Rather than returning a 404 error for a segment not yet available, the Live Origin can 'hold open' the request and serve it once the segment has been published, significantly reducing network chatter.\n\n---\n\n## Just-in-Time (JIT) Packaging\n\nAWS Elemental MediaPackage is a video origination and just-in-time packaging service that securely and reliably delivers streaming content at scale.\n\nThe JIT encoding/packaging workflow involves:\n- The JIT system packages the transcoded video into the appropriate streaming format by segmenting the video stream into chunks, typically a few seconds long, to facilitate adaptive bitrate streaming.\n- A manifest file (e.g., .m3u8 for HLS) is generated containing metadata and URLs pointing to each segment, guiding the client device on how to retrieve and play back the video segments seamlessly.\n- CDNs cache video segments at edge servers geographically closer to end-users, reducing latency and improving streaming performance.\n\n---\n\n## Edge Packaging\n\nEdge packaging is particularly favored for live streaming delivery, as it helps reduce core network bandwidth by moving the packager to an edge site co-located with the CDN, performing the same packaging functions closer to the end-user, optimizing network performance and reducing latency.\n\nHowever, there are trade-offs:\n- Implementing and managing edge packaging infrastructure can be complex and requires specialized expertise, and deploying/maintaining edge servers can increase operational costs.\n- Performance heavily relies on the quality and capacity of the edge network, coordinating content updates across multiple edge locations can be difficult, and distributing content closer to the edge introduces additional security challenges.\n\n**Fastly** offers an on-the-fly packaging solution: Fastly's On-the-Fly Packager (OTFP) add-on helps organizations cut costs associated with duplicating content for different HTTP streaming protocols (e.g., HLS and DASH), with support for DRM partner integrations, content pre-conditioning for ad insertion, and trickplay support.\n\n---\n\n## Origin vs. Edge: Scaling Principles\n\nOrigins scale with the content, while edges scale with the audience — this basic difference highlights the need for different technology deployment and management strategies.\n\n- Gone are the days of building out large, dedicated video storage and channel encoding & origination environments. The use of more flexible cloud platforms is increasing for central content storage and origination because these platforms provide more flexibility.\n\n---\n\n## Open Caching & Edge Computing Trends\n\nOpen Caching is revolutionizing content delivery by creating a standardized, collaborative framework for CDN architectures, championed by the Streaming Video Tech Alliance (SVTA) and adopted by innovators like Qwilt, promoting interoperability, efficiency, and scalability.\n\nEdge computing fundamentally reshapes the traditional CDN paradigm by decentralizing data processing, deploying resources at the network's edge to achieve lower latency, enhanced scalability, and improved reliability — often within Internet Exchange Points (IXPs) or directly inside ISP networks.\n\n---\n\nThese results reflect the ongoing industry shift toward more distributed, flexible architectures for video packaging and delivery, balancing centralized origin intelligence (as Netflix demonstrates) with edge-based packaging and caching for performance at scale.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"49da9aa3-f2b8-48b1-843e-7200caffbfdd","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:32:10.220Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4524073b-f9ea-4c19-96dd-40fe6e7a8f74"}
{"parentUuid":"49da9aa3-f2b8-48b1-843e-7200caffbfdd","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/posttooluse.py"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01Fh93Mi4QkAgyqLz1kz8Hx6","toolUseID":"toolu_01Fh93Mi4QkAgyqLz1kz8Hx6","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:32:10.221Z","uuid":"d0b3ea5e-5e78-497d-9732-683eef76352f"}
{"parentUuid":"d0b3ea5e-5e78-497d-9732-683eef76352f","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a81f5ee73ec6b1b14","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01KJyGABRUYNZseG9CUBHZEQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have comprehensive data across all five companies. Let me compile the research into a thorough report.\n\n---\n\nHere is the consolidated research across all five companies, organized for ADR and scaling document reference.\n\n## 1. Netflix\n\n**CDN Strategy: Build (Open Connect)**\n- Built Open Connect, a proprietary CDN with 18,000+ servers at 6,000+ locations, co-located inside ISP networks.\n- For live, Open Connect was extended with proxy-caching on nginx. Only designated nodes per stream rendition at each site fill directly from origin, reducing origin load.\n- During the Tyson vs. Paul fight (Nov 2024), they hit 65 million concurrent streams.\n\n**Encoding/Transcoding Pipeline:**\n- **Cosmos platform** — microservices-based encoding pipeline (replacing monolithic \"Reloaded\"), consisting of Video Inspection Service (VIS), Complexity Analysis Service (CAS), Ladder Generation Service (LGS), and Video Encoding Service (VES).\n- **Per-title and per-shot encoding** — each piece of content gets an individually optimized bitrate ladder.\n- **AV1 powers 30% of Netflix streaming** as of Dec 2025. AV1 HDR (HDR10+) launched March 2025. AV1 Film Grain Synthesis (FGS) productized July 2025, reducing bitrate by 66% with better quality. Also uses H.264 (AVC) and HEVC.\n- CPU-based encoding for VOD quality optimization; evaluating AV1 for live.\n\n**Origin/Storage:**\n- Custom **Live Origin** on EC2, separating read (EVCache/Memcached) and write (Cassandra) paths. Scalable without origin shields.\n- Initially tried S3 for live but found it couldn't meet 2-second retry budgets at scale. Quote: \"AWS S3 is an amazing object store, but our Live streaming requirements were closer to those of a global low-latency highly-available database.\"\n- VOD assets remain on S3, pre-positioned to Open Connect appliances.\n\n**Ingest:** AWS MediaConnect and AWS MediaLive for cloud ingest. Hub-and-spoke model aggregating production feeds at broadcast facilities before cloud ingestion. Dual-region redundancy with two distinct network paths each.\n\n**Delivery:** HTTPS-based (HLS), 2-second segment duration. No UDP-based delivery (no WebRTC). Manifest design uses segment templates with constant segment duration to avoid frequent manifest refresh.\n\n**Backend Language:** Java/Spring Boot (primary), federated GraphQL via DGS framework (written in Kotlin). Go used for infrastructure tooling. Python for ML/data pipelines. C++ for performance-critical encoding.\n\n**Key Blog Posts (2024-2026):**\n- [Netflix Live Origin](https://netflixtechblog.com/netflix-live-origin-41f1b0ad5371) (Dec 2025)\n- [Behind the Streams Part 1](https://netflixtechblog.com/behind-the-streams-live-at-netflix-part-1-d23f917c2f40) (Sep 2025)\n- [Behind the Streams Part 2](https://netflixtechblog.com/behind-the-streams-building-a-reliable-cloud-live-streaming-pipeline-for-netflix-part-2-8627c608c967) (Sep 2025)\n- [AV1 Now Powering 30% of Netflix Streaming](https://netflixtechblog.com/av1-now-powering-30-of-netflix-streaming-02f592242d80) (Dec 2025)\n- [Rebuilding Netflix Video Processing Pipeline with Microservices](https://netflixtechblog.com/rebuilding-netflix-video-processing-pipeline-with-microservices-4e5e6310e359) (Jan 2024)\n- [Netflix Real-Time Distributed Graph (Kafka)](https://netflixtechblog.com/how-and-why-netflix-built-a-real-time-distributed-graph-part-1-ingesting-and-processing-data-80113e124acc) (Oct 2025)\n- [From On-Demand to Live (InfoQ analysis)](https://www.infoq.com/news/2025/12/netflix-live-streaming-pipeline/) (Dec 2025)\n\n**Overlap with project:** CMAF (Netflix uses fMP4 segments), Kafka (for event streaming, ~1M msg/sec per topic), S3 for VOD storage, fault-tolerant redundant encoding pipelines with failover, custom packager, 2-second segments.\n**Differs:** Java/Spring Boot (not Go) for backend; built own CDN rather than using third-party; EVCache+Cassandra for live origin rather than S3; does not use LL-HLS (standard HLS with 2s segments).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Amazon / Prime Video / Twitch\n\n**CDN Strategy: Build + Buy**\n- **Twitch:** Built video infrastructure in-house with custom PoPs worldwide.\n- **Prime Video:** Uses AWS CloudFront (Amazon's own CDN) plus AWS Elemental stack.\n- Both are Amazon-owned but maintain **separate** encoding and delivery pipelines.\n\n**Encoding/Transcoding:**\n- **Twitch:** Transcoding system written in C/C++ and Go. Built custom hardware-based transcoder in-house, significantly reducing costs. Enhanced Broadcasting (2024-2025) enables client-side multi-encode with NVIDIA NVENC, shifting encoding to the streamer. AV1 and HEVC in beta testing for Enhanced Broadcasting (June 2025).\n- **Prime Video:** H.264 for video, AAC for audio. 9 video renditions for desktop (288p-720p, up to 8 Mbit). Uses AWS Elemental for packaging and ad insertion.\n- **Twitch released Twirp** — an RPC framework for Go backend communication, analogous to gRPC/ConnectRPC.\n\n**Origin/Storage:**\n- AWS Elemental MediaPackage for just-in-time packaging (HLS, DASH, CMAF, Smooth Streaming).\n- AWS reference architecture: Source -> MediaConnect -> MediaLive -> MediaPackage -> CloudFront -> Viewers.\n\n**Ingest:**\n- RTMP is the standard ingest protocol for Twitch.\n- Enhanced RTMP (ERTMP) supports modern codecs (AV1, HEVC, VP9) and multitrack video. Twitch co-leads the Veovera Software Organization driving this spec.\n- AWS Elemental supports RTMP, RTP, HLS, and MediaConnect flows for ingest.\n\n**Delivery:** Twitch uses HLS. Prime Video uses HLS/DASH. Amazon IVS (built on Twitch tech) achieves ~2 second latency.\n\n**Backend Language:** **Go is the primary backend language at Twitch**, powering chat (hundreds of billions of messages/day), microservices, and RPC (Twirp). C/C++ for transcoding. Prime Video uses Java, Kotlin, Go, Node.js, Python, and C++. Prime Video adopted Kotlin for higher developer satisfaction.\n\n**Key Resources (2024-2026):**\n- [Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting Beta](https://blog.twitch.tv/en/2024/01/08/introducing-the-enhanced-broadcasting-beta/) (Jan 2024)\n- [NVIDIA + Twitch Multi-Encode AV1](https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/geforce/news/gfecnt/20241/twitch-multiencode-av1-livestreaming/) (2024)\n- [AWS Live Streaming Architecture](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/solutions/latest/live-streaming-on-aws/architecture-overview.html)\n- [Adopting Kotlin at Prime Video](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/opensource/adopting-kotlin-at-prime-video-for-higher-developer-satisfaction-and-less-code/)\n- [Mux: Twitch vs Amazon Prime TNF Teardown](https://www.mux.com/blog/thursday-night-football-streaming-technology-showdown-amazon-prime-vs-twitch)\n\n**Overlap with project:** Go as backend language (Twitch), Twirp RPC framework (similar to ConnectRPC), HLS delivery, RTMP ingest, multi-CDN approach, client-side encoding shift concept.\n**Differs:** Twitch uses custom hardware transcoders (not cloud FFmpeg); ERTMP multitrack video is a newer approach than single-stream ingest; AWS Elemental is a managed service vs. custom-built pipeline.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Apple TV+\n\n**CDN Strategy: Build + Buy**\n- Apple operates its own CDN with cache infrastructure co-located inside ISP networks (similar strategy to Netflix Open Connect).\n- Also uses third-party CDNs. Highest density of CDN sites in the USA, followed by Europe and East Asia.\n\n**Encoding/Transcoding:**\n- HEVC (H.265) is the primary codec for Apple TV+ 4K HDR content. Supports H.264 for backward compatibility.\n- **AV1 officially added to HLS spec in 2024**, including Dolby Vision Profile 10 with AV1.\n- Apple's HLS Authoring Specification (updated 2024-2025) requires: H.264/AVC, HEVC/H.265, Dolby Vision, or AV1 for video.\n- **HEVC in HLS must use fMP4 (CMAF) container** — MPEG-TS is not supported for HEVC.\n- 6-second target segment duration recommended. Frame rates up to 60 fps supported.\n\n**Origin/Storage:** Proprietary; Apple does not publish details about their origin architecture.\n\n**Ingest:** Apple does not operate a user-facing live ingest platform (unlike Twitch/YouTube). Apple TV+ content is professionally produced and delivered.\n\n**Delivery:** HLS (Apple invented it). FairPlay Streaming DRM (AES-128 CBC encryption). Supports LL-HLS (Apple drove the specification). CMAF support for interoperability with DASH.\n\n**Backend Language:** Apple does not disclose internal language choices for streaming infrastructure. Swift, Objective-C, C++, and Java are known to be used across Apple.\n\n**Key Resources (2024-2026):**\n- [HLS Authoring Specification for Apple Devices](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/http-live-streaming/hls-authoring-specification-for-apple-devices) (updated 2024)\n- [What's New in HLS (WWDC 2025)](https://developer.apple.com/streaming/Whats-new-HLS.pdf)\n- [HLS Updates from WWDC 2024 (Bitmovin analysis)](https://bitmovin.com/blog/hls-updates-wwdc-2024/)\n- [An Update to Apple HLS Best Practices (end 2024)](https://www.radiantmediaplayer.com/blog/an-update-to-apple-hls-best-practices-end-2024.html)\n\n**Overlap with project:** HLS as primary delivery protocol, CMAF (required for HEVC in HLS), fMP4 container format, LL-HLS with partial segments, AV1 adoption trajectory.\n**Differs:** Apple mandates 6-second segments (project uses 2-second); Apple's spec is prescriptive (streaming services must comply to reach Apple devices); FairPlay DRM is Apple-only.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Disney+ / Hulu / ESPN+\n\n**CDN Strategy: Buy (Akamai)**\n- Disney+ uses Akamai as its primary CDN with a multi-layer CDN architecture.\n- CMAF reduces storage costs and increases cache hit rates across the Akamai CDN.\n\n**Encoding/Transcoding:**\n- x264 (H.264) encoding as primary codec. Exploring AV1 and HEVC adoption.\n- Uses AWS Elemental for encoding and transcoding in the cloud.\n- Cloud-native architecture with distributed CI/CD pipelines for parallel content processing.\n\n**Origin/Storage:**\n- AWS-based infrastructure (hybrid cloud).\n- AWS Elemental MediaPackage for just-in-time packaging.\n\n**Ingest:** Professional contribution; ESPN+ handles live sports feeds from venues.\n\n**Delivery:**\n- **100% HLS CMAF** — Disney+ was built on CMAF from day one, thanks to BAMTech's experience.\n- DASH-HLS interoperability work through CTA WAVE standards body.\n- Disney sunsetted older devices that couldn't support CMAF or required DRM levels.\n- ESPN+ achieves sub-10-second latency for live sports using edge computing.\n\n**Backend Language:** Java, Scala (JVM-heavy, inherited from BAMTech/MLB heritage), Python, Go. **Smithy4s** (open source, Scala code generation from Smithy IDL) is their flagship open-source project. Acquired Cake Solutions (Scala specialists) in 2017. Uses Kafka, Spark, Flink for data pipelines.\n\n**Disney+ Hotstar** (India) handles 50M+ concurrent viewers during cricket matches using Go for microservices and Java for backend services.\n\n**Key Resources (2024-2026):**\n- [How Disney's Media Engineers Enable Streaming](https://sites.disney.com/lifeatdisney/work-and-innovation/2024/08/02/how-media-engineers-enable-disneys-streaming-connection-with-audiences/) (Aug 2024)\n- [Disney Streaming GitHub (smithy4s)](https://github.com/disneystreaming)\n- [Inside Disney+ Streaming Technology](https://www.frugaltesting.com/blog/inside-disney-streaming-technology-transcoding-abr-and-akamai-cdn-explained)\n- [How Disney Streaming Delivers Consistent Media Experiences](https://www.streamingmedia.com/Articles/ReadArticle.aspx?ArticleID=147353)\n\n**Overlap with project:** 100% HLS CMAF (exact same format choice), Kafka for data pipelines, Go for microservices (Hotstar), AWS infrastructure, just-in-time packaging.\n**Differs:** Scala/JVM heavy (BAMTech heritage) vs. Go-first; Akamai CDN vs. custom/S3; x264 (not CMAF-native encoding); live sports latency targets differ from VOD.\n\n---\n\n## 5. YouTube / Google\n\n**CDN Strategy: Build (Google's Global CDN)**\n- Google operates its own global CDN with edge nodes worldwide. Custom-built network infrastructure.\n- Content is cached at edge servers closest to viewers; cache misses fall back to regional caches then origin storage.\n\n**Encoding/Transcoding:**\n- **Custom Argos VCU ASICs** — Google designed custom transcoding chips (Video Coding Units). 20-33x more compute-efficient than CPU-based transcoding. Each chip has 10 cores, can encode 2160p@60fps per core. Thousands deployed in Google data centers.\n- Second-generation Argos supports AV1. Eliminated millions of Intel CPUs.\n- VP9 is the default delivery codec (30-40% savings over H.264). AV1 saves 50-60% but costs 50-100x more to encode.\n- AV1 live streaming support launched in beta (2025), but streams are re-transcoded to VP9 for broader device compatibility.\n- **Enhanced RTMP** support for ingest with AV1, VP9, HEVC.\n\n**Origin/Storage:**\n- **Colossus** (successor to GFS) — Google's distributed file system for massive video file storage with redundancy.\n- **Bigtable** for analytics, watch history, ML data.\n- **Spanner** for globally consistent transactional data (Content ID, rights management). Handles 6B queries/sec at peak, 17 exabytes of data, five 9s availability.\n- **Vitess** — born at YouTube, for horizontally scaling MySQL.\n\n**Ingest:** RTMP is the primary live ingest protocol. Enhanced RTMP adds AV1, VP9, HEVC codec support.\n\n**Delivery:** MPEG-DASH for web browsers (1-5 second segments), HLS for Apple devices (6-10 second segments). DASH's shorter segments allow 30% less rebuffering on mobile.\n\n**Backend Language:** Python (original, still used for data pipelines), Java (core backend services), C++ (video processing, encoding), Go (networking, microservices). gRPC for inter-service communication. QUIC/HTTP/2 for video transport.\n\n**Infrastructure:** Borg (cluster manager, predecessor to Kubernetes). Custom networking. TensorFlow for recommendation engine.\n\n**Key Resources (2024-2026):**\n- [YouTube Tech Stack Architecture](https://www.vdocipher.com/blog/youtube-tech-stack-architecture/)\n- [YouTube Architecture Deep Dive (Dev.to)](https://dev.to/wittedtech-by-harshit/unveiling-the-backbone-of-youtube-live-streaming-a-deep-dive-into-youtubes-architecture-and-real-time-video-processing-f6j)\n- [AV1 Live Streaming Coming to YouTube (Tom's Hardware)](https://www.tomshardware.com/news/av1-live-streaming-is-finally-coming-to-youtube)\n- [Google Argos VCU](https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/google-develops-custom-argos-video-transcoding-chips-for-youtube-processing/)\n- [Spanner Innovations in 2024](https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/databases/spanner-innovations-in-2024)\n\n**Overlap with project:** Go for networking/microservices, gRPC (similar to ConnectRPC), RTMP ingest, AV1 adoption path, segment-based delivery, massive Kafka-like event streaming (Pub/Sub).\n**Differs:** Custom ASICs for encoding (not FFmpeg/CPU), Colossus/Spanner (not S3/MongoDB), DASH-first (not HLS-first), scale is 500+ hours uploaded per minute.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-Company Industry Patterns (for company-agnostic ADRs)\n\n### Converged Decisions (industry consensus):\n\n| Decision | Industry Consensus | Project Alignment |\n|----------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| **Container format** | CMAF (fMP4) is the architectural backbone. Disney+ is 100% CMAF. Apple requires fMP4 for HEVC. Netflix uses fMP4 segments. | Aligned (CMAF/fMP4) |\n| **Delivery protocol** | HLS dominates. DASH used by YouTube on web. CMAF enables both from single source. | Aligned (HLS + CMAF) |\n| **Ingest protocol** | RTMP remains dominant for ingest despite age. SRT growing for contribution. WHIP/WebRTC for ultra-low-latency. | Aligned (RTMP ingest) |\n| **Codec trajectory** | AV1 is the future (Netflix 30%, YouTube deploying, Apple added to HLS spec 2024, Twitch testing). H.264 baseline, HEVC for 4K/HDR. | Project uses H.264, AV1 is natural extension |\n| **Object storage for VOD** | S3 is the industry standard for VOD storage. Netflix found S3 insufficient for live at scale. | Aligned (MinIO/S3-compatible) |\n| **Event streaming** | Kafka is near-universal (Netflix, Disney, Twitch). Netflix processes ~1M msg/sec per topic. | Aligned (Kafka) |\n| **Fault tolerance** | Dual-region redundant pipelines, redundant ingest paths, epoch-based segment selection for failover. | Aligned (pipeline controller + failover) |\n| **Segment duration** | 2 seconds (Netflix live), 1-5 seconds (YouTube DASH), 6 seconds (Apple recommendation). Industry moving shorter. | Aligned (2-second segments) |\n| **Low latency** | LL-HLS with partial segments (200-500ms parts), blocking playlist reload, preload hints. 2-5 second glass-to-glass. | Aligned (LL-HLS planned in Epic 8) |\n\n### Where Go fits in the industry:\n\n| Company | Go Usage |\n|---------|----------|\n| **Twitch** | Primary backend language. Chat, microservices, Twirp RPC. |\n| **YouTube/Google** | Networking services, microservices. One of Google's core languages. |\n| **Disney+ Hotstar** | Microservices handling 50M+ concurrent viewers. |\n| **Netflix** | Infrastructure tooling only; Java/Spring Boot is primary. |\n| **Prime Video** | One of several backend languages alongside Java, Kotlin. |\n\nGo is a strong choice validated by Twitch (the most comparable live streaming platform) and Google/YouTube for networking-heavy, high-concurrency workloads.\n\n### Where choices differ and why:\n\n| Project Choice | Industry Alternative | Why It Differs |\n|---------------|---------------------|---------------|\n| **Go for everything** | Netflix uses Java; Disney uses Scala/Java | Netflix has massive JVM ecosystem investment; Disney inherited BAMTech's JVM stack. Go is preferred by companies building new systems (Twitch, Hotstar). |\n| **S3/MinIO for live segments** | Netflix built EVCache+Cassandra for live origin | S3's tail latency is too high for Netflix's 65M concurrent streams. At smaller scale, S3-compatible storage works fine. |\n| **FFmpeg for encoding** | YouTube uses custom Argos ASICs; Twitch uses custom hardware transcoders | Custom silicon only makes sense at YouTube/Twitch scale (500+ hrs/min uploads). FFmpeg is the industry standard for smaller-to-medium scale. |\n| **ConnectRPC** | Twitch uses Twirp; Google uses gRPC | All three are compatible RPC frameworks. ConnectRPC provides gRPC compatibility with simpler HTTP semantics. Twirp validates that RPC-over-HTTP works at Twitch scale. |\n| **MongoDB** | Netflix uses Cassandra+EVCache; YouTube uses Spanner+Bigtable | Choice depends on data model needs. MongoDB is appropriate for metadata/configuration at moderate scale. |\n\n### Key Talks and Publications (2024-2026):\n\n**Netflix:**\n- [Netflix Live Origin](https://netflixtechblog.com/netflix-live-origin-41f1b0ad5371) (Dec 2025)\n- [Behind the Streams Part 1](https://netflixtechblog.com/behind-the-streams-live-at-netflix-part-1-d23f917c2f40) and [Part 2](https://netflixtechblog.com/behind-the-streams-building-a-reliable-cloud-live-streaming-pipeline-for-netflix-part-2-8627c608c967) (Sep 2025)\n- [AV1 Powering 30% of Streaming](https://netflixtechblog.com/av1-now-powering-30-of-netflix-streaming-02f592242d80) (Dec 2025)\n- [Rebuilding Video Processing Pipeline with Microservices](https://netflixtechblog.com/rebuilding-netflix-video-processing-pipeline-with-microservices-4e5e6310e359) (Jan 2024)\n- [Real-Time Distributed Graph (Kafka at scale)](https://netflixtechblog.com/how-and-why-netflix-built-a-real-time-distributed-graph-part-1-ingesting-and-processing-data-80113e124acc) (Oct 2025)\n\n**Amazon/Twitch:**\n- [Twitch Enhanced Broadcasting Beta](https://blog.twitch.tv/en/2024/01/08/introducing-the-enhanced-broadcasting-beta/) (Jan 2024)\n- [NVIDIA + Twitch AV1 Multi-Encode](https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/geforce/news/gfecnt/20241/twitch-multiencode-av1-livestreaming/) (2024)\n- [AWS Live Streaming Architecture](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/solutions/latest/live-streaming-on-aws/architecture-overview.html)\n- [Choosing the Right AWS Live Streaming Solution](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/awse-choosing-aws-live-streaming-solution-for-use-case/)\n\n**Apple:**\n- [HLS Authoring Specification](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/http-live-streaming/hls-authoring-specification-for-apple-devices) (updated 2024)\n- [What's New in HLS (WWDC 2025)](https://developer.apple.com/streaming/Whats-new-HLS.pdf)\n- [HLS Updates from WWDC 2024](https://bitmovin.com/blog/hls-updates-wwdc-2024/)\n\n**Disney:**\n- [Disney Media Engineering](https://sites.disney.com/lifeatdisney/work-and-innovation/2024/08/02/how-media-engineers-enable-disneys-streaming-connection-with-audiences/) (Aug 2024)\n- [Disney Streaming GitHub](https://github.com/disneystreaming)\n\n**YouTube/Google:**\n- [Google Argos VCU Custom Chip](https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/google-develops-custom-argos-video-transcoding-chips-for-youtube-processing/)\n- [Spanner Innovations 2024](https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/databases/spanner-innovations-in-2024)\n- [YouTube Architecture Deep Dive](https://dev.to/wittedtech-by-harshit/unveiling-the-backbone-of-youtube-live-streaming-a-deep-dive-into-youtubes-architecture-and-real-time-video-processing-f6j)\n\n**Industry-Wide:**\n- [The State of CMAF in 2026 (Wowza)](https://www.wowza.com/blog/the-state-of-cmaf-in-2026)\n- [CDN Alliance Low Latency Whitepaper](https://cdnalliance.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/LL-WG-Whitepaper-Low-Latency-Streaming-%E2%80%93-A-First-Step-Towards-Standardization-V1.pdf) (Sep 2025)\n- [Mux: Which Live Ingest Protocol](https://www.mux.com/blog/which-live-stream-ingest-protocol-is-right-for-you)\n- [The Latency Wars: WHIP and MoQ](https://medium.com/@contact_45426/the-latency-wars-why-whip-and-moq-are-dethroning-rtmp-srt-for-real-time-streaming-7e5bea4032ee)\n- [Cloudflare LL-HLS Support](https://blog.cloudflare.com/low-latency-hls-support-for-cloudflare-stream/)\n- [GPU vs CPU Transcoding](https://antmedia.io/gpu-vs-cpu-transcoding-for-streaming/)"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1579,"cache_read_input_tokens":52319,"output_tokens":6662,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1579},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CYpH21wD8PhrUiqyG17T1","type":"assistant","uuid":"aa6c8c60-9d6c-42f8-b1b6-b21b74a541c6","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:34:35.827Z"}
{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are researching Warner Bros. Discovery's (WBD) streaming technology infrastructure for Max (formerly HBO Max) to add to a company-agnostic industry reference document. This is RESEARCH ONLY — do not write any code.\n\nResearch the following about WBD/Max streaming technology:\n\n1. **CDN Strategy** — Does Max use a build vs buy CDN approach? Which CDN providers (Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, etc.)? Multi-CDN?\n\n2. **Encoding/Transcoding Pipeline** — What codecs does Max use (H.264, HEVC, AV1)? Any per-title encoding? What cloud infrastructure (AWS, GCP, Azure)? Any public blog posts or conference talks about their encoding pipeline?\n\n3. **Origin/Storage Architecture** — How does Max store and serve video segments? S3? Custom origin? Edge packaging?\n\n4. **Delivery Protocols** — HLS, DASH, CMAF? LL-HLS support?\n\n5. **Backend Language/Tech Stack** — What programming languages and frameworks does Max use? Java, Go, Python, etc.?\n\n6. **Architecture Heritage** — What platform was HBO Max originally built on? How did it evolve after the Discovery merger? Any major re-architecture efforts?\n\n7. **Live Streaming** — Does Max do live streaming (sports, events)? How is live handled differently from VOD?\n\n8. **Key Engineering Blog Posts, Conference Talks, or Technical Publications (2023-2026)** — Any public technical content from WBD/Max engineering teams? Streaming Media conferences, NAB, IBC talks?\n\n9. **Open Source Contributions** — Any notable open source projects from WBD/Max engineering?\n\n10. **Scale** — Number of subscribers, concurrent viewers for major events, any public scale numbers?\n\nSearch for:\n- \"HBO Max streaming architecture\"\n- \"Warner Bros Discovery streaming technology\"\n- \"Max streaming infrastructure engineering\"\n- \"WBD Max CDN encoding pipeline\"\n- \"HBO Max tech stack engineering blog\"\n- \"WBD streaming conference talk NAB IBC\"\n- \"Max CMAF HLS DASH delivery\"\n- \"HBO Max engineering team technology\"\n\nAlso try LinkedIn searches or engineering blog posts. WBD may be less public than Netflix about their tech, so conference talks and job postings may be better sources than blog posts.\n\nProvide specific findings with dates and source URLs. Be factual — if information isn't publicly available, say so rather than speculating."},"uuid":"e1c9e76a-a753-4e13-962d-a7043b8f5b83","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:38:21.956Z"}
