{"parentUuid":"2c164ccc-b017-417b-a721-32c7ced1ad99","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"HBO Max streaming architecture technology infrastructure"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01ES81oBoLUNUqx6q2vrSQ47","parentToolUseID":"toolu_018FXEU6LzjhUyPMuRSsGkjY","uuid":"3b971552-a7c8-4f5c-b6d1-b21da32c825d","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:38:31.514Z"}
{"parentUuid":"cac86fac-be2e-4301-ab85-3549a308f019","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018FXEU6LzjhUyPMuRSsGkjY","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"HBO Max streaming architecture technology infrastructure\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"The Technology Behind HBO Max: High-Definition Streaming At Global Scale\",\"url\":\"https://www.frugaltesting.com/blog/the-technology-behind-hbo-max-high-definition-streaming-at-global-scale\"},{\"title\":\"Understanding the legacy of HBO Max & its powerful, scalable technical stack | TechAhead\",\"url\":\"https://www.techaheadcorp.com/blog/understanding-the-legacy-of-hbo-max-its-powerful-scalable-technical-stack/\"},{\"title\":\"Understanding the legacy of HBO Max & its powerful, scalable technical stack | PPT\",\"url\":\"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/understanding-the-legacy-of-hbo-max-its-powerful-scalable-technical-stack/254235154\"},{\"title\":\"For HBO Max, streaming technology is anything but a commodity - Fast Company\",\"url\":\"https://www.fastcompany.com/90373706/hbos-tech-is-prepping-att-for-the-streaming-wars\"},{\"title\":\"What technologies were used to build HBO Go? - Quora\",\"url\":\"https://www.quora.com/What-technologies-were-used-to-build-HBO-Go\"},{\"title\":\"Paramount+ and HBO Max to merge into one streaming giant with ~200M subscribers\",\"url\":\"https://ppc.land/paramount-and-hbo-max-to-merge-into-one-streaming-giant-with-200m-subscribers/\"},{\"title\":\"A Step-by-Step Guide to Develop an App Like HBO Max\",\"url\":\"https://www.jploft.com/blog/how-to-develop-an-app-like-hbo-max\"},{\"title\":\"HBO Max - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HBO_Max\"},{\"title\":\"\\\"A Benefit and a Curse\\\": How HBO Max's Tech Team Is Building On HBO Now\",\"url\":\"https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/general-news/a-benefit-a-curse-how-hbo-maxs-tech-team-is-building-hbo-now-1295521/\"},{\"title\":\"HBO Max Teardown Analysis | Streaming Strategy & UX - NextSprints\",\"url\":\"https://nextsprints.com/guide/hbo-max-product-teardown-analysis\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of HBO Max's streaming architecture, technology, and infrastructure:\n\n## HBO Max Streaming Architecture & Technology Infrastructure\n\n### Origins & Foundation\n\nPlanning on what would become HBO Max began in earnest near the end of 2018, and development of the product didn't get underway until spring 2019. Fortunately, the team had an existing framework for HBO Max: the five-year-old stand-alone streamer HBO Now.\n\nThere was some debate over whether WarnerMedia would use the same technical backbone to build HBO Max, but the infrastructure was proven solid after the service handled some 4.7 million concurrent video streams during the finale of Game of Thrones.\n\n### Core Framework: BAMTech\n\nThe framework deployed by HBO Max was created by BAMTech, which was earlier acquired by Disney. Both HBO Max and Disney use the same framework for delivering video content. This same BAMTech platform is also used by WWE and the National Hockey League to deliver live, streaming content to more than 8 million users across the globe.\n\nIn late 2014, HBO abandoned plans to build the stand-alone HBO Now streaming service with its own tech. Instead, the company signed on with BamTech—then called MLB Advanced Media—believing that it would deliver a more polished platform in time for HBO Now's launch.\n\n### Cloud-Native Architecture\n\nHBO Max delivers HD streaming through a globally distributed, cloud-native delivery architecture that ingests and processes content via automated transcoding pipelines, metadata normalization systems, and CMAF-based HLS/DASH packaging.\n\nThe system involves content delivery network caching, cloud infrastructure, advanced video compression, global load balancer systems, Kubernetes auto-scaling, AI-based personalization, performance analytics, and strict content protection layers.\n\n### Video Streaming & Delivery\n\n- **Streaming Platform:** HBO Max uses Unified Streaming Platform v1.9.5, which produces HLS Manifests. With their latest update for the app in 2021, they moved to an advanced version, as v1.9.5 had been in usage since 2018.\n\n- **Adaptive Bitrate Streaming:** With unpredictable user environments, varying internet download speed, and inconsistent network bandwidth, the platform leverages multi-tier CDN caching, edge compute nodes, protocol-aware traffic routing, and adaptive bitrate streaming.\n\n### DRM & Content Protection\n\nHBO Max (earlier version before 2021) used Widevine, PlayReady, and PlayReady (with multi-key). Post-2021, HBO Max transitioned to their own in-house built DRM.\n\n### Video Players\n\nFor earlier versions, HBO Max used the Shaka Player for web browsers, ExoPlayer for Android, and AVPlayer for iOS. HBO had been using Google's open-source player for Android users for a long time.\n\n### Backend Technology\n\nThe backend is primarily Java-based. Traditional technologies were used including Spring, Weblogic, and Oracle. Things have been updated over time to use Cassandra as the primary datastore and more of an overall SOA (Service-Oriented Architecture).\n\n### 4K & HDR Support\n\nAt launch, HBO Max did not support 4K, HDR, Dolby Vision, or Dolby Atmos. Support for 4K, HDR, and Atmos was added starting with the release of Wonder Woman 1984, with WarnerMedia promising to add more content in these formats throughout 2021 and beyond.\n\n### Team & Scale\n\nJeremy Legg, chief technology officer at WarnerMedia, and his team of 600 had been gunning for a May 27 (2020) debut for some time.\n\nHBO Max first launched in the United States on May 27, 2020. It is the fourth most-subscribed video on demand streaming media service, after Disney+, Amazon Prime Video, and Netflix, with 128 million paid memberships worldwide.\n\n### Latest Development: Paramount+ Merger\n\nParamount confirmed it plans to merge Paramount+ and HBO Max into a single streaming platform following the completion of its acquisition of Warner Bros. Discovery. The combined service would have approximately 200 million direct-to-consumer subscribers.\n\nThe architecture of the combined service—including branding, technology stack, and advertising infrastructure—has not yet been finalized. The prospect of merging the consolidated Paramount stack with HBO Max's own infrastructure adds another layer of complexity. HBO Max operates its own streaming technology platform, which has undergone significant development since the service launched in May 2020. Bringing the two together while maintaining service quality, personalization capabilities, and advertising systems will require careful coordination.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"4feb7d60-5b4d-4000-a6be-af5f55759579","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:39:04.335Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"cac86fac-be2e-4301-ab85-3549a308f019"}
