{"parentUuid":"7ab860cb-bd0c-46c2-83ad-40db07e92c72","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"query_update","query":"Max streaming HLS DASH CMAF low latency live delivery protocol"},"toolUseID":"search-progress-1","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01Kg6Rj5hS8Ce9FDSbFFpcGq","uuid":"cb17d9d2-0986-4f99-a802-57802e591a93","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:41:21.808Z"}
{"parentUuid":"cb17d9d2-0986-4f99-a802-57802e591a93","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Max streaming HLS DASH CMAF low latency live delivery protocol"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_01DG9PKQCg4hHGmydSCMhojU","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01Kg6Rj5hS8Ce9FDSbFFpcGq","uuid":"3834e271-b49b-453a-adbe-f77c2cbb2f8d","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:41:24.632Z"}
{"parentUuid":"ce8e4a41-99c6-4f3f-b226-eea8f1edd9ec","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Kg6Rj5hS8Ce9FDSbFFpcGq","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Max streaming HLS DASH CMAF low latency live delivery protocol\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Low-Latency HLS (LL-HLS), CMAF, and WebRTC: Which Is Best?\",\"url\":\"https://cloudinary.com/guides/live-streaming-video/low-latency-hls-ll-hls-cmaf-and-webrtc-which-is-best\"},{\"title\":\"DASH vs HLS in 2026: Latency, DRM & Protocol Guide\",\"url\":\"https://swarmify.com/blog/dash-vs-hls-streaming-protocols-compared/\"},{\"title\":\"What is CMAF? Advantages of CMAF Streaming [2026]\",\"url\":\"https://antmedia.io/cmaf-streaming/\"},{\"title\":\"HTTP Live Streaming - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_Live_Streaming\"},{\"title\":\"CMAF Streaming Specification: One File for HLS and DASH\",\"url\":\"https://www.videoexpertsgroup.com/glossary/cmaf\"},{\"title\":\"What Is HLS Streaming and When Should You Use It [2026 Update]\",\"url\":\"https://www.dacast.com/blog/hls-streaming-protocol/\"},{\"title\":\"DASH and a Media Services Live origin\",\"url\":\"https://techdocs.akamai.com/adaptive-media-delivery/docs/dash-and-msl-origin\"},{\"title\":\"DASH and HLS: An Update on Low Latency OTT Delivery\",\"url\":\"https://www.harmonicinc.com/insights/blog/dash-and-hls-update-low-latency-ott-delivery\"},{\"title\":\"Introduction to Low Latency Streaming with HLS\",\"url\":\"https://www.100ms.live/blog/hls-low-latency-streaming\"},{\"title\":\"Apple Low-Latency HLS: What It Is and How It Relates to CMAF | Wowza\",\"url\":\"https://www.wowza.com/blog/apple-low-latency-hls\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of **HLS, DASH, CMAF, and Low-Latency Live Streaming Protocols** based on the latest information:\n\n---\n\n## Overview of Streaming Protocols\n\nHLS and MPEG-DASH both deliver adaptive streaming over HTTP—but they differ in device support, DRM ecosystems, and how low you can push live latency.\n\n### **HLS (HTTP Live Streaming)**\nCreated by Apple in 2009, HLS was originally designed to solve a specific problem: getting video to play smoothly on iPhones over standard HTTP networks. Today, HLS is the most widely supported streaming protocol on the planet. It works natively on all Apple devices (iOS, macOS, tvOS) and the Safari browser.\n\nHLS works by breaking the overall stream into a sequence of small HTTP-based file downloads, each downloading one short chunk of an overall potentially unbounded transport stream. A list of available streams, encoded at different bit rates, is sent to the client using an extended M3U playlist.\n\n### **MPEG-DASH**\nUnlike HLS, which dictates specific video formats, DASH can wrap almost anything. It supports newer, high-efficiency codecs like VP9 and AV1, which can deliver higher quality at lower bitrates compared to HLS's traditional H.264/HEVC focus. DASH uses an XML-based manifest file (ending in .mpd) to tell the player where to find video segments. It's the native choice for Android devices and is widely used by major streaming platforms like Netflix and YouTube (on non-Apple devices).\n\n### **CMAF (Common Media Application Format)**\nThe Common Media Application Format, known as CMAF, was introduced to solve this fragmentation. CMAF makes it possible to package video once and deliver it to both HLS and DASH players. As a result, streaming platforms can simplify their workflows while improving efficiency and latency performance.\n\nCMAF itself is not a protocol, but a format that contains a set of containers and standards for single-approach video streaming that works with protocols such as HLS and MPEG-DASH.\n\nIt is an international media packaging specification developed by MPEG and standardized as ISO/IEC 23000-19.\n\nCMAF is the modern solution: it lets you encode once and serve both protocols from the same files.\n\n---\n\n## Low-Latency Solutions\n\n### The Latency Problem\nThe two dominant delivery formats (i.e., HLS and DASH) both offer latencies of between 30 and 45 seconds due to sequential buffering of multiple media delivery segments.\n\n### **Low-Latency DASH (LL-DASH)**\nDASH came up with a low latency solution based on chunked CMAF in 2017. LL-DASH uses Chunked Encoding for creating chunks and Chunked Transfer Encoding for delivering them over TCP.\n\n### **Low-Latency HLS (LL-HLS)**\nApple decided to release its own extension of the protocol called Low Latency HLS (LL-HLS) in 2019, often referred to as Apple Low Latency HLS (ALHLS). This version of HLS offered low latency comparable to CL-HLS and promised compatibility with Apple devices. Since then, LL-HLS has been merged into the HLS specification and has technically become a single protocol.\n\nOne approach is to divide the segments into parts and deliver them as soon as they're available. The other is to inform the player about the data to be loaded next before said data is even available.\n\nLow latency HLS will provide tools to deliver media at the live edge of the media playlist, where the media is divided into a larger number of smaller files, such as CMAF chunks that are 250-300ms in duration. These smaller files are called HLS partial segments.\n\n### **CMAF's Role in Low Latency**\nCMAF enables low-latency streaming by allowing the video to be broken into small chunks that can be transmitted as soon as they are encoded. These chunks can be delivered over HTTP using techniques like chunked transfer encoding, allowing playback to begin almost immediately. This approach supports near-real-time delivery (typically 3–5 seconds of latency) while later parts of the video are still being processed.\n\nChunked encoding allows media fragments to be transmitted before a full segment is complete. This capability is essential for low-latency streaming workflows.\n\n---\n\n## Key Comparisons\n\n| Feature | LL-HLS | LL-DASH | WebRTC |\n|---------|--------|---------|--------|\n| **Compatibility** | Good support for all Apple devices and browsers, gaining support for most non-Apple devices. | Supports most non-Apple devices and browsers but is not supported on any Apple device. | Supported across all popular browsers and platforms. |\n| **ABR Support** | Yes | Yes | No, but Simulcast is used for dynamically adjusting video quality. |\n| **Latency** | 3–8 seconds | 3–8 seconds | Sub-second |\n\n---\n\n## Requirements for Low-Latency CMAF Delivery\n\nStable latency reduction with CMAF is only achieved if: the content in the CMAF segment is chunked-encoded; the encoder adjusts its manifest to accommodate chunked encoding; the encoder pushes content using HTTP 1.1 chunked encoding transfer; the CDN propagates content using HTTP chunked encoding at each step; the player times segment requests accurately; the player decodes the bitstream as it's received; and HTML5 players must use the Fetch API rather than XHR because Fetch supports reading the response body while data is still downloading.\n\n---\n\n## Practical Recommendation for 2026\n\nFor most businesses, using HLS with CMAF covers 99% of devices efficiently. CMAF (Common Media Application Format) is the cornerstone for LL-HLS. It allows fragmented MP4 (fMP4) segments compatible across HLS and DASH. Improved compatibility between Low-Latency HLS and low-latency CMAF for DASH should help curb complexity and improve CDN efficiency.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"0eb0143d-81b4-4dc9-89f3-7ed97be33e10","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:42:01.483Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ce8e4a41-99c6-4f3f-b226-eea8f1edd9ec"}
