{"parentUuid":"1266b5c0-8408-4aa1-af56-c83225f0b1e6","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"search_results_received","resultCount":10,"query":"Warner Bros Discovery Max platform BAMTech Discovery+ migration replatform architecture"},"toolUseID":"srvtoolu_016aTJke1oVsUiRXmXUyUPuX","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01Su7pmrJ6ejY2rBA5hpZsCC","uuid":"a415bdbf-60af-4013-8000-9fee9c0074ee","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:43:43.269Z"}
{"parentUuid":"69ad7250-5f67-4e90-ae2f-9c8c18db205e","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Su7pmrJ6ejY2rBA5hpZsCC","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Warner Bros Discovery Max platform BAMTech Discovery+ migration replatform architecture\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"From dbt Core to dbt Cloud: Warner Brothers Discovery | dbt Labs\",\"url\":\"https://www.getdbt.com/blog/warner-brothers-core-to-cloud\"},{\"title\":\"discovery+ Migrates Technology Infrastructure, Unlocking Expanded Suite of Product Features | Pressroom\",\"url\":\"https://press.wbd.com/na/media-release/discovery/discovery-migrates-technology-infrastructure-unlocking-expanded-suite-product\"},{\"title\":\"Keeping the stories flowing at Warner Bros. Discovery\",\"url\":\"https://thefrugalarchitect.com/architects/tom-leaman-warner-bros-discovery.html\"},{\"title\":\"Warner Bros. Discovery plans migration to a single tech stack | CIO Dive\",\"url\":\"https://www.ciodive.com/news/warner-bros-discovery-plus-technology-merger/629012/\"},{\"title\":\"discovery+ | Pressroom - Warner Bros. Discovery\",\"url\":\"https://press.wbd.com/us/brands/discovery\"},{\"title\":\"Big changes announced for discovery+ app, unlocking suite of new features for users\",\"url\":\"https://thestreamable.com/tech-upgrades-discovery-plus-app-max\"},{\"title\":\"Discovery+ is Getting New Features | Cord Cutters News\",\"url\":\"https://cordcuttersnews.com/discovery-is-getting-new-features/\"},{\"title\":\"TVN Warner Bros. Discovery - Pretius - case study\",\"url\":\"https://pretius.com/case-study/cloud-migration-warner-bros\"},{\"title\":\"The Netflix + Paramount Pursuit of Warner Bros. — Implications for SATCOM Infrastructure – SatNews\",\"url\":\"https://news.satnews.com/2025/12/12/the-netflix-paramount-pursuit-of-warner-bros-implications-for-satcom-infrastructure/\"},{\"title\":\"Warner Bros. Discovery promises Max will be a more personalized, technically improved streaming service | TechCrunch\",\"url\":\"https://techcrunch.com/2023/04/12/warner-bros-discovery-promises-max-will-be-a-more-personalized-technically-improved-streaming-service/\"}]\n\nHere are the key findings from the search results on Warner Bros. Discovery's Max platform, BAMTech, Discovery+ migration, and replatform architecture:\n\n## Warner Bros. Discovery: Max Platform & Discovery+ Migration\n\n### The Merger and Max Platform Launch\n\nIn 2022, Discovery and Warner Media merged to form Warner Brothers Discovery. Shortly after, the digital organization was tasked with launching a new streaming platform: Max. They had 9 months to build the platform.\n\nThe technical foundation was to be a \"best of both\" solution, evolving from both companies' historical streaming applications, with lower operating costs per subscriber.\n\nOn launch day, it was expected that all HBO Max users in the US would seamlessly migrate to the new system so that the HBO Max application could be immediately sunset. Five days post-launch, Max would be the sole streaming host of the series finale of HBO's hit show *Succession*.\n\n### Architecture and Performance Goals\n\nThe company promised updates to its core architecture to deliver \"faster, more reliable, and more efficient performance,\" including a new connected TV sign-in process and a more dependable downloads experience.\n\nApp start times, video start times, and general navigation response times were targeted to be 20 to 30% faster depending on the device.\n\n### Cost-Aware and Resilient Architecture\n\nThey built for cost-aware resilience, crafting a shared metadata schema to map and manage millions of resources, designing override tools to tame replica sprawl, and embedding cost accountability into architectural decisions.\n\nMax had a robust Architectural Decision Document (ADD) process reviewed by their principal engineering community. Initially focused on scalability, reliability, and integration, going into 2024 FinOps ensured that cost estimates were required as part of these documents.\n\n### Discovery+ Migration to Max Tech Stack (March 2025)\n\nWarner Bros. Discovery announced that discovery+ (U.S. and Canada) will migrate to a modernized in-house tech stack. The move brings discovery+ to the same technical platform and infrastructure that powers Max globally.\n\nThis update will seamlessly enable the same feature capabilities across various Warner Bros. Discovery streaming apps, establishing a unified code baseline while preserving the flexibility to customize brand elements—such as color, design, and more—to meet the unique needs of the company's app portfolio.\n\nCTO Avi Saxena called it \"a huge win, not only for our internal teams but also for our subscribers,\" noting that \"all of our streaming products will benefit from a richer feature set.\" The shift reflects over a year of engineering efforts to streamline operations and enhance user experience.\n\nThis migration underscores Warner Bros. Discovery's broader strategy to unify its streaming ecosystem. By bringing Discovery+ onto the same stack, the company aims to boost performance, reduce churn, and pave the way for future innovations.\n\n### Data Platform (Zion) Migration\n\nMoving from dbt Core to dbt Cloud and dbt Mesh enabled Warner Brothers Discovery to reduce costs while increasing the number of domain teams who could create and manage data products without engineering assistance, resulting in better stakeholder adoption, higher reliability, and less time spent babysitting data deployments.\n\nTheir internal data platform, called \"Zion,\" is a large and important platform. WBD aimed to minimize the impact to the existing platform while maximizing the effectiveness of the migration result, performing the migration in steps starting with a small POC isolated from the Zion ecosystem.\n\n### Technology Costs\n\nTechnology is the third-largest portion of the company's OpEx spending, and the company has been exploring cost-saving automation opportunities.\n\n---\n\n**Note:** The search results did not return specific details about **BAMTech's** role in the architecture. BAMTech (originally a Disney/MLB-backed streaming technology company) was historically associated with HBO Max's original tech stack before the Warner-Discovery merger, but the results focus primarily on the post-merger consolidation onto the unified Max platform and the subsequent discovery+ migration to that same stack.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"4a705273-820f-4ea3-a503-addaa604e6f7","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:44:12.392Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"69ad7250-5f67-4e90-ae2f-9c8c18db205e"}
