{"parentUuid":"0e9b57e9-ba86-42c4-8fde-2fd83e268b68","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014QtXD6sbnYFfLccUoE7Ffi","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"HBO Max BAMTech MLB Advanced Media streaming platform history\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"MLB Advanced Media - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLB_Advanced_Media\"},{\"title\":\"MLB Advanced Media's Long, Strange Trip - Boardroom\",\"url\":\"https://boardroom.tv/mlb-advanced-media-disney-bamtech/\"},{\"title\":\"BAMTECH Media | Disney Wiki | Fandom\",\"url\":\"https://disney.fandom.com/wiki/BAMTECH_Media\"},{\"title\":\"MLB Advanced Media: The future of America’s pastime - Technology and Operations Management\",\"url\":\"https://d3.harvard.edu/platform-rctom/submission/mlb-advanced-media-the-future-of-americas-pastime/\"},{\"title\":\"What Netflix Shareholders Should Know About BAMTech @themotleyfool #stocks $NFLX $DIS\",\"url\":\"https://www.fool.com/investing/2017/04/26/what-netflix-shareholders-should-know-about-bamtec.aspx\"},{\"title\":\"Disney Streaming - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BAMTech\"},{\"title\":\"For HBO Max, streaming technology is anything but a commodity - Fast Company\",\"url\":\"https://www.fastcompany.com/90373706/hbos-tech-is-prepping-att-for-the-streaming-wars\"},{\"title\":\"How Major League Baseball Built A Billion Dollar Tech Company: For Free?\",\"url\":\"https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/how-major-league-baseballs-team-owners-built-billion-adefope-esq-\"},{\"title\":\"BAMTech valued at $3.75 billion following Disney deal | TechCrunch\",\"url\":\"https://techcrunch.com/2017/08/08/bamtech-valued-at-3-75-billion-following-disney-deal/\"},{\"title\":\"Disney Streaming - Crunchbase Company Profile & Funding\",\"url\":\"https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/bamtech\"}]\n\nHere's a comprehensive overview of the history of HBO Max, BAMTech, and MLB Advanced Media's streaming platform:\n\n## MLB Advanced Media (MLBAM) — Origins\n\nMajor League Baseball Advanced Media was formed in 2000 by Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig to consolidate online rights and ticket sales for Major League Baseball teams. The owners were smart enough to realize there was a lot they didn't know about this new technology and its future, and each of the 30 teams agreed to pitch in $1 million per year for four years.\n\nIn August 2002, MLB streamed its first-ever game online. In 2003, BAM rolled out MLB.tv to the delight of over 100,000 baseball fans.\n\n## Expanding Beyond Baseball\n\nBAM's early entry into online streaming led to the development of advanced technology and established infrastructure that they leveraged to create a white label streaming service for other companies. It provided the backend infrastructure for WWE Network, WatchESPN, ESPN3, HBO Now, and PGA Tour Live.\n\nForbes went as far as calling the company \"the Biggest Media Company You've Never Heard Of.\"\n\n## The HBO Connection\n\nIn late 2014, HBO rather infamously abandoned plans to build the stand-alone HBO Now streaming service with its own tech. Instead, the company signed on with BAMTech—then called MLB Advanced Media—believing that it would deliver a more polished platform in time for HBO Now's launch the following spring. Otto Berkes, who had been building the in-house streaming tech as HBO's CTO since 2011, resigned when the company announced its decision.\n\nIn April 2015, BAMTech launched HBO Now. Eventually, HBO decided to bring its streaming technology in-house. Season 8 of Game of Thrones was the first in which HBO relied entirely on its own streaming tech, having cut ties with Disney-owned BAMTech a year earlier.\n\n## BAMTech Spin-Off (2015)\n\nBAMTech was established in 2015 as a spin-off of MLB Advanced Media—the digital media arm of Major League Baseball, focused on providing video on demand technology, particularly for over-the-top (OTT) media services. BAMTech was founded in February 2015, spinning out its streaming technology business into a separate company with outside investors. The formation of the company was approved by MLB Advanced Media's board of directors on August 13, 2015.\n\nOn August 4, 2015, the National Hockey League announced a six-year deal with MLBAM for it to take over its digital properties, including its websites, mobile apps, operations and distribution of its digital streaming service. The deal was worth $600 million over the life of the contract, and also granted the NHL an equity stake of up to 10% in BAMTech.\n\n## Disney's Acquisition\n\nIn August 2016, The Walt Disney Company acquired a 1/3 stake in the company for $1 billion, with an option to acquire a majority stake in the future.\n\nOn August 8, 2017, Disney announced that it would increase its ownership in the company to a 75% controlling stake for $1.58 billion. This valued BAMTech at $3.75 billion.\n\nWhat came next was a period of accelerated growth, with BAMTech reaching deals with FOX Sports, MLS, Riot Games, later launching BAMTech Europe and partnering with Eurosport.\n\n## Transition to Disney Streaming Services\n\nIn October 2018, it was reported that the company had been internally renamed Disney Streaming Services. Disney used the BAMTech infrastructure to launch its major streaming services:\n\n- With Mickey Mouse already owning ESPN, the company soon announced what became ESPN+—the OTT streaming service.\n- Disney+, the pure Disney companion to ESPN+, came shortly after, and as of July 2021, had 116 million users. Hulu's live TV offering came in 2017, hastening the formulation of the now-famous \"Disney bundle\" of Disney+, ESPN+, and Hulu.\n\nOn August 3, 2021, Disney announced the company was renamed as Disney Streaming. In the same month, it was reported that Disney was purchasing the NHL's 10% ownership stake in Disney Streaming Services for $350 million, giving Disney an 85% ownership stake.\n\nOn August 10, 2022, it was reported that Disney Streaming had a total of 221 million subscriptions from Disney+, Hulu and ESPN+ combined. At the time, this number surpassed Netflix, which reported having 220.7 million subscribers as of July 2022.\n\n---\n\nIn summary, what started as a baseball league's modest digital venture in 2000 grew into the streaming technology backbone behind some of the world's biggest entertainment platforms, including HBO Now and ultimately Disney's entire streaming ecosystem.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"7e6f7305-c1db-4864-8747-ce973ffda60b","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:44:47.709Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0e9b57e9-ba86-42c4-8fde-2fd83e268b68"}
