{"parentUuid":"70a32f27-1fe4-4a54-8f91-06713e09d2c0","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015588Bm4J4ApENQ9arDUMdr","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"\"How Warner Bros Discovery Is Maxing Out on Streaming\" Streaming Media Dan Rayburn\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"How Warner Bros. Discovery Is Maxing Out on Streaming\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamingmedia.com/Articles/Post/Blog/How-Warner-Bros.-Discovery-Is-Maxing-Out-on-Streaming-158852.aspx\"},{\"title\":\"Rayburn: Key takeaways from Warner Bros. Discovery earnings\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamtvinsider.com/video/rayburn-key-takeaways-warner-bros-discovery-earnings\"},{\"title\":\"Dan Rayburn on LinkedIn: Warner Bros. Discovery (WBD) Unveils \\\"Max\\\" Streaming Service | TD…\",\"url\":\"https://ug.linkedin.com/posts/danrayburn_warner-bros-discovery-wbd-unveils-max-activity-7052281808968650754-TYXK\"},{\"title\":\"Rayburn: Warner Bros. Discovery channels exit Fubo\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamtvinsider.com/video/rayburn-warner-bros-discovery-channels-exit-fubo\"},{\"title\":\"Dan Rayburn’s Streaming Insights & Intelligence: Fubo restructures debt, YES & MSG launch JV\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamtvinsider.com/video/dan-rayburns-streaming-insights-intelligence-fubo-restructures-yes-msg-launch-jv\"},{\"title\":\"Have Warner Bros. Discovery (WBD) Layoffs Paid Off? | The Watch List| Schwab Network\",\"url\":\"https://schwabnetwork.com/video/dan-rayburn-layoffs-hit-streaming-services-export-\"},{\"title\":\"ESPN, Fox, and Warner Bros. Discovery to Launch Joint Sports Streaming Service - Dan Rayburn - StreamingMediaBlog.com\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamingmediablog.com/2024/02/sports-jv.html\"},{\"title\":\"'Max'ing out on streaming: Warner Bros. Discovery to unveil new streaming service\",\"url\":\"https://www.cnbc.com/video/2023/04/11/maxing-out-on-streaming-warner-bros-discovery-to-unveil-new-streaming-service.html\"},{\"title\":\"Why Warner Bros. Discovery Has to Drop HBO From Streaming Service Name\",\"url\":\"https://www.thewrap.com/warner-bros-discovery-max-hbo-compete-disney-netflix/\"},{\"title\":\"Rayburn: Sports streaming news recap\",\"url\":\"https://www.streamtvinsider.com/video/rayburn-sports-streaming-news-recap\"}]\n\nHere are the search results for your query about \"How Warner Bros Discovery Is Maxing Out on Streaming\":\n\n## Key Findings\n\n### Streaming Media Article (May 2023)\nThe primary article was published on **Streaming Media** and is a contributed piece from Bloomberg Intelligence. Here are the key points:\n\n- Warner Bros. Discovery (WBD) took the spotlight in the streaming world with the long-anticipated launch of its new MAX service, merging the assets from HBO Max and Discovery+.\n\n- After weeks of discussion, the company's turnaround strategy for its streaming service was designed to accelerate profitability, mostly as an opportunity to reinvigorate subscriber growth.\n\n- Previously, the HBO brand and existing track record of high-quality content established a subscriber base of roughly 75 million. With over 20 million subscribers of Discovery+, WBD's new platform was already used by 97.6 million consumers in North America and Latin America.\n\n- WBD was reported to be targeting 130 million global streaming subscribers by 2025, making for roughly 11 million in yearly gains. The vast majority of these projected gains were expected to come from MAX's global expansion, first with the LATAM expansion in Q4 2023, followed by expansions into Europe, Asia, and other markets through 2024.\n\n### Dan Rayburn's Analysis & Commentary\n\nDan Rayburn, a prominent streaming media industry analyst, has extensively covered WBD's streaming strategy:\n\n- According to Rayburn, WBD highlighted how they need to not only grow subscribers but \"retain\" them and drive \"free cash flow.\" They know that getting to profitability has to be the number one goal and it is no longer about \"growing at all costs.\"\n\n- Rayburn mentioned how the combined service, from a content depth standpoint, would help combat churn, but noted that the company had never disclosed what churn looks like or how it is trending — and in fairness, none of the other streamers had disclosed these numbers either.\n\n- Rayburn stated: \"Wall Street only cares about profitability. Success is going to be defined by, can you organically grow a streaming service while at the same time increasing your [average revenue per user] and getting the service to profitability?\"\n\n- Q1 2023 marked the first time Warner Bros. Discovery's (WBD) streaming products brought in more money than they lost, as noted by Dan Rayburn.\n\n### Later Developments (2024)\n\n- WBD reported Q4 and full-year 2023 earnings, showing a yearly profit in their D2C business of $103 million and year-over-year DTC revenue growth of 3% in Q4. The company discussed expected DTC profitability for 2024, exclusive NBA negotiations, international expansion of Max, churn rates, and a new JV streaming service with Disney and FOX.\n\n- More recently, WBD announced plans to separate into Streaming & Studios (HBO) and Global Networks (TNT Sports, CNN, B/R, Discovery) by mid-2026, effectively undoing the $43 billion merger between WarnerMedia and Discovery in 2022.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"a6f23cdd-469b-4516-8324-a6273de46f5c","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:50:43.488Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"70a32f27-1fe4-4a54-8f91-06713e09d2c0"}
{"parentUuid":"a6f23cdd-469b-4516-8324-a6273de46f5c","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:WebSearch","command":"python3 ${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/hooks/posttooluse.py"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_015588Bm4J4ApENQ9arDUMdr","toolUseID":"toolu_015588Bm4J4ApENQ9arDUMdr","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:50:43.489Z","uuid":"0cd15f79-ced3-46c6-90c1-c9b71d5f0d2d"}
{"parentUuid":"0cd15f79-ced3-46c6-90c1-c9b71d5f0d2d","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/go/src/github.com/alexrybrown/streamline","sessionId":"6dec9a89-152c-46c3-bd75-eeb0d902cfd5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"a63db3607a31f78d8","slug":"linear-crafting-newell","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Q1sb1bjhQZZByc6kyZeNdp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have enough information to compile a comprehensive research report. Here is the full synthesis:\n\n---\n\n# Warner Bros. Discovery / Max: Streaming Technology Infrastructure Research\n\n## 1. CDN Strategy\n\n**Multi-CDN, four providers.** WBD CTO Avi Saxena confirmed in a May 2023 TechCrunch interview that Max uses four CDNs:\n- **Amazon CloudFront**\n- **Google Cloud CDN**\n- **Akamai**\n- **Fastly**\n\nSaxena stated: \"In any given month, we deliver more than an exabyte worth of content, which is 1,000 petabytes a month... And you cannot rely on just one CDN to do that.\" The multi-CDN approach provides resilience: \"So when something goes down, the product still continues to work.\"\n\nSources:\n- [Warner Bros. Discovery CTO and CPO explain how they made Max less buggy (TechCrunch, May 2023)](https://techcrunch.com/2023/05/05/warner-bros-discovery-cto-and-cpo-explain-how-they-made-max-less-buggy/)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Encoding/Transcoding Pipeline\n\n**Codecs:** Dual-codec approach:\n- **H.264 (AVC)** as the universal baseline (100% device support)\n- **HEVC (H.265)** for supported devices (over 75% of their device base, per Alex Zambelli, former VP of Streaming Platform Product Management at WBD)\n- **AV1** reportedly under evaluation but not confirmed as deployed\n\n**Per-title encoding:** No public details found on a WBD-specific per-title encoding implementation, though industry best practice strongly favors it.\n\n**Cloud transcoding infrastructure:**\n- **AWS Elemental MediaConvert** for VOD transcoding (in use since 2021)\n- **AWS Elemental MediaLive** for live content encoding\n- **AWS Elemental MediaPackage** for content packaging\n- **AWS Elemental MediaTailor** for server-side ad insertion (personalized addressable advertising)\n- **AWS Elemental MediaConnect** for live video transport\n\n**4K/HDR:** The Ultimate Ad-Free tier offers 4K UHD, HDR, Dolby Vision, and Dolby Atmos for select titles. 4K HDR was first added with Wonder Woman 1984 in late 2020.\n\n**Key personnel:** Alex Zambelli (now at Dolby, formerly VP Streaming Platform PM at WBD) has spoken publicly about WBD's HEVC experience at Streaming Connect 2023. He noted real-world CDN savings from HEVC are \"probably closer to 5 or 10%\" (vs. theoretical 20%+ bitrate reduction) because users on slower connections couldn't take advantage of higher-bitrate encodes anyway.\n\nSources:\n- [HEVC vs. H.264: Bandwidth and Cost Savings (Streaming Media)](https://www.streamingmedia.com/Articles/ReadArticle.aspx?ArticleID=161357)\n- [Warner Bros. Discovery reinvents linear television advertising with AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/warner-bros-discovery-reinvents-linear-television-advertising-with-aws/)\n- [WBD presents the Olympic Games supported by innovations built using AWS (AWS Case Study)](https://aws.amazon.com/solutions/case-studies/warner-bros-discovery-case-study/)\n- [Alex Zambelli's Streaming Media Blog - About](https://alexzambelli.com/blog/about/)\n\n---\n\n## 3. Origin/Storage Architecture\n\n**Publicly confirmed details are limited.** What is known:\n- AWS is the primary cloud provider; all applications run on AWS per CTO Avi Saxena\n- HBO Max historically used **Unified Streaming Platform v1.9.5** for origin/packaging (producing HLS manifests), upgraded to a newer version in 2021\n- The platform uses \"CMAF-based HLS/DASH packaging\" according to secondary sources\n- AWS S3 is the presumed storage layer (given full AWS stack), but WBD has not explicitly confirmed this in public talks\n- **Just-in-time (dynamic) packaging** is the industry standard approach used by Unified Streaming Origin, where a single source file is stored and output formats are generated on request\n\nWBD has not published detailed information about their origin architecture or segment storage strategy.\n\nSources:\n- [The Technology Behind HBO Max (FrugalTesting)](https://www.frugaltesting.com/blog/the-technology-behind-hbo-max-high-definition-streaming-at-global-scale)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Delivery Protocols\n\n**HLS and DASH via CMAF packaging.** Secondary sources describe Max as using \"CMAF-based HLS/DASH packaging.\" This aligns with the industry-standard approach of encoding once in CMAF (fMP4) and serving both HLS and DASH manifests.\n\n**LL-HLS:** No public confirmation of LL-HLS support on Max was found. Given Max's primary focus on VOD content (where low latency is irrelevant), LL-HLS would only matter for live sports/news. WBD has not publicly discussed their live latency targets.\n\nSources:\n- [The Technology Behind HBO Max (FrugalTesting)](https://www.frugaltesting.com/blog/the-technology-behind-hbo-max-high-definition-streaming-at-global-scale)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Backend Language/Tech Stack\n\n**Primarily Java/JVM-based.** Based on job postings, engineering blog content, and public references:\n\n| Category | Technologies |\n|---|---|\n| **Languages** | Java, Kotlin (JVM), Node.js, JavaScript |\n| **Frameworks** | Spring Boot, React, Angular |\n| **Infrastructure** | AWS (primary), Docker, Kubernetes (Amazon EKS) |\n| **Messaging** | Kafka, gRPC |\n| **Databases/Caching** | PostgreSQL, Redis, ElasticSearch, Caffeine |\n| **Monitoring/Observability** | Prometheus, Amazon Managed Prometheus, Amazon OpenSearch, CloudWatch, Kibana, PagerDuty, OpenTelemetry |\n| **Data Platform** | dbt Cloud/Mesh (internal platform called \"Zion\") |\n| **CI/CD** | GitHub Actions |\n| **Video Players** | Shaka Player (web), ExoPlayer (Android), AVPlayer (iOS) |\n| **DRM** | Widevine, PlayReady, FairPlay |\n| **AI/ML** | Google Cloud Vertex AI (captioning) |\n\n**Scale:** 400+ microservices and hundreds of datastores power the Max platform, running on Amazon EKS.\n\n**No public evidence of Go usage** in the core streaming stack was found. The backend appears predominantly Java/Spring Boot.\n\nSources:\n- [Keeping the stories flowing at Warner Bros. Discovery (The Frugal Architect)](https://thefrugalarchitect.com/architects/tom-leaman-warner-bros-discovery.html)\n- [Warner Bros. Discovery plans migration to a single tech stack (CIO Dive)](https://www.ciodive.com/news/warner-bros-discovery-plus-technology-merger/629012/)\n- [Unifying global streaming metrics for WBD on AWS (AWS Case Study)](https://aws.amazon.com/solutions/case-studies/warner-bros-discovery-aws-case-study/)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Architecture Heritage\n\n**Timeline of platform evolution:**\n\n1. **2014:** HBO abandons plans to build in-house streaming tech; signs with BAMTech (then MLB Advanced Media) for $148M+. CTO Otto Berkes resigns.\n2. **April 2015:** BAMTech launches HBO Now.\n3. **2017:** Disney acquires 75% of BAMTech for $1.58B (valued at $3.75B). HBO begins bringing streaming tech in-house.\n4. **2019:** Game of Thrones Season 8 is the first season on HBO's own streaming tech, having cut ties with Disney-owned BAMTech. The platform handled 4.7 million concurrent streams during the finale.\n5. **May 2020:** HBO Max launches on WarnerMedia's in-house platform.\n6. **August 2015:** Turner Broadcasting acquires iStreamPlanet for $148M for live streaming capabilities.\n7. **April 2022:** Discovery and WarnerMedia merge to form Warner Bros. Discovery.\n8. **2022-2023:** 12 months of planning to build the combined Max platform. The team evaluated \"best building blocks\" from both HBO Max and Discovery+ rather than choosing one stack wholesale. They chose iStreamPlanet's technology as the foundation for the live platform.\n9. **May 2023:** Max launches, replacing HBO Max. All US HBO Max users migrated seamlessly. Five days later, Max hosted the Succession series finale.\n10. **August 2023:** iStreamPlanet shut down as an LLC; its technology and most employees absorbed into WBD's internal streaming org.\n11. **March 2025:** Discovery+ (US/Canada) migrated to the Max tech stack, creating a unified codebase.\n12. **2025-2026:** Paramount+ and Max merger announced; combined platform expected to have ~200M subscribers. Architecture of the combined service not yet finalized. WBD also announced plans to split into two companies (Streaming & Studios vs. Global Networks) by mid-2026.\n\nSources:\n- [For HBO Max, streaming technology is anything but a commodity (Fast Company)](https://www.fastcompany.com/90373706/hbos-tech-is-prepping-att-for-the-streaming-wars)\n- [\"A Benefit and a Curse\": How HBO Max's Tech Team Is Building On HBO Now (Hollywood Reporter)](https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/general-news/a-benefit-a-curse-how-hbo-maxs-tech-team-is-building-hbo-now-1295521/)\n- [Warner Bros. Discovery Shutters iStreamPlanet (Deadline, Aug 2023)](https://deadline.com/2023/08/warner-bros-discovery-shuts-down-istreamplanet-1235519412/)\n- [iStreamPlanet - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IStreamPlanet)\n- [discovery+ Migrates Technology Infrastructure (WBD Press Release)](https://press.wbd.com/na/media-release/discovery/discovery-migrates-technology-infrastructure-unlocking-expanded-suite-product)\n- [Dan Rayburn Podcast: WBD's CTO and CPO Discuss Building Out Max](https://www.danrayburnpodcast.com/1893312/episodes/14079313-executive-interview-wbd-s-cto-and-cpo-discuss-building-out-max-for-live-news-sports-and-enhanced-discovery)\n\n---\n\n## 7. Live Streaming\n\n**Yes, Max streams live sports and news.** Key details:\n\n- **Sports (via B/R Sports on Max):** 1,700+ live games/events per year -- NBA, MLB, NHL, NCAA March Madness, NASCAR, Roland-Garros, and more.\n- **News:** CNN Max (live news stream within Max).\n- **Live platform foundation:** Based on iStreamPlanet technology (acquired by Turner in 2015, absorbed into WBD in 2023).\n- **Live encoding:** AWS Elemental MediaLive for live content.\n- **Olympics:** WBD streamed 1.3 billion minutes to 175 million viewers for Tokyo 2020 Olympics using AWS Elemental Media Services. Reduced on-site technical footprint for Beijing 2022 and Paris 2024 by leveraging cloud-based production. WBD holds Olympic broadcast rights in 49 European markets through Brisbane 2032.\n- **Audio analysis (Metronome):** AWS serverless system that analyzes audio spectrograms to detect key moments (referee whistles, crowd excitement) for automatic timeline markers in soccer matches.\n- **Addressable advertising:** AWS Elemental MediaTailor enables personalized ad insertion in live linear streams. Launched first in Italy for free-to-air linear TV.\n- **Sports tier:** WBD initially planned a separate sports add-on tier but reversed course in February 2025, keeping live sports within Standard and Premium tiers.\n\nSources:\n- [Warner Bros. Discovery Sports engages fans using scaled audio data analysis on AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/warner-bros-discovery-sports-engages-fans-using-scaled-audio-data-analysis-on-aws/)\n- [Warner Bros. Discovery presents the Olympic Games (AWS Case Study)](https://aws.amazon.com/solutions/case-studies/warner-bros-discovery-case-study/)\n- [Warner Bros. Discovery reinvents linear television advertising with AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/warner-bros-discovery-reinvents-linear-television-advertising-with-aws/)\n- [Warner Bros. Discovery Reverses Course on Plan to Launch Separate Sports Tier (SVG)](https://www.sportsvideo.org/2025/02/27/max-to-keep-live-sports-and-news-within-standard-and-premium-subscription-tiers-at-no-additional-cost-to-consumers/)\n\n---\n\n## 8. Key Engineering Blog Posts, Conference Talks, and Technical Publications (2023-2026)\n\n### Engineering Blog\n- **TECH @ WBD** (Medium-hosted): [wbdtechblog.com](https://wbdtechblog.com/) -- launched April 2025. Covers streaming, gaming, enterprise tech, product and design. Notable post: \"Engineering the Future of Streaming: How HBO Max Is Reinventing Merchandising with Automation, Vision, and Scale\" (August 2025).\n\n### Conference Talks / Interviews\n| Date | Event | Speakers | Topic |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nov 2022 | **AWS re:Invent** (COP201) | Tom Leaman (Dir. Observability & SRE, WBD), Marc Chene (AWS), Karthik Rengasamy (AWS) | How Discovery increased operational efficiency with AWS observability |\n| May 2023 | **TechCrunch interview** | Avi Saxena (CTO), Tyler Whitworth (CPO) | Building Max from the ground up, CDN strategy, performance goals |\n| 2023 | **Streaming Connect** | Alex Zambelli (VP Streaming PM, WBD) | HEVC deployment experience and real-world bandwidth savings |\n| Late 2023 | **Dan Rayburn Podcast** | Avi Saxena (CTO), Tyler Whitworth (CPO) | Video stack, live sports/news, latency, QoE, LATAM expansion |\n| Sep 2024 | **Google Cloud AI announcement** | Avi Saxena (CTO) | AI-powered captioning on Max using Vertex AI |\n| Apr 2025 | **NAB Streaming Summit** | Jenny Hua (WBD), Steven Woodard (WBD), Connie Huang (WBD) | Scalable cloud video stacks; live sports streaming workflows; kids' streaming architecture |\n| Sep 2025 | **IBC2025** | Avi Saxena (CTO), James Crossland (EVP Content Ops) | CTO Roundtable; MovieLabs 2030 Vision panel |\n\n### AWS Case Studies / Blog Posts\n- [Unifying global streaming metrics for WBD on AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/solutions/case-studies/warner-bros-discovery-aws-case-study/)\n- [WBD presents the Olympic Games using AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/solutions/case-studies/warner-bros-discovery-case-study/)\n- [WBD reinvents linear television advertising with AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/warner-bros-discovery-reinvents-linear-television-advertising-with-aws/)\n- [WBD Sports engages fans using scaled audio data analysis on AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/media/warner-bros-discovery-sports-engages-fans-using-scaled-audio-data-analysis-on-aws/)\n\n### Other\n- [Keeping the stories flowing at Warner Bros. Discovery (The Frugal Architect / Werner Vogels' site)](https://thefrugalarchitect.com/architects/tom-leaman-warner-bros-discovery.html) -- detailed interview with Tom Leaman, VP SRE, covering observability, FinOps, OSTAT, and the Max launch.\n- [From dbt Core to dbt Cloud: Warner Brothers Discovery (dbt Labs)](https://www.getdbt.com/blog/warner-brothers-core-to-cloud) -- data platform migration.\n\nSources:\n- [Building the Future of Media & Entertainment Technology (TECH @ WBD)](https://wbdtechblog.com/building-the-future-of-media-entertainment-technology-b92c75c90563)\n- [Engineering the Future of Streaming (TECH @ WBD)](https://wbdtechblog.com/engineering-the-future-of-streaming-how-hbo-max-is-reinventing-merchandising-with-automation-4a52fb203376)\n- [2025 NAB Streaming Summit Videos](https://nabstreamingsummit.com/videos/videos-2025-lasvegas/)\n- [IBC2025 announces speakers from WBD (Advanced Television)](https://www.advanced-television.com/2025/05/12/ibc2025-announces-speakers-from-nbcuniversal-itv-youtube-wbd/)\n- [AWS re:Invent 2022 COP201 PDF](https://d1.awsstatic.com/events/Summits/reinvent2022/COP201_How-Discovery-increased-operational-efficiency-with-AWS-observability.pdf)\n\n---\n\n## 9. Open Source Contributions\n\n**Minimal public open source footprint.** WBD's GitHub presence is modest:\n- [github.com/warnerbros](https://github.com/warnerbros) -- 8 repositories, mostly older projects (react-static, react-svg-morph, spacechop, docker-node-awscli, a fork of mux.js)\n- [github.com/wbdl](https://github.com/wbdl) -- Warner Bros. Digital Labs, limited public repos\n\nNo major streaming-infrastructure open source projects have been published. WBD does value open source participation culturally (mentioned in VP Engineering job descriptions), but they have not released anything comparable to Netflix's open source portfolio or Shaka Player (Google). Their engineering blog launched only in April 2025, so public technical contributions may increase over time.\n\nSources:\n- [Warner Bros. Entertainment Inc. (GitHub)](https://github.com/warnerbros)\n- [Warner Bros. Digital Labs (GitHub)](https://github.com/wbdl)\n\n---\n\n## 10. Scale\n\n| Metric | Value | Date |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Global subscribers** | ~128 million paid | Q1 2025 |\n| **Subscriber growth** | +5.3M in Q1 2025 alone | Q1 2025 |\n| **Projected subscribers** | 150M+ by end of 2026 | Guidance |\n| **Monthly content delivery** | 1+ exabyte (1,000 petabytes) | May 2023 |\n| **Microservices** | 400+ | 2023 |\n| **CDNs** | 4 (CloudFront, Google Cloud CDN, Akamai, Fastly) | May 2023 |\n| **Countries** | 77 countries and territories | 2025 |\n| **Languages** | 28 | 2024 |\n| **Live sports events/year** | 1,700+ | 2025 |\n| **GoT S8 concurrent streams** | 4.7 million | 2019 (HBO Now) |\n| **Olympics (Tokyo 2020)** | 1.3 billion minutes streamed, 175M viewers | 2021 |\n| **HotD S2 premiere** | Max's biggest streaming day ever | June 2024 |\n| **Annual DTC revenue** | $2.7 billion | 2024 |\n| **DTC profit** | $345M (Q-level), on track for $1.3B annual | 2025 |\n| **Ad-supported tier** | ~50% of domestic subscriber base | 2025 |\n| **Post-Paramount merger** | ~200M combined subscribers projected | TBD |\n\nSources:\n- [HBO Max Subscribers, Revenue & User Stats 2026 (Priori Data)](https://prioridata.com/data/hbo-max-statistics/)\n- [Max Revenue and Usage Statistics 2026 (Business of Apps)](https://www.businessofapps.com/data/hbo-max-statistics/)\n- [How the Streamers Stack Up (The Wrap, Nov 2025)](https://www.thewrap.com/netflix-disney-hbo-max-paramount-peacock-subscribers-revenue-profit-november-2025-update/)\n- [Streaming Platform Statistics 2026 (StreamRecorder)](https://streamrecorder.io/research/streaming-platform-statistics/)\n- [Paramount+ and HBO Max merger (~200M subscribers)](https://ppc.land/paramount-and-hbo-max-to-merge-into-one-streaming-giant-with-200m-subscribers/)\n\n---\n\n## Summary: What Makes WBD/Max Distinct\n\nCompared to Netflix (which publishes extensively about its tech), WBD is **moderately transparent** -- more so than Apple TV+ or Amazon Prime Video's streaming tech, but less than Netflix. The best technical information comes from:\n\n1. **AWS case studies and blog posts** (the most technically detailed public sources)\n2. **Avi Saxena's interviews** (TechCrunch, Dan Rayburn podcast -- high-level but specific on CDN, performance targets)\n3. **Tom Leaman's interview on The Frugal Architect** (detailed on observability, FinOps, microservices scale)\n4. **Conference talks at NAB and IBC** (2025 onward, with the TECH @ WBD blog launching April 2025)\n\nThe TECH @ WBD engineering blog is new (April 2025) and may become a richer source of technical details over time."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1457,"cache_read_input_tokens":41066,"output_tokens":5424,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1457},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CYpJS5cFVeHfepXEG4uCX","type":"assistant","uuid":"0f61453e-70b8-4ce6-852b-d221bf7ca8d2","timestamp":"2026-03-07T19:52:41.978Z"}
